\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 1913.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 The year when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 '86. 1886.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And the place where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Dewsbury. West Riding of Yorkshire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How long did you live at that house in Dewsbury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Twenty-seven years. Excepting the two years I was in college in London. I was in college '05 to '07.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When you left after twenty-seven years is that when you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 That was when we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 , yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I had seven brothers and four sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Can you give me the order and spacing between?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You don't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 want}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  their names do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You can give their names as well if you like,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 All right. John, died when he was
 eighteen months old. Born 1876. Ernest Clark born 1878. Lily born 1886. I'm sorry,1880. 1880. It's my bad figures, my dear, that's what - I knew it was wrong though when I compared it with the other. That's Lily, 1880. Edith, born 1882. Eva -1884. then I
 came next, '86 you see. Then my sister - Lizzie, 1888. Harold, 1890. Horace, 1892. I've gone wrong there. I gave you 1892 didn't I there for Horace? That's right. Alfred, 1}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 8}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 94. Charles John, '96 -1896. And Norman, 1898.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So that was quite a crowd then wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 It was a crowd.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How old was your father when you were born or what year was he born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well I make him forty-six, he was born in 1840.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 From Gloucestershire, from Tewksbury. Well, Ripple, a little village outside - Tewksbury in Gloucestershire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What was his occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well - really he started as a baker. And then he had his own business, quite a big business in Leigh - in Dewsbury. He was a corn factor, baker, grocer. He had a big whole
sale place all together. And did a lot of - of trading with the - farmers on the outskirts of Dewsbury, there's a lot of farming on the outskirts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Presumably it was quite a fair sized business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And he would employ people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You say he started off as a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15878306  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 baker}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And that was in - I think in - in Worcestershire, before he came and what brought him to the West Riding I do not know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did he ever do any casual or part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Do you remember him ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 He had his business all the time that you knew?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
His own business - that I knew him, yes. And for a very long time before - before I was born. He started in the business as manager and then he bought it. And built it up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How old would your mother be when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 She was born in 1857.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well - I think that she was born in - in London. But - she came to the West Riding of Yorkshire, came to Reed as a mat
ter of fact to live with - her - aunt, her father's sister. And she stayed with her until she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. No, not quite. No. The last three years, she wasn't really very happy with her and the last three years she went to live with a school mistress and h
er husband, I don't know whether her husband was a schoolmaster or not, I don't know. He was dead before I knew him but I knew her and she lived with them and really acted as housekeeper for them until she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was she acting as housekeeper or doing something in the house with the aunt?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did she work at all after her marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
No, excepting of course that she helped father but I mean she'd no definite work, it was - she - she'd go into the business if she were wanted f
or anything. How could she with that family? She spent - we always say she spent her time - with one tugging at her skirt and one in her arms and one on the way. Well of course it was. But they were very happy. It was a very happy family. And - you know, 
how you all - you all fit in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 With this very large family what sort of a house was it that you lived in, how many rooms were there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Do - is this all going down as I'm s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 eaking, because I'll have to count up. One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight. And a cellar. I don't know if you count the cellar.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you use it for something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes. It was storage cellar and for washing, things of that sort. And afterwards the business premises had a room that my father tuned into a laundry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 For the household?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 For the household. And - we always had plenty of help in the house }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 
you see}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  and the - the woman used to come and - all the washing was done away from the house in this laundry that father made.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Of these eight rooms, how many were downstairs and how many were bedrooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
There - there were two down - two downstairs, I don't know whether I've counted up properly or - and a sitting room upstairs. And the rest were bedrooms. There was one - two, three, four, five bedrooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were the house and the business attached?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Exactly, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So you had five bedrooms and a sitting room upstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. It was a three storey house. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 On the ground floor, was that the business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Kitchen. No, there was a kitchen, but the business was attached.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have a living room as well as a kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
No, it was a kitchen - a kitchen, living room. They were all very big rooms. We - in - in the sitting room which we used if we had visitors you know for - for
 meals, we could seat twenty people quite comfortably with - when the table was out. We seated twenty often. We started with twelve you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did anyone else besides your parents and brothers and - sisters live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. Oh yes, I'm sorry
. Of course they did. An old man who was a friend of my father's from before marriage. And he had been a Roman Catholic priest and he defected.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did he stay as a sort of lodger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Part of the family. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You say your mother had help in the house, did she have somebody living in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
We used to have a daily maid. At one period, when we were all tiny she had a maid living in but as we - the family got bigger there wasn't accommodation and she used to have somebody come in daily.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Can you remember the maid who lived in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
I can but if you're going to ask me her name I can't tell you that. Oh yes, I remember her very well. I can remember, her name was Sarah. And - she was - she was really grand. She - you know, in those days people worke
d and they didn't grumble about work and she'd work very had indeed but we all loved her. She was with us for a big number of years. And I think after she left, I don't think mother again had one living in. If she had I can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What was Sarah's duties, can you remember what part of the household work she undertook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh everything with mother's help and - and as we - as we girls grew up we took our part as well you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did she have set hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did she have any set hours as time off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes, she could have - she always had one full day a week off. And if she wanted any other time, I mean, she was treated as one of the family and she wanted to go out, she went out. She got her work done. Said she'd like to go out for
 a little while and she went, but in those days you know people didn't go out and about as they do now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When she did go out would your mother expect to know where she was going?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Or what time she'd be back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no. She had to be - to be in in reasonable time but - I mean, there was such; perfect trust that - there was no question -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was she quite a mature person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. Yes. I should say now, I don't - I don't answer for the voracity of this, but I should say she would
 be in her thirties or forties. She certainly wasn't a young girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So the question of whether your mother gave her moral guidance would hardly apply?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No. And we always had - it - it's really stupid to call her a nursemaid, and yet that's - t
hat's how she acted. She came in - and I can't remember now how often - to take the baby out. She - she'd take out the baby and - the - the next little one. There were two in a pram and she - she'd come so many hours a day. Now I can't tell you how often,
 I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You can't remember much about her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
No. Very little indeed, because as soon as - you notice that there was one boy and then five - two boys but one died in - in infancy, and then five girls. Now as the five girls grew up, we - we we
re nursemaids to the younger ones. Saturdays, and I - I remember it with nothing but absolute joy. I took out my three younger brothers. And we used to go up to Sameltown cricket field, take a lunch out with us, a packed lunch, and stay there for the day.
 Or we went up to Crownest Park which is the Dewsbury Park and again took a packed lunch and we stayed out for the day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did Sarah stay with you for a good long time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes, she was with us for -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You say she was a grand person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes, she was wonderful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You loved her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. She didn't do the washing, mother always had a woman in to do the washing. She did the housework.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did she do anything for you as children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well she'd help with dressing us in the morning and -
 if - before we were old enough to take over and dress the - the boys, you see, she would help with that. She were always taken up a cup of tea to bed in the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you feel that she was interested in you as a person?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes, very. As a m
atter of fact, not only interested in us as a person but interested in the way we behaved. Oh yes, she took full charge - when we were with her. Oh she was wonderful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 The nursemaid didn't make as much of an impact?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, she just came. She used to
 come in the - I think in the mornings but - I'm very vague about her. But I know she came and she - took the babes out. She had her dinner and she helped with the washing up and she went home. She really never became a part - a part of the family you kno
w.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When Sarah was living with you she lived completely as a member of the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes. Yes. The only thing was she didn't have meals with us but if she preferred to have meals on her own. No, she didn't - she didn't want to have meals with us. An
d - when the meal was laid, and it was a very big kitchen and we used to have meals in the kitchen excepting at the weekend when we carried them upstairs and - she would leave the meal all ready and then she'd say, well she'd so and so to do upstairs, and
 away she'd go upstairs and do so and so. And then - she'd have her dinner after us or before us, whichever suited her. She was free to do as she liked about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did she have a bedroom of her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. Yes. There was one - one room that was 
a very big room and mother had it partitioned so that she could have her own room, absolutely on her own. That was her domain. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You also had a maid who did not live in afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of relationship was she on with the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well - we always were on very friendly terms with out helps. We didn't regard them as - as helps, they were - they'd come to help us, that was all, I suppose they were helps in that respect but I mean there was no question of them being anything inferior.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you feel that the relationship was as close with one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh no. Oh no. Couldn't be as close as with Sarah. Sarah saw us all grow up - well, not all but - she was - I do know that she was there when I was about five or six but I can't tell you anything beyond that, I don't know when she left.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 The one who did not live in, did she cover the same range of duties as Sarah?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. Yes, she used to come by the - by the time - that had happened we were old enough to be up an
d get breakfast ready you see. And I think, if I remember rightly, that she used to come about half past eight. I seem to think that she came just before we were going off to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306  did}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 she stay all day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 She stayed all day. And - Sundays sh
e would have an early tea and go, some days she would stay on after tea to see the washing up done. She'd a free hand in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did she do anything for the children that you can remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No. The - we girls you see were up then and able to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did your various helps address your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Mrs White.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 Did they call the various members of the family by their Christian name?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Christian names, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did your mother and you address your helps?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well Sarah of course was Sarah and - one or two of the helps we had afterwards - sometimes they asked for their }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 Christian}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 name}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 to be used and if so it was used. But quite often it was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 woman who was doing this as extra work you see and they were called Mrs whatever their name was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 The washing was done at home until you had the laundry at the business?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes. It was - it was one of the business buildings. And - it was - really it wasn't used you know, it was a big empty room and my father had it made into 
a laundry, so - because with a big family like we had you see there was tremendous amount of washing. And - they could wash - there was a wash house there - built there and then there was this big room was used as a drying and ironing room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And the woman used to come one day a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well she came one day for washing, one day for ironing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did she do all of it or did your mother take a part of it as well?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no, we - as soon as we were old enough we did all our own ironing and - we woul
d have to take charge of one of the - for the boys you see. The ironing for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 There would be a lot wouldn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh tremendous. Terrifying. I hated washing all my life, I never had it to do when I was a girl because we had it done you see,
 but - seeing that washing, see those baskets now, piled this high. Ooh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did your mother or father mend or make any of the family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, but mother used to have a - in those days you could get sewing women and mother used to have a sewin
g woman. Now that was not a regular - I mean there was no - no coming every week. She used to come in - came when she was needed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was that for making or mending or for both?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 For both.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 About how often would you have new clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh we had a new outfit every year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 For any particular occasion?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Whitsuntide. We all turned out in new clothes for Whit Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did the same apply to shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Shoes my father was fussy about. He never would allow us to go and buy our own shoes
, even when we'd - were grown up. When we were quite big children I mean. he always went and he was very fussy about the - the size - the fit of them. And - if he saw any of us limping, at once our shoes were examined and if he thought we'd grown out of t
hem we went and got - got another pair. That was a - an absolute }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 fetish}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was there any handing down at all of clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 amongst}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  us girls there was. I think there must have been with the boys too but I do remember with the girls that - they were handed down from the - the best things became our second best.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 The clothes that were bought would always be new clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Oh yes. We had them made. At the dressmakers in those days you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well they bought - readymade suits was - were bought for them you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 Would}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  that be from a tailor outfitters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 General - general outfitters, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You didn't have a particular tailor they went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, not until they got to the - into lo
ng trousers and then of course they were always made by the tailor in - there were quite a number of tailors in the town.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you tend to patronize one particular source of supply for clothes or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 We always went to - a big firm, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 Eddlestone's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 ,
 they're still in going Dewsbury by the by, I don't think they do this sort of thing but they had a very big staff of - of work people and they made our dresses and coats. And - for any extra little knock about frock this - this sewing woman who came in m
ade those for us. The boys went - there again my mother was very fussy about - about things like that and the boys went to a very good class tailors to be measured and have things made.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Do you remember your father helping your mother with any of the jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no. Can't see my father doing anything in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Nothing at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Nothing whatsoever. He was a real intellectual. A very successful business man but how is beyond my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 understanding}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . I can see him now, sitting back }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 in his}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  chair at the end of the day and quoting poetry by the yard. He'd a wonderful memory. And - he read very widely and committed things to memory. He was a big public man as well, he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 served}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  on the - in those days it was the school board and he served on t
he school board and he was on the council and we were very interested in politics and he was a big Liberal politician.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would he have regarded doing anything in the house as completely beneath him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. It wasn't beneath him, he couldn't do it. He
 hadn't time, he'd too much else to do. And - he always saw to it, or mother saw to it, that he provided that she'd ample help in the house. Oh no, it was - he'd - he'd nothing at all of that about him. Not a bit. But - he just - it just never would have 
entered his head to do it. And why should he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about doing anything with the children?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh he used to take us out. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 We went out for long, long walks. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And - when I say long walks as we got to be in our teens twenty miles was an - an average wal
k. Oh yes. And was keenly interested in our education. He was very ambitious for us all. I shall never forget when my first baby was born, she was just a day old and he came to see me. And there she lay in her cot, screaming her head off, and my father sa
i
d, now Mary, whatever else you do, see that that child has the best education the country can give her. And I looked at this little screaming mite. I was always sorry he didn't live to see them grown up because this screaming little mite went to Somervill
e College, Oxford for a scholarship. So I knew - I knew he would have been thrilled. But he wasn't here to know it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What had his own educational background been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Self educated. He attended every class that he could, he came from a village you see
. His father was a - market gardener. Highly intelligent man but in those days people weren't educated. My father did go to school, to the village school, but - I really don't know what - what age he was when he left. But he was educating himself up to th
e day of his death practically speaking. Keen educationalist.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was he entirely self taught or with the help of any evening classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh he went - oh yes, it was all evening classes he went to. And in those days I forget what they were called. What 
were the classes that were held in those days? They weren't the ordinary evening classes. Mechanics Institute. That's right. Yes, well he went to Mechanics Institute. And - he - not satisfied with - with the education in which he was interested, the liter
a
ry education, he - thought it would be just as well to know how to do shorthand and typewriting and he learnt that as well. He was a wonderful man. Really very wonderful man he was. He was reading for the third time the book The Rise and Fall of the Roman
 Empire in his - the last year of his life. Yes, I own him - an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 enormous}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  amount to my father. Always encouraged us to read.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did he look after you much as children, if your mother was out for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, there was always somebody else there you 
see and my mother didn't go out very much. She wasn't - she was never fond of walking, I never remember her going for a walk. They went to church together and - she - worked in the - the bazaars and things of that sort you know that they held in the Sunda
y school, Sunday school or church bazaars.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What denomination?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 
We were brought up Congregationalists though my father had been, and my mother, they were both of them confirmed and baptised - baptised and confirmed in a Church of England but - fath
er got across - there all sorts of - of tales and what the truth is I do not know but I think that it was, he was a rabid teetotaler and I mean a rabid teetotaler. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
He wouldn't - when he was - the doctor thought he was dying and wanted him to have some bran
dy and he - did that - but not - I - I can't answer for the truth of this because I've heard one or two tables but I always think this is - fits my father best. You know how they always used - I don't know whether they always do now - but they always used
 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 fermented}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  wine in the communion and my father asked to be excused taking communion because he wouldn't have }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 fermented}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 wine and the vicar wouldn't allow him to go to communion. without taking it. So my father broke away. That's - that's the usual tale that'
s told but he was not very keen on us talking about it so whether it is the real truth I wouldn't - I wouldn't like to say.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 If it was a reason of that kind he would find it rather hurtful wouldn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes, he didn't talk about it because t
he whole family were Church of England people. They'd all been - brought up in the Church of England. And - when my father and mother were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  my mother was a second wife and when they were - when they were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  mother left the church and joined him
 at the Congregationalists you see. But I always felt both of them were really Church of England at heart. That was what I always felt. But it was a matter that was never discussed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You obviously took part in the work in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. Well all had our duties.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You had particular assigned tasks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh yes. Yes. Yes. On Friday evening I - cleaned all the knives, the forks and the spoons and the knives were cleaned on one of those old cleaning boards. Covered with leather, on which you s
prinkle bathbrick and you've to - and my mother was a very proud housewife and when we'd finished they were all examined and - if there was a mark on any of them well you did it over again, that was all. That was all there was to it. And we had - we had t
o
 clean our own shoes and the - in those days there was always Sunday - Sunday clothes and weekday clothes. The Sunday clothes had to be brushed and put away on Monday and the Sunday shoes had to be cleaned and put away on Monday night. But for the weekday
 shoes, the errand boy used to do all those. That was his job. Yes, he - he did - he came on duty at eight and cleaned the shoes for us children to go to school. But the best shoes weren't trusted to him you see, we had the care of those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Your brothers and sisters also had their jobs to do in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes. Yes. Except my eldest brother who from the very outset - that was Ernest, not John. John I never knew you see. From the very outset was - I - I hesitate to say this because it sounds mean and 
I don't feel mean about it, but he really was the darling. And he was waited on hand and foot. But - all the rest, and particularly the girls, that was a strange thing you know how it was the girls who came in for the duties in our young days. The boys ar
e waited on. My brothers never cleaned shoes. We did the shoes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did they do any things like chopping wood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
No, again they - that was done by the men on the - in the business. They kept us supplied with the wood and fetched up the coal and things of that sort. We - we hadn't any of those things to do among us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about the making of the fire and keeping the fire going and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well that was done whoever happened to be there. The lighting of the fire was by the Mr Clark, my father's 
friend, who was with him before. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 Now he was up five o'clock in the morning always, you could tell the time by hearing him go downstairs. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And - he always lighted the fire. He didn't take out ashes or anything of that sort you know, that was done afterwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Whose job was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
The - the - help used to do it when she came. And - he sang through the whole of the Mass in Latin every morning, I can hear him now if I close my eyes, seeing that mass in Latin. He was a wonderful man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Have you any idea how it was he came to leave the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 Well again it's difficult because again so many, many tales were told that I prefer not to offer one. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. But that he was hounded by the Catholics there is no doubt whatsoever. I myself was in the house one
 Sunday afternoon, again some things rather stand out in mind, I should be in my teens, how much in my teens I do not know and he came in, in a terrific rush and slammed the door to, it was a very big door, slammed it to, slipped the bolt, locked the door
,
 got hold of me and pushed me behind him and he was such a gentleman I - I was simply staggered. And - within a few minutes that door was broken down and a man came in. And it was the - we always - we were always told, he always told, he always told us th
a
t he carried a pistol but I never believed it until I saw it, his pistol was out at the man. It was an awful experience. And that was a Roman Catholic who had followed him and - I don't know what would have happened, he would have certainly been attacked 
i
f he hadn't got into the house before the man overtook him. But that you see is an instance that I myself saw. Another time I was alone in the house, no I wasn't, my sister was with me, my youngest sister and the baby boy, just toddling around. And a knoc
k
 came on the door. I went to the door and - were two men there, very rough looking fellows and - we want to see - he was always called Paddy Clark by the people outside - we want to see Paddy Clark. I said, you mean Mr Clark? And he sees nobody here. He h
a
d a room by the by in the town. If you want to see him you must go, and I told them where, if you want to - and they pushed past me and came in and they - there were armchairs in the kitchen and they sat one each side of the fireplace and they said, and w
e
're stopping here Miss until he comes, we're going to see him. Well I had a - a brainwave, it was nothing else, I said, to the little toddler, go and call - I forget the name of the dog. And this little one you see couldn't be in any scheme because he was
 too }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 tiny}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. And went up - upstairs calling the dog and I said, and when that dog comes - I'm not responsible. And hearing the little chap calling for this dog the men evidently took fright and they got to the door and they had it open and I just motioned to 
my sister and we got behind and pushed the door and they fell out into the road.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And how old would you be at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh I should be about fifteen or sixteen. But - he led a harassed life. And he was a wonderful man. He was a - he was a - a w
onderful - he was an Irishman remember, he was a wonderful speaker, he could hold an audience and in those days it was the days of the open air meetings, a wagon would be brought into the market place, I've seen Dewsbury market place }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 crowded}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  and he could always hold a crowd. Again it was mostly - it was either temperament or education that he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 spoke}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 on. And one Sunday afternoon he was speaking, there's this huge crowd there, and the man came just in front of the - of the - wagon and - kept on interrupting so
 at last Mr Clark said, now what is the matter, what is it you want? Well Paddy, I hear that you call - you said I wasn't right in me head. So he said, oh no }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 Tommy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 , I never said any such thing. He said, what did you say? He said, I said, you were non }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 compos}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 mentis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. Oh well now, he says, if that's what he said that's all right, I don't mind. And you know the crowd howled. But he always was right on the dot. He was a wonderful speaker. He - he was on the - on the - council. And he was a big educationalist. An
d he was - he - worked hard for a school to be built in one area where a school was very much needed. And he used to lay the foundation stone. Well he hated anything of that sort. And he said, no. However they insisted. And they day came for laying the fo
undation stone and the whole assembly and mayor and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 chain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 and all the rest of it were there you know and - they looked round and they said, where's Mr Clark - he's to lay the - the head builder came up, he said, that stone was laid yesterday, Mr Clark came 
yesterday and laid it and I was to tell you that he - he preferred to do it on his own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You told me about the girls having to do things for the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was there any question of the younger children helping the older ones or the older ones helping the younger ones?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Excepting with their lessons. They did with their lessons. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were you expected to go to bed at a particular time as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, but it was not very early. As - up to I should say ten, we were
 early birds. But afterwards when we got to grammar school and had homework then mother and father were - were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 sensible}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. We were expected to do our homework and I mean we took it as matter of course and we settled down and did it. Well then they thought we
 were justified in having a bit of leisure. And - our leisure either would be playing games together, it depended if you got - if you found enough who were eager to do so, or reading. We were always encouraged to read. Nobody ever grumbled however long we
 
spent reading. I remember my father on more than one occasion coming up in the early hours of the morning and finding me - sitting reading, hadn't gone to bed. And - all he said, was, ah come lassie, I think you've done - read enough now, put that away an
d get to bed. And I'd say, yes, I know why you're doing that father. You've got to the end of your chapter haven't you? 'Cos he hadn't got to bed either. But I was up in my bedroom and he was downstairs in the sitting room reading you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did your mother or anyone else put you to bed as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
As a small child Sarah put us to bed. But after that the older ones, the older you see, with - we were girls, five of us, and we put the little ones to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 About how old would you be when you started putting yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Myself? Oh I should think about six.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You had five bedrooms altogether, what were the sleeping arrangements?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 In the girls bedroom we had two - double beds and the room easily took them and left plenty of room to m
ove about, they were as I say, big and two girls slept together. Now what I haven't told you is that my sister Eva, the one next older than I died when she was five. That left four girls you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And you had one bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. And - Mr Clark had 
the little bedroom. And - there were - one other room, there were two beds again in, double beds and two boys slept in each. And then the other room was one double bed and two boys slept there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7734968\charrsid15878306 And there was usually a baby you see and that was in the cot in mother's bedroom.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have a bathroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, we hadn't. But we had a big slipper bath.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was that a fixture?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No, it was moveable. And of course we had to draw all the water and fill the bath. In the winter time we had the bath 
- we had baths in front of the fire and in the summer time we had a very big landing and we had the bath on the landing and carried the water up two flights of steps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 That would be an effort wouldn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, but you know it wasn't an effort. We
 did these things automatic. We had water - on all the three floors. But - not hot water. The hot water was in the kitchen and it all had to be carried up in - we had big cans - water cans that we carried.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How far would }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  hot water stretch with a family as large as this having baths?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh it went on almost interminably. It was an old fashioned Yorkshire range I think they called them, you know, with a fire in the middle and the oven here and the boiler there and always - spring, summer, autumn an
d winter there were big fires and there was a tap to draw the water off, there was a tap at the side here to fill the - the - boiler and then a tap to draw it off you see so that there was no lifting of water for that. And there was always a good supply o
f water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 About how often did people have baths?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Once a week dear. My father, who was again - one of these outstanding men - he had a cold bath pretty well every morning. But we were never brought up to cold baths. We didn't have cold baths until 
we got into - late teens and then we followed fathers - you see and had a cold bath. And of course that could be filled from - the level of our bedroom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was it a case of certain people having their bath on a particular night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh we - oh yes, we - we bath night. Yes. We had our own night - bath night, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Having clean clothes to put on would be tied in with the bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 With the bath.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 The cooking would be done on the Yorkshire range?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. And we had a gas oven as well. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was it your mother who did any of the cooking or was it Sarah?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
well they shared. Until we got old enough to do it. And then of course we could cook breakfast but then we were out during the day you see. So mother and - the - by that time, by 
the time we got out Sarah had gone. I rather thing she'd died, I think - I don't mean she died at our house but I rather think that she left us because of illness but I - I wouldn't like to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 About what time did you have breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well - my father had - my father my eldest brother Ernest had theirs at seven. And the rest of us, quarter to eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of a meal was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh I can tell you that easily. One morning we had a basin of bread and milk. And toast or bread and butter as we 
liked and - marmalade and - and syrup, golden syrup you know, and honey. And the next day it was porridge with the same to follow. Very seldom did we have bacon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about on Sunday did you have anything special on a Sunday or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, Sun - Su
nday, after all the business hours Sunday's the day - day to relax. And - if you wanted to cook a breakfast for yourself well you could. But we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 seldom}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  did. Father by the by - father and my brother always had a cooked breakfast. But they had theirs at seven
 and one of us girls got up and did that you see. And served it, father as a busy business man wanted quite - he wanted quiet, he wanted to read his newspaper, he wanted his breakfast quietly and Ernest had to go out, he went to, in those days - I don't k
n
ow whether there was a residential but he went to Leeds university and he went - had his train to catch, I forget now, but it was before eight and so he had his breakfast with father and they always had a cooked breakfast. And mother usually, mother alway
s had hers in bed. Sarah took it until we were old enough, and then one of us took it and she had a boiled egg. We could have boiled eggs if we liked but - we were too lazy to boil them. For ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have tea to drink or something else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Tea or cocoa. We weren't encouraged to have tea - cocoa. Was the - the drink.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was that for the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 For the children. Oh no, father always had tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about the other meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Very good meals were served always. I never remember
 a single day when we didn't have - excepting in the middle of summer - when we struck against hot meals and had a salad meal. But - you know, the old fashioned Yorkshire - two veg and - and meat of some sort. The roast was cooked on Sunday, we had it col
d on Monday, we had it hashed as a - or done as a shepherds pie on Tuesday. Then we started again with another roast on Wednesday. The same thing went. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 
And - tea was - a salad, tomatoes, things of that kind. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And always jam. Always jam and always syrup. I remember those well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have a supper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well if you had supper you - you got what you wanted, a glass of milk and a biscuit or in those days, with such big roasts as we had, there was always plenty of good dripping and we were always very fon
d of dripping. And - a glass of milk, hot if you wanted it, cold, but you got that yourself, there was no laid supper. And - bread and dripping I loved, we all loved it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of times did you have the meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well I've told you breakfast. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 Lu
nch of course had to be - it was on the table from soon after twelve, those of us who were at school came home until two o'clock, depending on father or - father did a good deal of traveling in connecting with the business and depending upon what time he 
got in you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 But - it was always on the - more than an hour and a half.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And tea time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Tea time would be about five, when we got back from school. and that would drag on, my brother didn't get in from Leeds until between six and seven and it - 
he had his alone when he got in. And he always had a cooked meal in the evening, of course he had his midday meal in Leeds but I really don't know what he had, I've forgotten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were you encouraged to have cocoa at these other meals as children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 W
e were encouraged to have it but we could have tea. We were - they were really - I - I think my mother and father were very advanced in their ideas from that - for that age because there wasn't that hard and fast rule. The only hard and fast rule I do rem
e
mber was that until we were quite - oh - in our twenties, nobody was allowed out - to be out after ten o'clock at night. And - we were all - not all of us but some of us, very fond of dancing and of course it was all private dancing in those days you know
,
 no public dancing you see and - he had to be - come straight home and father was always waiting for us, he never would go to bed until we were all in. So it meant you didn't dance - because you knew he - he who had to be up in good time in the morning wa
s waiting for you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did your mother or Sarah bake the bread?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh no, because you see it was a - the shop was a baker's shop and it was all done down at the bakehouse. Yes. No, there was no baking done. Sometimes, mother who was a very good baker, 
sometimes for a treat she would bake some bread. And occasionally make a cake but she always said she couldn't make cakes like the bakers did. The three or four bakers and - we had the pick you see of anything that was going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about making jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. Oh - I've picked stones and stones of strawberries, raspberries, plums and mother used to bottle fruit as well, but she }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 did}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  all - all that with - we did the preparation.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did she preserve any vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
I don't remember her making any. Those - came from the business. They weren't encouraged, we - mother didn't think they were good for children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 As a teetotal household there wouldn't be any wine made?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no. There was none allowed in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Or home brewing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
And nobody - and nobody was allowed to smoke in our house, not even visitors. My father was terribly strict about that. Any visitors come in they were told it was a - a teetotal, non-smoking home. Father - he - I - I th
ink it was too bad there, because he didn't allow his visitors to smoke. One thing that - that - mother made tremendous amount of was raspberry vinegar. Have you heard of it. She made a tremendous amount of that. And it was a very nice drink. Really refre
shing. That she always made.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh, the doctor was never out of the house. With a - with a family like that. We - father always used to laugh, he'd say - big doctor's bill evidently this quarter, Doctor hasn't sent one in. You 
see, we supplied, he had horses, it was before the days of motor cars and father supplied all the corn for the doctor's horses and of course the family shopped at our shop as well and the doctor never sent a bill in if his bill - his quarterly bill - what
 we owed him, exceeded what he owed us.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you grow your own vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
We'd no garden. But I had a grandfather, my mother's father, he didn't live with us, he lived in Dewsbury, and he had a big garden. And - just, you know, as a hobby, and he used to bring lots of fresh - of fresh vegetables and fruit for us from }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 the garden}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . And one of the happiest memories I have is of being }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 
wheeled}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  in his wheelbarrow, oh - yes, about of a mile from my home up to his garden and - we played round wi
th him in the garden you see only he said we didn't go to play we went to work. And one of the things we were set to do was to pick up worms. It really was just to keep us busy you see, whilst he got on with his work. He - he had been a Naval Engineer and
 had traveled the world but his health failed when he was in his, I think, late fifties, early sixties and - he was - interested in gardening and he took this big garden and worked with it as long as he lived.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did that provide for all your fruit and vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh no. Oh no, no, no. And we had a gallon of milk left every day. But milk in those days you know was not what is it - three ha'pence a pint, something of that I'm not sure what the price was but it was very very cheap. But we had a gallon 
left every day. And - for the bakehouse they used to have skimmed milk there for making the bread - they made milk bread you see - for making the bread and if we ran short for puddings or anything we simply went down and helped ourselves there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Presumably you would have to buy some fruit and vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh yes. Yes. A lot. Father used to bring it back - he traveled as I told you - he had a horse and trap that he traveled in and he used to bring vegetables back from the country. In big quantities.
 And the farmers who came to collect their feeding cake and corn and so forth from the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 warehouse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 they would bring fresh vegetables and fruit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you ever have any tinned or dried fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no, oh }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 no}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . The only dried fruit we had was - dried apricots and prunes. Nothing else, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you keep any livestock for the family, hens, pigs, goats or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 The boys had rabbits. And of course there were horses for the business and we had our own pony for - for us to d
rive about. And we always had cats. And a dog. A collie dog.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Who looked after the pony?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
The men. There was a stableman - who had charge of the - of the horses. We were taught to groom the ponies. And - it wasn't made a task for us so we loved go
ing to do it. It wasn't a case of you have to do it, but we would go to Harry the - the stable man and say, can we - can we groom Daisy today. - And he'd say, well yes, if you're really careful you can, but mind you don't scratch her with that comb. Well 
then you see it was a privilege, it wasn't a duty.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were the cats and dog anybody's particular pet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 The cats were the family. The dog was my brother's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have any of your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I myself? No, the only one I was interested in was th
e pony. I don't like cats. And - we lived right away in the heart of the town and taking a dog out wasn't a lot of fun you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you ever know any poachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Any? Well - we did because my father being a country boy believed in the country for
 the children and the horses were put out in turn to - to grass at the farm and we always said, and we were put out as well because we went for the summer onto a farm and went to the little village school and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Where was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 At Midgley. It's a
 - oh I don't know, between Ossett and - and Wakefield, but in those days it was quite open country. I - I want to go but - I can't go unless the car's available you see and my daughter's a busy girl, she hasn't much time. But I expect I'll be very disapp
o
inted if I go. But the horses went in - in turn, two at a time, onto the farm and we used to go and stay there and we had three miles to walk to the - come to the - and - oh there'd be about between ten and twenty children in the school and we'd a very ha
p
py time there, we loved it. And that was just the - the summer months that we went and I really don't know how long it was. Whether we went for two or three months I don't know. - And - there of course we had a - a lovely time. They'd a big orchard and we
 
were allowed to help ourselves. We were allowed to climb the trees, the farmer's - farmer and his wife had - I think it was three boys and two girls. But anyway we were all much about the - an age you know. And they had a pond and we were allowed to make 
a
 raft and if we - if we fell in well we fell in that was all, we got out again. It wasn't deep enough - but the - the thing that I - I remember most about that was going out mushrooming. We used to go out early morning to gather mushrooms. And in those da
y
s you know girls and boys wore pinafores and my sister, the one next to me, we still tease her although she's old woman of turned eighty, she used to go with the farmer's son and he gathered the mushroom and she'd say, put it in me pinny, put it in me pin
n
y, and she'd hold her pinafore you see while - that was - those were very happy days. And then we went into the fields singing - turnips. Now don't ask me what that is, I did - I did it for hours but I - I don't know, I think it was pulling out the - ther
e
 were too many or something, we were told. And we were always there at harvest time and the joy there was riding on the top of the hay - coming back from the field to the - to the barn. And - the - farmer's men, they were awfully good to us, we must have 
been an awful nuisance to them but they were good to us. We used to go milking time morning and evening with our cup and they milked - the milk straight into the cup from the udder you see, and we drank it warm. And - I would say no milk's ever tasted as 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 good}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 as that. People nowadays horrified at the thought of it but we loved it. And going into the dairy and seeing them make the butter. And - we'd turn the handle of the churn if we were allowed to you see. And the great }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 panicans}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  of milk set out on the floor
, stone floor and to go and watch the farmer's wife skim it to make the milk, take the cream off. There's never been cream like that. We could have as much cream as we liked.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did this sort of constitute your holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. Though we went aw
ay to the seaside every year. When we were very young Skegness was our - place but of course it was not a Skegness like today, very quiet little place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you all go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well - we had to go - all the children went - and mother. And then the older 
end came home and father joined mother. We had to take it in - like that - to arrange - arrange it like that you see. Mother and father couldn't be away long together but it always worked like - like that, that father came and joined the part of the time.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of things did you do there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Sand - making sandcastles. And we always made seat for mother and father, sand seat and we made really wonderful ones because we've managed to put back and - and arms to them and they could - they could sit 
on them. And - in those days they hired ponies and traps and you could hire them for the day and - so many went in the pony and trap, it was governess kind, and then the rest of us had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 
donkeys}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 And father used to hire them for the day, we took picnic meal with us and went - as long as - we wanted to go. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
I remember so well blackberrying. The blackberries were very very good there, we used to pick the blackberries and bring them home for the - landlady to cook for us. We took the house, you see, we needed a f
ull house with a family like that and we went to the same house, it was right on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 front,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 I can see it now, we used to - put on our swimming costumes in the - oh no, no that was later. No when we were children that wasn't done. Went - went across from th
e house with our towels and things and it was the days of the - bathing lines that were drawn out by a horse you know. And my father was great on bathing. He never could swim but he was great on bathing. We were all taught to swim. And - I - our introduct
i
on to the sea was always with a - with father and he helped us out of the bathing van and we had to have two of course, one for the girls and for the boys, the girls and boys didn't mix in those days and father took us by the hand and ducked us into the w
ater. That was our introduction - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 you must}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  get your hair wet before - you start playing about. And we used to go for a }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 bath}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 every day. Oh they were happy days. All simple pleasures you know. And I always think it's a pity that the wireless and television ha
ve taken the place of the - the - of the family piano. We - we were always encouraged to have friends and it was a - a get-together and get round and somebody played and the rest were sang. Whether we sang in tune or not was nobody's business, we enjoyed 
it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have any other instruments as well as a piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. A violin. And - what was the other one? Can't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Who were the players?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 We were all taught to play. We all had - it was a - it was the done thing in those days you 
know to have piano lessons and we could all of us play sufficiently to play simple tunes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about the violin?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 My brothers learnt the violin. Two of them. the eldest brothers became - he was very musical and he became quite a good }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 violinist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . W
e all went to cricket matches. And we were keen supporters of - of the Yorkshire cricket team. One of my brothers played for the Yorkshire second and we were all very proud. Oh yes, they were very - very happy childhood days, I', - I'm sorry for the child
ren of the present day 'cos we made our own pleasures. And I'm sure we enjoyed it better than the more sophisticated way the - the youngsters spend their time nowadays, I think so anyway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were there any other sorts of things that you did in the leisure and pleasure line?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well walking was a big thing. We did an enormous amount of walking. And - we played the usual games at school you know, hockey and - tennis, so forth, at the school. And - we took part in the Sunday school plays, we were great on that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I suppose you'd be regular attenders wouldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh my dear. We went - we went to Sunday school at quarter past nine, morning service half past ten, afternoon Sunday school quarter past two and evening service half past six. And sometime
s there was an after service, revival meeting. But in that - in that connection, a very very vivid memory is of Mr Anstew who was the minister who ran a mission for a period, now I do not know how long it lasted but I know I took part in it and it was cal
l
ed the Midnight Mission. And in those days drinking was very bad. And we went - we went through the town in a - you know, two by two - what's the word I want - a procession and Mr Anstey headed it and senior minister - senior teachers were place at variou
s
 int - and those of us who were Sunday school scholars who took part, mind we were in our late teens then, and we sang hymns at the public houses at - near closing time and at closing time. And then Mr Anstey invited the down and outs or anybody else to c
ome to the church for service and he held a service there. It was a revival, the sort of thing that fortunately is - dead now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of response did he get?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Very wonderful. We had the - it's a big church, it's still there - the - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 Ebenezer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  chapel and we'd have it full. Sometimes you didn't go into the chapel. Really, if the truth were told, that was when there were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 too}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  many drunks there and you didn't want them in the - in the chapel. They could go in the school and somebody could clean up
 afterwards you see, but not in the chapel. And - well, he talked to him and the older ones - we were not allowed to mix with them at all, we were simply there to see what was happening and to sing the hymns. And - he talked to them and prayed with them a
n
d there was the penitents form you know, in which they came forward and - we took it all very seriously and - until we really started to see through it. I think what set that going was one night - see we were there until midnight and one night a very - no
ted reprobate was going up to the confession and somebody behind him tapped him on the shoulder and he said, hey Johnnie, what do you mean? You know quite well you're not converted. He said, sssssh. Sssssh. Don't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 you tell}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  anybody. I never show when I get th
ere and I can pray like hell. But there is no doubt about it that it did - I think - quite a fair amount of good. But - I'm very doubtful about those revival meetings as I got older. I fully believed in that one, that Midnight Mission. I was sure we were 
doing a good job of work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was there temperance club attached to the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 This would take the place of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 There was a - a - a very strong temperance movement in the town and they had their temperance hall and they had all their 
Sunday afternoon and evening services. There was a very strong one. My father was president for quite a long time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Going back to mealtimes, what was the atmosphere at the table, did you all sit down together?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 As many as could. I mean - you see,
 we never knew where my father would be. And my eldest brother was - away a good deal, 'cos he was away }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 every}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 day from - before eight in the morning until turned six in the evening, so they had different meal times. but }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 rest of us had meals together. A
nd - there was no repression. How they - how they managed to keep us fairly quiet because we were never made to be quiet. If anybody got obstreperous of course mother's quiet voice would come in and say, none of that. And that was quite sufficient.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 But you were allowed to talk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to have a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, we were pretty well kept to - what was prepared was - was - we were expected to eat tho
ugh again mother quickly found out those who had - any special - thing that was distasteful, and she never insisted upon you having that. Only, nothing was substituted. The family were very fond of - of liver and - kidney. And that was often dinner and I 
c
an't - to this day I can't bear the smell of it, never mind the taste. And I couldn't eat it, well I wasn't made to. Mother realized that I just couldn't but there wasn't anything substituted. If I didn't have that, well, that was that, I didn't have it, 
that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 Apart from particular things which was known you didn't like, what was your mother's attitude if you left food on your plate?}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 There were always cats and dogs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Could you ask for second helpings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. As many as you liked. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
If there was something on the table that you wanted, the salt or something like that, could you ask for it or did you have to wait for it to be passed round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no, you just asked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would you be expected to hold your knife and fork in a particular way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
We were very strictly brought up. Mother was very very meticulous about our eating habits and the holding of - of our - tools. Very. And about the setting of the table. We usually set the table even if we were not there to help
 with the cooking and she used to do this, she'd run her hand round the edge and if any - if any knife or fork extended it was given a gentle push in, everything must just be - she was very meticulous like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 As a smallish child - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 would}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  you bring a book or toys to the table at meal times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well usually we - all left pretty much at the same time. But I don't remember there being any ruling about it, I think it just - we - we finished and 
we - pretty well all together and we all came away together. And then always, even when we had a maid, those who were old enough had to take their part in clearing the table and putting things away. That - as long as ever I can remember we did that. And a
s we got older we did the washing up as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You didn't have to ask permission to leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
No. No, unless on Sunday - sometimes you know with a big family like that to serve the - the meals were always dished up and brought on the table 
in tureens and so forth and by the time you'd finished being served sometimes it was time to go for Sunday school and then you would ask, you were always excused for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you always have the same places at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. Yes, we had our own places.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How was the meal served?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Father carved. Yes, father carved. And - the two older ones would have - there'd always be two vegetable and they'd - they'd have a vegetable dish each to serve and then the other - father was at this end 
of the table, mother was at that end and she had the Yorkshire pudding and so forth. And the Yorkshire pudding was always served, I think it's Lancashire style, but - it was served - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 
Yorkshire}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  pudding was served with the meat and vegetables, not - as mother said, how in the world could you start going round with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 Yorkshire}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  pudding and then with all the - with the meat and vegetables afterwards. It was always served the same time and mother had the pudding, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 Yorkshire}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  pudding, and the gravy and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would she serve your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 father first}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no, father was carving, father - father and mother were served last. We were all served first you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about the younger children when they were very tiny?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well they would be put by the side of one o
f us older ones and it was our place to attend to their needs you see, before they were old enough to cut up their own we cut it up for them. And gave the eye to them in helping them to feed themselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would you like to tell me a little bit about your mother, the sort of person she was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
She was small - smaller than I am. Rather - stout, shall I say, and yet that exaggerates, she wasn't, she was well rounded. She'd a small face, she'd very dainty hands and feet. And - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 
you never}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  heard her raise her voice. Even with the family. I never once that I can recall heard her raise her voice. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 
If she was annoyed with you, you quickly knew it from her attitude. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 If she had to rebuke you for anything it was always done in the same quiet voice. She - she didn't 
go out very much excepting, as I say, she went to service because on Sunday when we got old enough - there were four girls left you see, and we took it two and two together to - do everything on the Sunday - midday meal, this was after we hadn't a maid bu
t
 that was - and the helps didn't come in on - on Sunday, we did it. And - she just went to service. And - she didn't read very much. Excepting magazines. She was a strong contrast to my father in that, father read - very widely but mother didn't. - She di
d
n't like going for a walk but she loved to go shopping. And - she loved going out in the - the trap. We had a - a trap when just two or three of us were going it was a trap that held four. Two in the front and two; with their backs to them, you see, facin
g
 the other way and she liked that. And then if we were all going out which happened on a Tuesday which was closing day for this - for the business, or who were not at school would go out - up into the country and we had for - for that a wagonette. And - I
 
think it would take eight, four each side, inside facing one another you know. And then the driver was usually my father or one of the boys and two could sit up in the front. And mother loved that. And she liked it especially when father would take the pa
i
r, we had a pair, the black horses of whom we were very proud and very fond. Star was the - the - horse and he had a white star - black horse and a white star and Bonny, who was also black but she's no white on her at all and - mother loved to go out with
 
the - with the pair. She - she wasn't really fond of housework and - she didn't do it if she could - if there was somebody else to do it. She was a - a wonderful hostess. She loved having company. And - she was always in a - quiet way, gay, very quiet way
.
 She - well if I tell you this I think this will put it better than I can put it. Whilst my son was here recently he said, you know mother you're in very much better condition than granny was at your age. So I said, do you think so? So - he said, I'm sure
,
 I don't think. He said, you can do everything. You see I don't have any help in the house, I do it and my washing and everything. And he said, granny always had to have people round her. Looking after her. And I was talking to my daughter about this, she
 
said, well it's true you know, mother. She said, granny always had to be waited on. Now I suppose as her daughter I hadn't thought of it like that. but that's how the grandchildren see it. I never remember my mother getting up for breakfast. She always ha
d her breakfast in bed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was she an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh very easy. And very popular with people when they came. She was a very lovable woman. And the people loved coming, and they loved having her to talk - to. On her ninetieth birthday sh
e'd a huge party and my aunt, who was eighty-six, came from Essex for it and - we - three of us girls were there, of course we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 women you know, and auntie made this comment to me and it summed up my mother. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 She said, you know Mary, if I had any
thing like this I should have been busy going from the kitchen to the room - she said, your mother's just sat there like a duchess and she's been waited on. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
And she - she was very much like a duchess and that day she'd dispensed tea to about fifty people but she'd never needed to move from her chair, you see, we were there being the daughters. No, she was - she was a very wonderful woman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did she show her affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes, she was a very affectionate woman. Very affectionate. She loved to - to s
it down in an easy chair and have us sit on the floor at her feet and just chat. About things that had happened at school. But when it came to real difficulties - you felt she mustn't be worried with them - it was to my father I went with my difficulties.
 He was a very - sympathetic understanding man in a different way from my mother. I never felt that mother must be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 worried}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
, we must keep }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 worries}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  from her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did he seem stronger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 He was stronger in his interest in our characters. Than she was. She 
was always and - very much fonder of the boys than she was of us. The girls were there to serve the needs of the boys and to look after her. My mother was looked after as long as ever I can remember. I don't know whether I - did I tell you that my - when 
my son was here, did I mention that? Well it's no good repeating you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did your father show affection in the same way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. Yes. Not in the same sort of way, in a different way but just as much so. And - he was the intellectual. And he love
d to take - to talk to you on particularly on literature, he was keen on literature. He loved to talk to you on literature. He loved to take you out for walked and he talked on every subject under the sun then. But he was a good conversationalist in a muc
h }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 deeper}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  way than my mother was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
I don't know whether I could say that any more than that we were just - behaved normally. I don't remember ever being told to show respect or anything of th
at sort, we were brought up from babyhood and - we showed respect, it was - it was expected of us and it was shown. Automatically.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Apart from this question of looking after the younger children and the girls doing things for the boys, did your parents
 bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in any particular ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Do you know, I can't remember they did but I do know if any one of us said anything unkind thing we were pulled up at once.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did your parents say that you should hit back or not if another child hurt you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh no. Stand up for yourself but not to hit back. Don't - don't accept - ill treatment from others, but don't give ill treatment to others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you would grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Interested in public work. Receiving the best education that we could get. And working hard. In every way. But }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 particularly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  at our studies. That was always the first thing in our lives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did they bring you up to consider that certain things were very important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes. Always behaving in a kindly way to people. Putting yourself well in the background and acting to others as if you - you were considerate for them, showing consideration for them. When we had guests - the dema
nds of the guests were never too heavy, whatever they wanted - this is a silly little thing but I'm going to tell it to you. An old friend of my father's used to come and stay with us and he was really a hypochondriac. And he wanted a drink at night, milk
 
- and I forgot what was put into it - but the milk must not be boiled. It must just be brought to the boil but stopped immediately it was getting to it. And you know, the old wretch knew if it had gone - when you took it to him it was his - his last drink
 
at night, and when you took it to him he'd look at it and he'd say, no, that's no good. And - you boiled it. And - I would go, if it were - if it were me, I'm afraid I was the naughty one of the family, I would go back and I'd say, you know, one day when 
t
hat man's here I'll throw the milk right in his face. And my mother was horrified. So I said, well really, I have taken great pains with it and all I get is, no, you've boiled it, take it back and get me another glass. But my mother wouldn't expect us to 
resent that. The thing hadn't been done as asked for, well that was our fault. Go and do it again and see you don't make the same mistake next time. And I always wanted to throw it at him. But never would have dared to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What did your parents think about swearing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh it never was - it simply never was mentioned. At all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When the grown ups were talking were you as a small child allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Not to join in, to listen. We could - we could listen, we were always allowed to be there a
nd hear the conversation but we mustn't join in. That - that would be out of place quite. 'Cos we weren't old enough to understand - what they were talking about. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 
And my father was a very, very keen chess player and a very clever chess player and he and an
 uncle of my mother's used to play chess and if - if we didn't know that they were playing chess and were - walked into the room, we quickly turned round and walked back because you mustn't make a sound. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And when the games was ended, I don't know whether y
ou know chess at all, but a - a chess game with these two could go on for days and the chess board was most carefully lifted by either my father or my uncle onto one side, and if it were - if it was there for a week nobody would have dreamt of moving it, 
those chessmen must be left just as they were. And my mother was very - particular about the house being dusted through and we had to take our turn at that you know, but the chessmen mustn't be dusted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 If you did something that your parents disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well it would depend upon the nature of it. Quite often you were sent off to bed. And that would happen until - until you were twelve or so on. And - no supper. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 
If it was something that was very, very serious that you had done - this happened very rarely, I only remember it happening once in my lifetime. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Father would take a whip. And give you a whipping - with a horse whip. But I only - and I was much the worst of the family so that I daresay some of the others never got it at all but I do remember once, having a real whipping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What was that for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Do you know, I don't remember. I remember the whipping. But I told my children this sort of thing you see and they said, well what had you done mother? I said, I haven't the foggiest idea. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 
But it was something that had roused father very badly and I can see him now, lift up the - the - horse whips were kept on - on hooks, standing on - lying down you know, on - on the hooks and I can see him lift up his hand and take it down an
d you know how naughty I was, well I turned to him and said, would you like me to take me dress off and then you'll get nearer to me?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Can you remember how you felt about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Very angry. 'Cos whatever I had done I - I knew I didn't deserve that. 
I really; think that it was that - some member of the family, my youngest sister, had told some tale that was not true to avoid getting into trouble herself. She was rather a spoilt child and she did that sort of thing and - I was stubborn and I wouldn't 
d
eny it when - if I was accused of something I'd say, well do - do you really think I would do that? All right. And - but I only think that, I don't - I'm not sure. I know that sort of thing did happen. That I got in - into trouble because of - the things 
that she had said.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You said that your mother could make an impact on you simply by talking to you in a quiet reproving way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. And she had another habit, I'm rather sorry to mention this about her, but it did happen. She'd sit down and weep. A
nd father would come in you see and say, what's - what's the matter? And he would be told the tale, then of course we were packed off to bed for upsetting mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would you say that you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Not more from one than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well - more from my father for me but that was not true of every member of the family. My father and I - had similar tastes and were very
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  very close to one another. And I wouldn't have 
done anything willingly to upset him. If I did upset him it was like I have told you where I've been got into trouble by somebody else or it was quite unwittingly. I - I worshipped him. I - I still do. His memory. To my mother I always felt protective. Sh
e'd to be looked after.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When you had a birthday what would happen then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh there was always a beautiful birthday cake - made. And - of course being a business house we couldn't always have a birthday party on the actual day. And being such a big 
family we couldn't - all of us have a - a birthday so we used to combine. Those that came near one another, there'd be three or four combined. and - oh mother knew how to make a beautiful birthday for us. She went to no end of trouble, it was no trouble t
o her to put on a wonderful meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was this just for the family or did you have guests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh we - guests were invited. We were - if there were four of us we were each allowed to - to ask twos - two friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes, al
ways presents. But mind, with a big family like that we haven't got a lot of money to spend on presents and we used to make presents for one another. I've embroidered handkerchiefs galore in my day, I was very fond of - I've knitted gloves. For my father 
I
 used to make - out of wash leather and a silver backing - not silver - a silk backing to it, I made, cleaners for his glasses, he had wear glasses long as ever I can remember him and I used to make those for him. For my mother I've made these, in fact, i
n looking back I think she - I don't know how she managed to get rid of them, we used to get walnuts and - get them, open them - so they was whole and yet the two shells joined. And - varnish them and line them for her }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 silver}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  - for her silver }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 thimble}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . - Som
etimes we'd decide that we'd all combine - we'd hear something that she wanted. I remember so very much - so very well her - wanting a table brush and crumb tray you know and - we were all young, we hadn't much money, - but we combined and bought - bought
 
that for her and that - I can't tell you any other things but I do remember that because we were all sworn to secrecy and - I - I don't know, we were only quite young, but I remember saying to her, you would like a brush mother wouldn't you, to brush the 
crumbs off the table? Didn't I get into trouble with the rest of the family because I'd given the game away.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Stockings were always hung up at the bed - foot. And - we got very good presents. Mother and father never stinted 
there at all. And we always, in the stockings, went always an apple, an orange, some nuts, some new money - and perhaps a handkerchief or some little thing like that. And then the real present was - too big to go inside. When we were younger we had dolls 
o
r something of that sort you know. But we always had very lovely presents. And my mother had an idea that I've never met with anywhere else and I do not know where she got it form. Father Christmas came on Christmas Day and the fairies came on New Years D
ay. I'd never heard of it before. And we got a repetition }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 on a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  very much smaller }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 scale}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. On the on New Years Day. It was nice. And - we were always told that - fairies would never come into the bedroom as long as any eye was open. So we always went to sleep.
 But referring to Christmas again we had a most happy time with my grandparents who lived - oh ten minutes or quarter or an hours walk away and my grandfather was the one that I told you had the - garden. Well he - he was a clever man, they lived in a cot
t
age, it had a big open fireplace and the chimney went straight up and they knew of course that we had Father Christmas come on Christmas Day and we had the fairies come on Boxing Day - rather on New Years Day - and so some other day and I don't remember w
h
ether there was a set day for it. We - we all of us went up to granny's and grandpa's and - he - fixed a basket pull of presents and fruit that was let down the chimney. He climbed onto the top of the roof, it was a cottage, and fixed it up and we had to 
c
all up the chimney, Betty, we're all here, what have you got for us? And then down came this basket. He swept the - the chimney beforehand. But - oh it was a thrill. When we - when we called up the chimney, Betty we're here, we were answered by a little t
inkle of a bell. I think it was wonderful grandfather doing that because he was - a sick man but we - we had that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 That was some time round about Christmas was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, it was during the - during the Christmas festivities. But - I don't remember
 whether there was any special day for it. In my mind it was on Boxing Day but I could be wrong. But it was during the Christmas festivities.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you spend your Christmas Day as a family at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Family at home. Nobody was expected to go out on Christmas Day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about going to church on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well - there - there wasn't a service in the - in the chapel on Christmas Day. At least, if there was I don't remember and we certainly didn't go. No, I should think there wouldn't be o
ne or else we should have gone. But I shall always remember Dewsbury parish church had a wonderful peal of bells and - they - they really were wonderful and beautiful - beautifully rung and we always listened for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 those}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  bells. And the - the choir from the c
hapel that we attended came on Christmas Eve and sang. And - mother always had a - quite a big supper provided for them, hot supper was provided. There'd be about twenty or thirty of them but there was a meal provided for them. And on Christmas morning, t
he band - and I cannot remember, I think it was a local band that we had, I don't think it was a Salvation Army - came and played Christmas carols on Christmas morning. That was - as long as ever I can remember as a child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did your parents play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Either indoors or outdoors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, indoor - father particularly would join in our children's games like snap and ludo and that sort of thing you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Do you remember a funeral in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. In those days
 unfortunately children went to funerals. My little sister who died, I told you, at five, she was the one next older than me, she and I had been very very close friends and I know I remember, my mother knows I remember, she was five when she died so I was
 
three. But she - she had T.B. and in those days of course there was no cure and she lay ill for months. I can't tell you any nearer than that. And I was allowed to go and sit on her bed and play with her. And - then she died and she was so tiny you know a
n
d altogether she shrunk, and she was laid out on the big couch in the sitting room and in those days, you know, funeral was poorly and all he curtains were drawn in the house and they were kept drawn from the moment of death until after the funeral. And I
 
- my mother was ill. She collapsed after Eva's death and was in bed and I used to tip-toe into her room and say, mother, can I - it was always mother, we never had mummy you know, always mother - can I go and - and talk to Eva. I promise I won't waken her
.
 And I used to go and sit on a little stool by the side of the couch and I was allowed to take the handkerchief off her face and I talked to her. Now I remember that very very well. What I am amazed at is that my father took me to the funeral, that was a 
c
ruel wicked thing to do. And I was dressed all in black, I can see my little black bonnet now that I had on. Three years old my dear. And - I stood by the open grave, I could see it all now, and saw that little coffin go down and screamed. And my father h
ad my hand, held me, he was very upset of course - he said, ssh, you mustn't do - I said, Eva's calling, she doesn't like being in that box and - she mustn't be put in that hole. Now I'm eighty-four now }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 so}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  that's eighty-one years ago but I can see - and fee
l the whole thing still. And my mother said when I got home I went in to her and threw myself on the bed and sobbed. They put Eva in a hole mummy - mother - and - she didn't want to go and she cried out. Of course it was a - it was a wicked thing to take 
a
 three year old to a funeral. But it was the sort of thing that was done you know, all the family went and because Eva and I had been so close to one another my father thought I ought to go. And even now I wish he never had. But there were - there were ot
h
er funerals as well we - funerals were wicked things weren't they those days, you won't know but they were, they were wicked things. I can see the horses with their big plumes on, you know, most of the coaches had a pair of horses and their big plumes on 
and I went to my grandfather's funeral, I was only a child when he died. And to a cousin's and - oh I couldn't tell you. But certainly we went to funerals.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about the length of time you would be in mourning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Twelve months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 For the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
I don't think the children - no. No. No, I don't think so. It was only those who were getting up. But I remember this was in 1910 so we're in the time aren't we? In 1910 I lost a very dear friend, in fact he was my fianc\'e9 and he died - just like
 that as I was talking to him and - I was twelve months in deep mourning. And - we began to think it was time I came out of the more or less coal mine I think I was in and I went to a - a think it was a concert or something to help, I think it was a dance
 
really but I was helping with the refreshments and that - it was the first time I put anything to relieve the black and I had on a gold brooch. That was all. I was in deep black and just a gold brooch. And somebody came up to me and said, are you going ou
t
 of mourning so soon? And that was over twelve months after. And - I went to funerals with my father of his friends and they had what I think is a - I don't know, they liked it, I don't now that they liked it, they considered it correct - they would all s
t
and round the open grave after the coffin was - was lowered and sing God be with you 'til we meet again. Now that's another thing I can remember well. They sang it. And of course the - the widow of a man who had died would be dressed in very deep mourning
.
 Crepe veils down you know. All their dresses had to be - it was only correct to have them trimmed with black crepe. and the drivers of the coaches had black crepe bands tied round their hats, they had tall hats and they had a crepe band tied round and th
e
 streamers hung behind. Looking back now I laugh that - that - that has no bitter memories. But the two little things I've told - well they were big things in my life - seeing my sister buried and being asked if I was going out of mourning. Those seared a
nd - it isn't that I - I don't let myself be unhappy about it, but it's left a mark. There's a scar still there. And I'm talking to you now as I haven't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 talked}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  to anybody. The incident of the gold brooch I haven't even told members of - well of course you wouldn't - I wouldn't tell members of my family because it wasn't their father you see, it was - four -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Let's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 get onto}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  happier things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, I should think so. Those are dreadfully - depressing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were you taken out to visit neighbours and friends and relatives quite often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well - I don't remember being taken much. But we went. Amongst our own friends. Now one - my father used to take me particularly because I was very fond of this friend. She was a - she was in business like my father wa
s only a different business and - she was very highly intellectual and a big reader and we used to talk books. She was a - a very interesting woman and she lived in a very old house, most interesting house. In the living room, there was a balcony went all
 
the way round and a staircase went up to this balcony from the living room and from this balcony the - the bedrooms opened. There was one there, I can see it now, one there and one over here. Now I don't know any others but those three had a special signi
f
icance to me. And - she was a wonderful woman to talk to, and she always wore a house dress in the evenings and she had lovely colours, dove grey was her favourite and she had lace ruffles round the neck and round the - the sleeves. She was a picture - I'
m
 always sorry we hadn't a photograph of her. And this house was supposed to be the shooting box belonging to a big house that was down the road some distance. The house had gone now. I don't know whether - whether Miss Wilman's house is still there but th
e
 shooting - the - the big house had gone and the tale told about it was that after the old man's funeral, a very - a very eccentric old man he was and - he'd had - a tunnel dug from his big house under the - up the hill to the shooting - I don't know they
 
call it a shooting box or a - anyway it was his sort of place to go to when he wanted to be on his own. Now that tunnel was found. And the tale that was always told about it was that after his funeral some friends went up to this smaller house up the road
 
and he was sitting by the fireside smoking his pipe. That was popularly believed. But of course that was before my time. But what I do know, this was an actual experience. So vivid again that I can see it all. I was with my father, this woman was sitting 
t
here, father was sitting there and I was sitting here, and we were talking. And at last this woman said, Mary, what in the world's the matter with you? You've been fidgeting ever since you came in. So I said, well Miss Willman, I didn't know anybody was i
n
 the house but us three. She said, there isn't. So I said, well tell me, who is it comes out of that bedroom, goes along the corridor there, into that bedroom there, comes out again, goes round here and into that bedroom there? So she said, what - what - 
w
hat is it, is it a woman or a man? I said it's a girl. And she's in a long white nightdress, she's got beautiful long golden hair to her waist and a very lovely oval face. Oh, she said, that's my sister, she died twenty years ago but she often comes to vi
s
it me. Now I didn't know that Miss Willman had a sister. So - I - it - I couldn't have imagined it and that was what had made me fidgety, I kept seeing her come out and go along there and in there and round here, and then she'd come back again and go into
 
her own room and close the door. That was a very - it was a lovely experience, I wasn't frightened, it was a very lovely experience. And I didn't know Miss Willman had had a sister, so far as I knew she was a only child. But - that was a house I often wen
t
 to. She was a very interesting woman. My father, unfortunately - but I never felt - felt anything gruesome about it - his Sunday morning walk after chapel was up to the cemetery and he always said he went to sit - to talk to his old friends there and one
 
or two of us would go with him. There was nothing gruesome about it. He just went - he went there, when I - if I go to Dewsbury I always go to the cemetery, not that I am given to visiting graves, I never go to my husband's grave, I won't go, but I go to 
t
hese old - you know - you know what terribly big - memorials they put up in those days. Well they're still there you see. Very very old. And I still go and look at those and think this was where I used to come with father, to see these old people and that
 was a - regular Sunday morning walk.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were you taken shopping as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes, we loved to go with my mother shopping, she was a wonderful shopper. Wonderful. And she was - you know, she was such a friendly soul, despite all I've said about her 
being a duchess, she'd - a very lovely voice and - she was very easy and friendly with folk. And - they - one thing that I liked very much, and she liked too, to go on market evenings, I think it was Wednesday evening, and there was a big - open market, o
pen air market in the middle of Dewsbury. And they were the old fashioned stalls you know that were put up with the awnings over the top and really you got some wonderful bargains there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 
They - they used to - buy up - one - one crockery shop - they bought up the leftovers or the slightly damaged, really good class china. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
I bought a lot there. But the thing that was most fun was to go to the fish shop, there was an old man there - as straight as a dye, he would never - never sell you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 anything}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  that wasn't just
 so, if you were young. My - my mother could send us to that - that stall and - I can hear him now crying such and such fish, such and such a price all - all fresh from the - sea, or fresh from the river or something of that sort and it was a pantomime to
 
go and listen to him. And my mother was very fond of fish, the family were and Wednesday evening we go down and buy fish, either to cook that same evening for supper or for the next day's dinner. But it was real fun. And - my mother was - she was very goo
d
 at repartee and he - he would - you know, she'd tell him what she wanted and he'd hand it over and he'd say, and that's so much and - it's cheap at the price you know, m'm, and she'd say, yes, maybe, but I know who's got the bargain - not me. But they kn
ew one another you see and it was - oh yes, I - I loved to go to the market with my mother.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You've told me about holidays and weekend outings, what about Bank Holidays, did you used to have a Bank Holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 A Bank Holiday, oh yes, and we - usually went out with the horses you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 As a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. As a family, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Going back to Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about playing games on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no. Oh no. All games were put away. Sundays were the most - we didn't feel them bor
ing but in looking back I - I wonder how in the world we got through a Sunday. But of course, as I've told you, we went to Sunday - to Sunday school, we went to chapel, we went to afternoon Sunday school, we went to evening service and as long as the - th
e
 child - there were children who were too small to go to evening service some of the older ones, one of them had - the duty of - we took it in turns you see, of staying and - there was a regular routine for that, you told a story to the little ones and - 
you taught them some verses from the Bible which father would hear when he came home to make sure we'd done our duty, and then we played }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 hymns}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  and - and the children - the little ones sung the hymns.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about Sunday school outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well the Sun
day school outing of the - of the year, we didn't have many others, was the Whit Monday and that was a big affair. Oh yes, very big affair. The little ones were taken on wagons - sides were put up on some wagons and teachers went in charge of the tinies. 
A
nd then the others walked in pairs and of course everybody turned out very smart for that, white dresses were the - the routine. And - you stopped at certain places and sang Whitsuntide hymns as we called them. And then up to our - our chapel went up to M
a
jor Percy Walker's, which was - he was a big man at the chapel you see and - he had woolen mills, he was a man of very high standing in the town and you sang for - for him and for Beatrice, his sister. For the older man, John, as long as he lived, he was 
l
iving - oh - from my - oh my early days. And then the fields were thrown open and you - ran races and there were ice cream carts there which were always a joy to children. And - then at a certain time, I think it was four o'clock, you were given a big bun
 and the - men came round with cans of tea and you had a mug and you had tea and buns. And then you were free to play games or anything, you see, that you liked.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What other social activities were there organised by the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 There - there were always - groups who arranged what they called social evenings. And - somebody would train }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 some}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 of us to sing and act and - there was a - a refreshment stall put up and somebody took charge of that and there was great rivalry between the different companies as to who could make the most money for the chapel funds or the Sunday school funds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you belong to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you belong to any other club or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes, the - the Christian - the Christian Endeavour was the big thing in those days you know. And we were all members of Christian }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 Endeavour.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 And Mr Anstey, the man that I have told you of, was a - he was a - a very well educated, highly educated man and he used to take Bible study once a week and we all went t
o that. And then at the end of the time there - there was scriptures examinations held by the Sunday school union and we sat for - for those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was grace said at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 By?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about being taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you - have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
No. No. With a family like ours you see you went to bed at different times and whoever was putting you to bed - knelt with you and - the prayers were said. That that terrible - man, Jack t
he Ripper was in vogue and - I don't know, the tale got round that - he'd come into Yorkshire. And my - my sister next older, not the one who died, the one older still, got - she must have believed it because we'd terrible times with her, she used to wake
n
 in the night screaming. And - if any - if any of us were disturbed in the night it was always my father who came up to us you see and - time and time again father would waken her to find out what was the matter and she'd say - oh Jack the ripper had got 
me. So some - we never knew where she'd heard the tale but someone somewhere - had got it instilled into her. But she - night after night she would have these screaming fits and it was always same thing and father got her wakened and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 quieted}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 , oh, Jack the Ripper had got me. I don't think I should know the name Jack the Ripper if it hadn't been for that connection. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 And that - that song - Daisy, Daisy, give me your answer do, you must have heard it, well - one of my younger brothers learnt it, he was a - he wa
s a jolly little chap, really very jolly, you know, good company, and he would sing it and then he got that he sang it at night in his sleep. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
And he stood by the side of his bed and he'd be fast asleep in bed and he started singing this, he'd take it up and sing it, it was real fun.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Your father and mother and their politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Politics? Oh Liberals - radical Liberals. We worked like niggers for the Liberal party.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was your mother a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 Liberal }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 in her own right or because your father was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I d
on't think that mother was very - much minded in that direction you know but father had been a Liberal all his days, a very active Liberal. And people used to tell him that as a business man he had no business to be so outright a Liberal. But if it - if i
t affected his business we never knew. But in that connection he'd a terrible nasty experience }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 during}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 the Boer War. Are we in the right age? He was a pro-Boer and spike at meetings pointing out the wrong that the British people were doing in fighting the Bo
ers. And - he was out one night, passing one of these meetings when a crowd of roughs came along - with rotten eggs and bad tomatoes and threw them at him. And he and my sister came in drenched from head to foot. That was the sort of thing that went on in
 those days. I think sometimes when I hear of these stupid - students who are making such asses of themselves, that's my opinion of course, things were much }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 worse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  in - in those days, in - in the political world. 'Cos it - oh they got very - very hot under the collar about politics. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 
And we youngsters, as quite youngsters, used to go round - in bands singing, vote, vote, vote for - whoever you were - and the opposing ones went round the same and if the two bands met, well it - it was - rough play.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Tell me something about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well we - we used to - we were forbidden to but we did it. There'd be a band of perhaps twenty young folk and we all wore our colours, the Liberal colour in Dewsbury was Yellow. The Conservative colour was blue and that was befor
e the days of Labour party you see. And - we'd have - make a big banner and - print on it, Liberal, in big letters and - underneath vote for whoever it happened to be. During my day it was - it was Mark Oldroyd to begin with and then we had Mr Runsom and 
-
 who's name you will have heard. And - we went - just round the various - the various streets singing vote, vote, vote for Mr Runsom, for he's a proper man. I don't think I can remember it all now. Then something else came and then - we'll return him if w
e
 can. I've forgotten it. There's another line afterwards. And - you - you'd hear the singing in another - direction. Well it depended whether you felt that night ready for a fight or if you wanted to avoid one. If you wanted to avoid one you took a turnin
g
 that didn't bring you near to this other lot. But if you happened to meet, well then we scrapped. Scratched faces and black eyes, all the rest of it. And - it was quite a - quite an accepted thing at - at election time. And as we got a little bit older I
 
think we were allowed to go when we got to be ten or twelve down to hear the declaration of the - of the poll. And that was a time. We all went out and - you know - listened with bated breath. It so happened that Dewsbury in those days was a Liberal const
ituency so that we were always - very thrilled and shouted ourselves hoarse.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Why do }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 you think}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  your father was so strongly Liberal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So strongly Liberal? Well I think everything in his life tended to be the Liberal side of things. He certainly had
 studied it. And - again we had the open air meetings you see and he was a - a constant }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 speaker}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 at open air meetings. And he could put a very good case, it wasn't - his people were - were country people and they were Tories you know, absolutely. But - my f
ather and his younger brother they both of them were strong Liberals and I can't give you any other reason for it excepting that that was - they'd thought it out and that was what they felt was the right thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did he go canvassing at election time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh yes. And - aw we got old enough to go we all canvassed. Oh yes. And we drove the - the pony and - governess car fetching up the people for - for voting you know. We were given a list of folk who hadn't voted and we went - went round bringing them u
p for voting. Oh it was - it was great fun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did your mother take part in any of these activities or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
No. She really wasn't - she didn't think father ought to do it, she thought as a business man he shouldn't do it. But - that - wouldn't make
 any difference to him. Mother would help on the side, really our house was a meeting house for all - for the - people - the workers and mother would help in that she - provided - when the folk would come in when they wanted to see some - about something 
o
r do something a bit of work or meet somebody that they thought might be at Mr White's shop - house and mother would serve cups of tea and - sandwiches and - and cakes galore. She'd always do that. And to give you an idea of it, I was one day in charge, I
 
don't know where my mother was that I'd had to take charge of these people calling and - I took the trouble to count. I served a hundred and fifty cups of tea that day to a hundred and fifty people, there'd be more than just - some fold would have a coupl
e of cups you see. But - that was the sort of life that we lived during election time. Oh it was very hectic but we loved it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was there any of this sort of scrapping in the streets at other times than at election time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well I think amongst the b
oys but not us girls. The boys would. And - you see the only place for them to play in those days was the streets and they played football in the streets, well how many broken windows my father had to pay for is anybody's guess. And - if - some other boy 
- some other set of boys wanted the pitch on which - the party were playing then there'd be a real scrap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Your parents other interests, your father was the intellectual and the reader and so on, your mother rarely went out and didn't do much except the church bazaars, what else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well father did a tremendous amount of writing. I have upstairs a book of letters that he wrote to the papers. His letters were nearly always in the Yorkshire Post and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 Dewsbury}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  Reporter and the Bradford Observer I think it was. And - he wrote on educational matters. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 
temperance matters and he was a very great admirer and student of the Brontes and he wrote articles on the Brontes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Mother had quite a number of - of - close friends who used to come - it wasn't the afternoon te
a, it wasn't - she never had a day like they - like they did. She went to them - we had one or two friends who had their - at home days you know and mother went but she never had an at home day herself. But - lots of people came in - for - a chat and a cu
p of cup of tea you see or stay and have a meal with us. It was a house where there was it was seldom there was just the family - we'd always folk in and out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And these would be friends and relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Mostly friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, we've no neighbours. No. At least, no neighbours - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 nearest}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 neighbour,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 you had to go down past all our buildings, which meant the shop, the house, the warehouse - and round the back - down the side streets there and - you came to a door and that was the first neighbour. We - there were - there weren't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 neighbours}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So there wasn't any social contact much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, excepting that we knew them all you see. And we slipped into their house - they - they had families and - we met together t
hat way, played together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 The children you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Who did you play with in the main as a child, was it with neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 With}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306  neighbours}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Or with sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 With - with - with - our - our own family and the neighb
ours families. I have a - at least I have a letter but my sister has a letter from a boy who was - who lived in this house I've just been telling you that was the nearest house to ours, and he said, remember me to Mary and tell her I'm the same age, I'm e
i
ghty-four as well as her. Well I haven't seen him since we were boy and girl. But - the association was so close you see. And the - the - this particular family, they were very strict - very very very strict. Occasionally we used to go for tea. And - ever
y
 body at the table had to stand - stand up and say grace. You all had to say it, in turn, not - not in unison, in turn. And I was there one time - and - you know I felt I couldn't say it. So I wasn't allowed to have any tea. Mrs Cooke said, come along Mar
y, you know your grace. And I just shook me head. I should only be six or seven, something you see, I shook me head, didn't say a word. And then she started it for me and I didn't take it up. And it was nothing but sheer }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 fright}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . And why I should - why I should - I don't know but I wasn't allowed any tea, I sat through tea time and I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did you feel about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well I was just thankful for the meal to end and I could get home and get me tea. I went home, told mother, I said, Mrs cook wouldn't le
t me have any tea. Oh, you've been naughty? So I said, well she thought so and I told mother what - had happened. She said, well, you know that when you go to the Cooke's for tea you always each one to say grace. I said, well I just didn't want to mother,
 that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was there anyone of your brothers and sisters that you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes. One. And he was - a brother - he came about third below me. And he was very delicate, he wanted a lot of care and - and attention and he again was one of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 literary}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 ones of the family and - he really looked upon me, although how many years older should I be than him? Oh perhaps six or so, but he looked upon me as a mother. And I helped him a lot with his work. And he - he loved it if I would go
 out for a walk with him. We used to go out for walks five o'clock in the morning. Yes, the boys would come, knock at my door, I was the one who liked to go out walking early, they knocked at the door and say, come along, Mary it's a lovely morning. And w
e
'd - you know - just go quietly out so that we didn't disturb anybody else and go to - right away onto the top of the hills, two or three miles away and then come back and be back in time to get breakfast ready and have it. Walking was the great - exercis
e for us you know. Yes, we loved walking.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of outdoor games did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well as we got to the - to the - oh you mean, as children. Oh yes - pot checks - heard of them? And hopscotch - loved both those. And marbles. And skipping a lot 
- we did a lot of skipping, both - skipping with a rope just on your own and skipping in a - a group. One at each end you see. And hoops, the girls had the wooden hoops and the boys had the - the iron hoops with the hook on. I never could - I can never co
u
ld use one of those and I was very annoyed, I didn't like my brothers being able to - to work their hoops and I couldn't. I - I could - I was quite good with a - an ordinary hoop you know, but not that. And - whip and top. And isn't it strange how - I - I
 don't remember the order now but they all came in order.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You had a phase you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes. Yes. I think hopscotch and pot checks, they went pretty well all through the spring, summer and autumn anyway, winter wasn't the time for them. But - we used to be very very clever I think in looking back, with our hoops. And with the whip and top.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What happened if you got dirty while you were playing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well we'd to go in and get washed, that's all. We did get dirty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 It didn't meet with disapproval?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
No. Mother - mother would say, well that - everybody wore pinafores by the by in those days, all the girls. We had a clean pinafore on every day for school. And mother would just say, oh, it's a pity you haven't to wash it yourself isn't it? Whe
n it was particularly dirty you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were you free to play with anybody that you chose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Up to a point. But it so happened, it was lucky, that there were very few people about - in fact I don't remember any - who lived within distance who mother
 would have disapproved of. But if we brought home with us from school anybody that - looked a bit down and out we would be told afterwards not to do that again. And yet I'm perfectly certain my mother would - would have said that she hadn't a bit of a sn
ob about her, but there was certainly that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you belong to any youth organizations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
No. No. The boys belonged to the - Boys Brigade. But - I never belonged. I don't think either of my sisters did either. They used to play the school games, on
e was in the hockey team. We all played tennis. And - when I was in college, which was '05 to '07 so we're still in the right age, I was in the cricket team in college.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When you were still at school, apart from reading, what other hobbies did you have, did you collect anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
No, I don't remember collecting things but I did an enormous amount of knitting. Did I - did I tell you - yes, I thought I'd mentioned that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 On the outdoor side, apart from swimming and walking, did you have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 
a bicycle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  or did you go fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
No. The others - the boys had bicycles but - you know, it was hardly the thing for girls to - to - it - they hadn't become very common. And - my mother didn't think it was very ladylike. Anyway we never had one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Apart from your hockey and tennis and cricket were there any other sports that you took part in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well the boys of course played football. Very - both football and cricket they were - all the younger end, my eldest brother didn't do much, but the - all the others did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 But there are no others you can remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I can't remember any. We were all very fond of dancing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 At what age did you start on that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well I don't remember a time when I didn't love dancing. And I never had lessons. We used to
 dance - the girls danced together in school you know. There was a - a period when we were in the grammar school and we were allowed a period for dancing. But I don't remember having any special lessons. And I was always conscious of the fact that I wasn'
t
 a really trained dancer and when the boys came along again you'll notice from the list I gave you that I had five brothers younger than myself. Well as they got to the age I paid for - I was then working - I'd come out of college and I paid for them to g
o and have proper dancing lessons. Yes. Which I got the benefit you know, myself, because I'd always plenty of dancing partners.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about theatres and concerts and things like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. Yes. In - in those days there were a lot of concerts. We had a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Amateur or professional or both?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Both. And my father was an absolute fanatic on the theatre. And - we - whenever there was a decent play we went. And whatever was it they called them? The choral society - the Dewsbury Choral Society,
 used to give a lot of - of concerts and we always had the season tickets for those. And then there was a - a series, and I'm }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 sorry}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  I cannot - it had a special name of Science lectures, and again we had season tickets and went to those. My father always went and two or three of us went with him you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Who would organize those, do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well the Choral Society was an - a number of musical people who organized themselves. And - that's what I - if I could remember the name of the scientific l
ectures, then I should be able to tell you but it was a body of people in Dewsbury who organized these and they used to get lecturers very noted lecturers too from all over the country. But the ones I remember best was, one who was - lecturing on the begi
n
nings, away back in these days, the beginnings of wireless. And I can see him now with two pianos, tuned to one another you see, and he played the note on one and to our amazement the other piano - echoed it. And he told us how that would develop in time 
-
 we never believed him you know. But I can - it was in the Dewsbury Town Hall, they had a very very good lecture hall there and these two big pianos were there and - I can see him now, playing on one and the other one - producing the sound. We thought it 
was a bit of magic you know. But he - I - I don't pretend to remember all about it but I do remember that he said the time would come when - that would be used for us to have - music in our homes from - but of course we didn't believe him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about music halls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well they were things that my father wouldn't have taken us to. I think there was a music hall in Dewsbury but I'm not really sure. He wasn't keen when - the cinemas started. No. No, he thought that was not constructive enough, you just s
at and there was no demand for any effort on your part to understand. He thought it was just amusement. Although he didn't a bit mind us having a magic lantern of our own at home and we used to - we used to give - have our friends in you know and give - m
agic lantern shoes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about pocket }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 money}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Now I don't remember how old I was when I was moved from a penny to tuppence a week. But I do know that when I came out of college - and I was twenty-two, the year I came out - or very soon afterwards
. I had half a crown a month and from that - I provided my - collection money and in those days we wore hair ribbons and bought my own hair ribbons and my goodness my hair ribbons used to last a long time. I learnt how to tie them so that they - the shred
s didn't show. And that was for quite a long time. That I had half a crown a month.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 As a child did you spend any money on sweets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, chocolate. A - a bar of - raspberry cream chocolate was my favourite and that was a ha'penny and then I'd a ha'
penny for something else you see. But we had to save up for - for presents for Christmas and birthday presents so - out of your penny a week, yes. Of course we weren't expected to spend much on presents but we had to provide the money ourselves, mother wo
uldn't give us money for presents. If we hadn't money then we defected and we looked a bit mean, so nobody defected very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You had plenty of domestic help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did anyone outside the home help your mother to look after the house or family, meaning relatives, friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. After my grandfather died - the one of whom I've }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 spoken}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  - my grandmother - father had cottages and she came to live in one of the cottages and she used to come up and help with washing up and
 - looking after - the children and mending, she was very good with her needle and she used to help with the mending. Just a - there was no set time, just when she liked. It was not five minutes walk away. In fact, it was so near that - mother always went
 her dinners down for her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 If your mother was ill or at confinement time, how did she manage then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well she always had a monthly nurse in. In those days you see they were - they call themselves monthly nurses, they - they - I think really they were just handy women who knew how to - deal with these things. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 And - if extra household help were needed during that time you could always get in, in those days. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
There were plenty of people that you could get to come in and give a hand. But my granny was with - was - very much a stand-by.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would these monthly women - they dealt with the maternity side of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did they used to do laying out as well? Or would it be different people who did that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Now that I don't
 know. They - I think that they would. Because this is going later now but it was a - I'd never heard of it until my own case, when my last baby was born and that was in - 19 - 19, she was born. That was the one you met here, she's my baby. She was born, 
I
 don't know, it doesn't matter, but during the night time the bell rang and the nurse I had - she was a nurse - went and answered it, the maid slept right at the top of the house and she - my nurse could get down quicker and evidently she was expecting th
e
 call and she came back and she said, I had a cousin who lived a few doors away, she said, I'm going down for your cousin to come and stay with you because I've promised to go and lay somebody out who I knew was dying. Well of course that was a wicked thi
n
g, she'd do business to do that when she was nursing me. But - she went. And I was amazed that anybody who did the maternity work also did that so whether that - dated back, whether it was a hang over from - earlier days, I just don't know. I don't know a
t all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I think in some parts of the country this did happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I daresay. No, I really don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Do you remember what happened when one of your younger brothers of sisters was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When? Oh yes, there was always - always a general sti
r in the house and - my mother had the same - monthly nurse, for one after another, and when she appeared then we wondered when - we always knew what was going on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Now to the question of the social classes in the community?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What were the different ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well there were the people who had money and lived on their money. They were the - in a - in a small town like - well it isn't a very small one, but in a - an industrial town like ours, those were the aristocracy. And then there
 were the heads of big mills who came next. There were a lot of those, I mentioned two. Mark Oldroyd and Percy Walker. There were a lot of those and - they were very much the superior people. And in the chapel, the superior people sat at the back downstai
r
s. Yes, that - everybody - everybody in those days had their own pew, you paid - few - pew rents. And you had your own pew. And - the back four rows were the aristocrats. Whether they had to pay more for their - pews or not I don't know. And why at the ba
c
k I don't know. Because it was under the gallery and you couldn't hear a thing there but that was - that their - their place. And - then there would be the - the councilors and people like that you know, who were the - because in those days an ordinary wo
rking man was seldom - put up for the council. They kept to the - more the - wealthier and - I was going to say more intellectual, but I know that that is true but they were the wealthier people. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 Trades people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  - would possibly come next, but }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 trades people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 hardly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  middle class people There was very much a - they are }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 trades people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. The doctors of course came - doctors and dentists came in the higher rank - ranking. And - then there would be shop assistants I think would come in - next. And then the road me
n and the - labourers. Just telling you, you know, on the spur of the moment that's as - as near as I could tell you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you think of some people belonging to one social class and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh definitely. Oh - oh yes. At the time, yes. 
Yes. The - the people who sat in the back pews of the - of the chapel, well - you - you hardly spoke to them, you certainly didn't unless they spoke to you. And they seldom spoke to you. They were - very superior.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Which group would you belong to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 trades people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . Yes. Yes, we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 trades people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would it be just other }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 trades people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  whom you would put in your group or would you class other people in the same group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well mostly other }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 trades people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  but - well, as I have told yo
u, father was an intellectual. He was on the council. He was an outstanding public man in public work. He was on the school board. So that we mixed with those - a little above us. And, believe me, we never thought they were above us in - you know, we didn
't really think they were but we knew we were expected to - think they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were you brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I think my mother had that, my father hadn't, but I think my mother had that. A rathe
r - differential attitude towards these - so called superior people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were you ever told to curtsey to anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no. But - but my father came from the country - Gloucestershire - and - there we were. Of course we - we had not met it at home but
 I remember being with my granny, my father's mother - and we were going down the village street and the carriage came by with the Squire and his wife and I can see my granny now stop and curtsey. I was furious. -Absolutely furious. And my father was with
 
us and he didn't - stop and make any sign to the - to the gentry and didn't we get a telling off afterwards. I can hear my granny now say, Charles, didn't you know who that was? Yes, he said, I did know mother. But the day has gone by when I'm going to - 
bow to the - the gentry. But he was always taught to as a boy, he says, well I've taught myself since not to. But my granny, up to the end of her life, did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 This was more prevalent in a village community?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh definitely it was. Yes. My - my mothe
r's sister and her family lived in an Essex village and - uncle was in quite a good position on the - the - Port of London Authority and - the children went to the village school and we laughed often when they came home one day, three of them, came into t
h
e kitchen, I was staying there at the time, came into the kitchen where auntie was and all three of them that were the boy pulled his forelock and the girls curtsied and auntie turned round and she said, what's this in aid of. Ooh, the vicar's been in thi
s morning. And we had to curtsey to Mrs Rigby, that was my auntie, and we'd to curtsey to the - to the vicar's wife and we're to do that wherever we see them so we thought we'd better come home and practice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was there anyone that you called sir or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Do you remember anybody showing respect to your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh yes, my parents were held in great respect. They - you know, they were big - my father particularly - a big worker in the public life. And - oh yes, they certainly were. An
d part of father's - work - public work - was to visit the schools - with the - not of course for any inspecting of schools, nothing like that, but to see the heads and to see if there were - if there were any difficulties or if there were any things espe
c
ially needed, like new furniture and so forth and he was always greeted with very great respect and - the members of the - of the board, the education board, were made governors of certain schools, there were certain schools. Father. Yes. Mind, there were
 people, as you can understand, he was so thoroughly outspoken on the things in which he believed that naturally he had enemies who disapproved of him. But - they were very highly respected.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Can you tell me who the various groups of people would normally associated with as a regular thing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306  different wasn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. Yes. Normal circumstances }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 trades people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  - mixed with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 trades people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. Yes. There were exceptions, particularly the people who were - who had high standing in the - Freemasons. And - t
here were people who were in trade who were also very - I don't know whether the Freemasons are active or not - but they were outstanding members of the Freemasons and that gave them a higher - category.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about the clergy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well - they were really in the upper class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Who would they mix with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 With one another. And - with the - upper class in - in other walks of life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would their relationship with the people in their congregation be purely pastoral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. They were social with the upper classes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well in those days you know teachers were a very depressed set but we kept very much to our - to one another. In - a town of that size there were a big number of teachers. But when I tell you I came ou
t of college having done - a year probation, four years pupil teacher, two years training in college and I had sixty pounds a year. That was my salary. And we went up by - annual rises of two pounds ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 The farmers on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 outskirts}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 , what were their social relationships?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well very much with one another. You see, it was before the days of the motor car and - a farmer only came down in his gig or on his - cart that he had and didn't come often into the town. They were very much - separate community.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about the employers in the town, there'd be the big mill owners wouldn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Builders.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 They would keep to themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh very much. Very much to themselves, yes. Yes. And they lived - there was a - one area - well, ther
e were two areas in which these people lived and they had houses, you know, detached houses with big grounds round. Very select.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about the lesser employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well - there were the - Shoddy and Mungo people - they had smaller ones, you know what they are don't you, the Shoddy and Mungo. Well}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306  there}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  was a lot of that in Dewsbury but - very - they really ranked with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 trades people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 , they weren't - they weren't of any standing very much. In the area there were collieries and the outskirts of Dew
sbury and the colliery owners were amongst the - the aristocrats. Very wealthy - in fact, I think it was much more the wealth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306  that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  gave them their position than any - than any special ability. Their ability was business ability you see. The big employer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306  was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  Mark }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9515254\charrsid15878306 Oldroyd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. And he gave the town the - clock. It's always called Old Mark in the Town Hall. A beautiful clock, striking }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 clock, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
it's still the same one after all these years. I expect there would be money left for the upkeep of it and - he was very stri
ct with his work people and - they - they responded very well. You see Mark - Mark Oldroyd's people going to work was an education. They all wore shawls. Some of them wore the shawl over their head but many of them wore a hat and the shawl round their sho
u
lders you know, and hanging down and - they knew how to put them on and they were all spotless. And of course in those days everybody wore black woolen stockings and clogs and their clogs shone. They'd such pride in them and they had toe caps of either br
a
ss or steel and - the strap over was decorated with either brass or steel, you could see yourself in them, they were beautifully kept. And - no - nobody would have gone to work untidy. They - he expected his work people to turn out well and they did. He w
a
s a very strict man. But - he seemed to get work people who - responded to him. But I can still hear those clogs you know with their big irons on the bottom. But they were beautifully kept. Nobody ever went out - none of the mill people - ever went out in
 dirty clogs.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about those that worked at the other mills, were they as particular?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well I think some of them were but I just happen to know Mark Oldroyd's best because I passed his - big mill as I went to school. And I would see them when I
 was coming home for lunch. I would see them coming out you know, crowds of them, hundreds of them and it - it was an education to see those - those girls, they were mostly girls, there were men as well. The overseers were men but - I never saw a dirty sc
a
rf - shawl and I never saw a dirty pair of clogs. And one or two of them, when I got older - old enough to be a Sunday school teacher - I - chatted to them about it you know and - they said, wouldn't allow anybody come into out - our works with dirty clog
s
 on. There was a real pride - in their appearance. I expect the others would be with - with the - the better class mills, they would be the same. But I knew Mark Oldroyd's because I passed it four times a day. And of course the streets were cobbled in tho
se days, you know, and you - you heard the clogs. They started work at six. Yes yes. And nobody - nobody resented it. I think they were a lot happier than they are now with their shorter hours. Yes, they really did take a pride in their work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Could you see any difference in the sort of people who went to the Anglican churches and the Catholic churches and the Non-conformists?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well - I think that they - on the whole, the people going to the Anglican church were the moneyed, better class people - on
 the whole. Now Mark Oldroyd and Percy Walker - and I can think of others but the name won't come - went to the - the Non-conformist. But on the whole the people going to the Anglican church were the wealthier people. And - the Catholics were absolute scr
uffy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 They would all be similar types of people to those you've told me about who harassed your Mr Clark?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. That's right. And there was one area, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 Dave}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  Green it was called, now that was a place that we were forbidden to go near. It was very rough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was that a particularly Catholic area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
It was the Catholic - the Catholic community - around the Catholic Church. But - although I've never been a Catholic and never been tempted to be one, I have the greatest admiration for the way th
e Catholics will help in illness. My sister, the one older than myself, had a terribly severe attack of smallpox. Shockingly severe, so severe that she had to have her hands tied so that she couldn't - and she was weeks in hospital. Now the Catholic pries
t
 there, I never understood why a Catholic priest was the only one, our own minister couldn't go and see her, I think perhaps because he had a family and the Catholic priests hadn't, I'm only - I'm only guessing there, but the Catholic priest went every da
y
 for weeks to see her and knew we were anti-Catholic. And came down and reported her condition. She was not expected to live. And of course to a Catholic - to have somebody with you at death who can - hand your soul on to heaven is a necessity and - he sa
i
d that he would see that she was cared for - when the end came. We never thought she would come out of it but she was wonderfully nursed. It was in the public - of course it would be for - for - smallpox. But that Catholic priest never failed. Every singl
e
 day, to go and see her and to come and report. And you realize how, as a family, we were deeply grateful. And he knew when he was coming that he was coming to an anti-Catholic family. But he was - he was a wonderful man. Really wonderful. But it pretty w
e
ll ruined my father's business - the grocery said of it, you see, people wouldn't come near us. The rest of it was all right but that - took - in fact it never did get back to what it had been. And that is where - one sees the difference, anyone connected
 
with the - with the cremations had a big pull, they came and - came with the ambulance to collect my sister - oh, about between eight and nine at night and in those days the streets were crowded - a man who lived quite near to us, his - he was a - draper 
but he was a big cremation, they came at two o'clock in the morning for - to fetch his - it was his dressmaker, his head dressmaker.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You say the streets were full at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh - oh yes. Wednesday and - Wednesday, Saturday and Sunday night I don't
 think I exaggerate if I say you could have walked on their heads and all they seemed to do was to walk - we lived in a place called Daisy Hill, was to walk up to the top of the hill on a normal day it would take you ten minutes or a quarter or an hour to
 walk to the top and then they walked in couples or in groups up to the top of the hill, turned round and walked back and as children our interest used to be to count the same person to see how many times they passed our window.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 They kept going up and down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Up and down, and up and downs all evening. Sunday evening was the worst after the churches closed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of street activities can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well, when }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 you get}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  a crowd like that there are bound to be some rough }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 customers and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  
there - quite often there were fights. And - the shops kept open until ten o'clock at night in those days. And the - public houses were open 'til eleven and at turning out time you quite often got drunken people coming out and one of our pastimes - you' -
- laugh when I call it a pastime - used to keep all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 the old}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 electric light bulbs and - when the rowdies came out of the public house is they came anywhere near, as they did, near our house we - sat at our bedroom windows and threw out the - it was a case of who - who could frighten the drunken men most.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did people or did people show }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 disapproval}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  for other people or particular families or anything like this, did they do anything like banging dustbin lids or doors or anything like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I don't remember anything of that sort. If you'd }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 offended}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 some of these - of course we lived near the centre of the town you see and there were a lot of public houses about you know - and - if you in any way offended them they'd come and shout and bawl outside your
 house. But I don't remember any of them knocking at the door. Might have done but I don't remember it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 The working class people, would you say that they all had the same standard of living or would there be different groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no, there were g
rades. Definite grades. Some of the - of the working class people lived - quite as nice lives as - more ordinary educated people. And they'd a very great pride. And a - the better ones had a great pride in their houses, their houses were beautifully kept 
and that terrible habit of - of scrubbing the flags outside and whitening them, that - that was regularly done. And - their houses - their doorknobs and everything were, you know, they were usually brass knobs and they - they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 shone}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  and shone again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about the lesser ones?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well some of those were rather disgusting. My father and mother had quite a bit of property and as I got older I was rent collector for them and - some of them I used to say to father, turn that - turn that set out - they - 
the house is disgusting. It wasn't clean and - the children didn't know what it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 to sit down to a table, they were given a piece of bread and butter and some jam and ran to sit out in - eating it you know. And I always shall remember amongst that class 
of people, the dirty runny noses. Shocking. And the untidy unkempt hair they had. They didn't seem as if they knew what a brush - hair brush was for.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was there any particular family that you knew well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Like that? Yes, there was one particularly 
in one of mother's cottages. I don't know, there were four or five children but they were always in rags and people were always giving them things. But they simply wore them until they dropped off their back, they never put a - a stitch to them to repair 
them at all. And - the father was a drunkard and I don't think the mother was much better.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did he work at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Intermittently. Intermittently he worked. I don't - I forget what he was. A labourer }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  some kind you know, I suppose it would be with a building firm very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 likely}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  - there were a lot of labourers with building firms. And the - the street cleaners were the - rather low class labourers. There were - I - I well remember - I'd seen my father do it and I got the ha}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 it, stopping and talking
 to some of these folk and - to my amazement one of them had a highly cultural voice, spoke perfect English and I suppose I was - young enough to show my surprise and I can see him now, he was very handsome man though raddled, and he said, you didn't expe
c
t to hear anyone speak like that. And he - he had - he'd been to the University, he had his degree and drink had brought him to where he was. And he told me quite frankly. But - I always stopped and chatted to him afterwards, they were doing some repairs 
on the - on the hill, on the way I went to school you know, but he was a very interesting man. It seemed such a wicked shame. Of course the worst job of all was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  emptying the ash pits. That was a terrible business. I think they - you know they had a - a big place into which all ashes and rubbish went and I think they were only emptied once a month. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 And the way of emptying them was that they climbed in amongst all this and shovelled it out and threw it out into the road and they had a - cart there a
nd - one man would shoveling it out and two men shovelling it into the cart and whenever the refuse men were round all windows were closed and doors were closed, 'cos you can imagine - the refuse from a - a house over a long period like that was terrible.
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was this the day of the cess pools and things like this too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
I don't remember those. No. No, I don't remember those at all. But - the ash bins I do remember. Filth. Ash pits they were. Quite big places too.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was there a distinction felt between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh yes. Very definite. Oh yes, and - I think the labourers were the ones who kept it most alive. They - they - they didn't feel or they didn't act as if they were able to speak to other people. Kept very much to themselv
es. And - if they did speak to anybody else I always felt that they found the filthiest language they could and the broadest words }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  they could. The broadest Yorkshire. They seemed as if they were out to make themselves as offensive in every way as they
 possibly could. I thought so, their attitude seemed to be - to be that and I - in looking back, of course at the time I don't suppose I thought about it at all, but in looking back I think it was a kind - a kind of inverted snobbery. We can't speak like 
you so we'll - we'll let you see the worst we can do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in the different classes and groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, mother was very much more - inclined to - what shall I say - because obsequious is quite wr
ong, there was nothing obsequious about her - but she would show more - what's the word I want - deference. Now my father never showed deference. But mother would show more deference.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did your mother think of herself as belonging to a particular social class do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 She always thought - thought of herself as belonging to a higher class than the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 trades people}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How do you think that was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Because - her - on her mother's side particularly, they did belong to the professional classes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And it would be because of her own home background than because of your father's public position?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 To what extent could and was it possible for people to move up from one class to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 another}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Not very easy b
ecause they were not accepted by the higher class. And in those days the way that you rose was mostly by money. And - they were not acceptable to those who }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 consider}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  themselves the real - aristocracy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Can you remember anybody who did?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Who - who 
- oh yes, yes, quite a few. And - I - I used to feel that they were very silly to try to do it. Because - they were tolerated, they weren't accepted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Might they possibly be laughed at on the quiet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh definitely. And not so much on the quiet. It
 was - they professed they weren't doing it you know but it was done on the sly and you could see it done. Oh yes. One man in particular whom I - knew was - he was rather a rough cut, he didn't speak the King's English, he was an uneducated man but he cer
tainly made money and then he tried to mix with these other people. Well he tolerated more - I felt insulting attitude to him than I can imagine any man }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 with}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  any pride accepting. But that - that's one man in particular I remember, but he was - he was a - a very pushing man you know, wanting to be considered amongst the upper ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 With a rather thick skin?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
A very thick skin. Yes. Yes, a very thick skin. I've heard him make comments - I can't speak the broad Yorkshire but on these lines - don't know
 what he - when he thinks he is, I've as much brass as he had. Now that was his attitude you see. And - the other people well simply they wouldn't accept him, was all. But as you say, he'd got a thick skin. I don't think he was ever nonplussed at all.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh yes. And I can see her now, the one who was the real lady. She belonged to - the upper classes. Her name was Oates, Miss Oates. But she was one of the loveliest people, sh
e was a true Christian in all her actions in life. She was tall, nearly always dressed in black. She was quite good looking. She carried herself very well. I knew her into her eighties. I never heard her say an unkind to anybody. And if she could do a kin
d deed she did it. She was also one of these people who attracted all kinds of people and they always gave her love and they always looked after her. Yes, she was as you say, I've heard it said of her, many times, Miss Oates is a born }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 lady}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . And - I - I'm no
t sure if they were related - there was a Mr Chadwick, a Charles Chadwick. His granddaughter's still, I notice her name in the paper sometimes - he was a - kindly man. He was quite well-to-do, lived in a nice part of the town. He went through an awful lot
 
of sorrow. His young son - fell - I think out of a window but I', uncertain, but he fell on his head when he was a boy of about eight and he was a cripple for the rest of his life. And you never heard Mr Chadwick, I can call his Charles Chadwick, you neve
r
 heard a compliant from him, and he devoted himself to that boy and - nobody would ever dared have offered a word of sympathy to him. And I was going through a very bad period at one time and was rather bitter, in fact I think I must say I was very bitter
,
 and I used to meet him, he was coming down to his office as I was going up to school and sometimes he would stop and have a word and he'd say, now Mary - in any better mind? Say, no. And - well it's time you were. I'd been through a pretty stiff time. An
d
 he said, if you knew the real heart of the people against whom you're so bitter you would very likely be very sorry for them. Never entertain bitterness. If you feel it it's because you don't know the other person. Now I remember that very well, I'm not 
going to pretend that I - that I followed it but it was a piece of advice that I valued. And he'd a lovely face, he'd the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 face}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 of an angel. He was a lovely man. And I don't think anybody had more sorrow in his life than that man had but he was always - he a
lways showed a bright side to the world. And again a man who - if he could do a good turn, he did it. And you never heard and adverse criticism of anybody. If somebody made some adverse comment he could always counter it with something nice that he knew a
bout the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 person.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  Yes. Yes. Miss Oates was a perfect lady and Charles Chadwick was a perfect gentleman.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Remember? Oh yes, regularly. Oh yes, - they were always on - on these busy nights they were always on duty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What did you feel about them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
They - they certainly knew how to keep order and what was more they were highly respected. If a policeman spike to - a young person, that young person obeyed. And I have seen a policeman cuff a youngster too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were you as a child ever }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 threatened}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  by your mother or father that they'd call the policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no. Oh no. No, we were always taught to regard the police as friends. Oh no, there was - there was nothing of that sort of thing.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How do you think that they treated people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
The police? Well we never saw anything but if they had to arrest anybody they - put on the - you fasten them by the hand - the - the handcuffs and walked them off and - I never saw any - any upset about
 it. They just - if the policeman said, they came. That's my - recollections.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you feel that they were very fair with people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. We really respected them. And - always felt that - they would always befriend you if you were in trouble at 
all. That was - of course that was the teaching of my mother and father you see from childhood. We were taught, if you don't do anything wrong the policeman will be your friend. If you do anything wrong then you expect to get into trouble.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was your home your own }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 property}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was there ever a time that you felt they had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh they'd a - I think they'd a struggle all the time we were growing up, you see, because - all of us were - went to - the gra
mmar school and it was in the days when you'd to pay to go - it - it was only latterly that - scholarships were given and - I think at - I think all the younger boys got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 scholarships,}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  I think so. But in our day, we didn't. Father paid for us. And - there w
as - there was never any money to throw about, there was always money for necessities, we were always well clothes, well fed, the home was comfortable, warm and - there was never any question of - be careful, don't out that piece of coal on. There were al
l good fires always you see. And plenty of help. But never - never money to waste.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you know anybody that had to get help from the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4325554\charrsid15878306 Guardians?}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes, I knew two families. And - it wasn't a very nice business. I remember a woman - family in p
articular and it was a very sad case, a woman was left a widow with - four children. And she had to go, as they said in those days, go on the guardians and the man used to come round you know, to visit the home. And - if they happened to have a - a roast 
i
n the oven - or anything that they thought might be considered by the man to be extravagant that was carried out straight away into the back place. Outside the house into the - into the lavatory as a matter of fact, it was an outside lavatory and it was p
u
t out there so that he should neither smell it nor see it. Because they'd get into trouble if they were having food like that. And it wasn't that they were extravagant, they were not. No. No, they were not at all. And - the others, the other family, they 
w
ere rather a big family there but I do think that they were feckless. And - they were wholly on the public assistance, guardians it was called then. And - they were terrified, the - the - one of them liked to smoke and they were terrified lest the man sho
uld smell the smoke from the house and if he did they would have had so much docked of that at once you see. No, it was a very - a very dreadful thing - to have to go on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3028758\charrsid15878306 Guardians,}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  however necessity it was. Where I started was a - a three - part school, you know, there was the infants, and the girls and the boys, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3028758\charrsid15878306 separate,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 yes. And I went to school when I was three. And I took the school pence, but I don't remember how much, it was so much a week to pay and it was a - a council school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was it one of the schools that your father had to visit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
No. No. No, he - he visited the other end of the town. From our house to the school it was every inch of the way up a steep hill. We loved it. I mean, we were taught to like walking. And - of course the old
er ones went you see, I had one two, three older than myself and - the older ones took the younger ones. And - the - the little ones, the three year olds sat on a - a tier of seats, what do they call - bal - the seats went - yes, in - and - no backs to th
e
 seats, just a - and you went up the - you knew which was your row and you went up the steps at the side then went along your row into your place, you had your own place. And - All the work was done on slates, which you duly cleaned by - licking your fing
ers and rubbing them. And - the slate pencils were - sharpened on the steps outside. And you were the very favourite person if you were allowed to go out and sharpen pencils, which you did in the playtime or - scripture time or some - some time like that.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was it a day similar to school hours are now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes. Yes. Nine to four. Nine 'til twelve and then half past one t four. And - there was no question of the little ones being sent home early. You just stayed, that was all. And if you fell asleep wel
l you - you lay down either on the floor or on the seat - only on the seat wasn't a very - a very sensible thing because you were liable to roll off. So - little ones often did fall asleep you see and they just slept on the fl-or and they were left there 
to waken up and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was it all work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh yes. Yes, all work. The - work on the - writing was making pot hooks and then gradually joining them up to make n's and m's, so on, and making ovals, we weren't allowed to make a circle, it had to be an oval 
and then you put a stroke on and you got your b's and your d's and your g's and son forth. That was how you learnt your alphabet and that was how you learnt to write. And - your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 numbers}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  were learnt by - a - a big - card was put up in front with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 numbers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  on and you copied them down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I was as happy as a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 sand boy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . I don't remember not being happy in school. Excepting when I got the cane, which I did. Yes. If you were late for school it didn't matter - the little ones weren't but the older ones w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 ho}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  brought you got the cane for b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 inging you late you see. And you got the cane for bringing the little ones late and then when you went into your own school you got the cane for being late in school, that was just to bad but -
 you put your hand out and - I - I remember so well somebody told me that if you put a hair over your hand it didn't hurt. Well I tried putting - putting two or three hairs out and putting over but I never found it hurt any less.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of things did they give you the cane for apart from coming late?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Poor work. Laziness. Being obstreperous at all. I don't remember really much else.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did they have any other sort of punishments?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, sometimes you were put in a corner, a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 dunce}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  cap put on your head. And that was far worse than being caned. Because you were the butt of the whole school then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was that just for poor work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 It depended upon the teacher. Some teachers - it was for poor work only. If you had been a dunce you see. An
d - with some of them we used to feel, I used to feel, that it was a case of taking it out of you for something or other. I know quite well I shouldn't think that then but in looking back I - I wonder if they - they'd had a poor breakfast or something. Bu
t I know I didn't think on those lines in those days. Teacher was in a bad temper that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What did you feel about the teachers generally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Some of them, lovely. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 
I can remember one headmistress in the infants' room and - I'd have done anything for her. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
She was a lovely woman, she was a lovely woman, she was in the right place. When I moved room the infants at seven into the girls school - the headmistress there I thought was just lazy. She used to sit at her - her desk and she had a - a bottle
 of something we didn't know whether it was brandy or whisky, just inside her desk and she took a nip every now and again and she seldom moved from her seat. And - you did your work and then you exchanged it with one another and - and marked it from the a
n
swer book. She - I - I think she was lazy, she wasn't very strong and she'd a pretty hard life, as I got to know later for I worked for her later, I became an assistant in her school later. She was - very particular and very good in training in manners. V
e
ry good. Quite a lot of things that she taught in that school I remembered for the rest of my life. But - she never bothered herself to teach you much. If you got on well that was all right. There were two other teachers in the school. Again, I think they
 
were splendid, I think they were splendid teachers. And - there were three others and I thought they fitted in with the headmistress. One of them, of course in - it was the day you know of the untrained teacher, very much so - and one of them could have b
e
en a very good teacher but - she was one of the choral society, she'd a beautiful contralto voice, if - if we could get her singing we were as happy as larks. She could sing, and - the inspector came one time and he said to her, now it's time you got your
 certificate. That was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 teacher\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 certificate. Oh, she said, I'm going to get a certificate you know, I - that's what I want. She said, I - I think I've seen the man and I'm hoping to get a marriage certificate before too long. And - that - that was her 
type you know. She - nothing - nothing bothered her very much. I remember an inspector coming in and - there was no grammar on the - on the syllabus - on the timetable and he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 protested}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  about this. And Miss Gazey the headmistress said, my children don't nee
d any grammar. They come from homes where they never hear anything but grammatical speech. So I'm not going to waste my time teaching them grammar. And she never did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 This}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  lady sounds to have been concerned more with your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 behavior}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  than your academic progress?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Definitely. Yes. But her training in behaviour was perfect. She - her whole - attitude was nice it itself, excepting for this laziness you see. And - that didn't bother us very much, we were left alone to get on with it ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What did you think about the nips of brandy and so on coming from a home like yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 It is surprising how much you accept and don't - don't query. It was just Miss Gazey, that was all. We used to laugh about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did your father know about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh yes, he was horrified. And - we had to be very careful, he being on the - on the committee you see. But - he was too wise a man to bring up anything that his children said.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about the other children, did they come from similar types of home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 On the whole they did. We had naturally, amongst them - a number who didn't. But on the whole they came from a good class - home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did the ones who came from different sorts of homes get left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well rather, yes. That was one thing that I don't think Miss Gazey was affair about she encouraged us to be rather snooty to these.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did they actually single out some of the children for special treatment or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, I don't think so. It was more in an aside than anything else. Th
ere was no doubt about it, one knew the children who were disapproved of. But it was more a general attitude than any definite singling out of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 They didn't attempt to single out any for special tuition?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh yes. Did you ever know a school where there were not. And - one gang wouldn't allow anybody else in. That was - that was that gang and - I can't really remember what we did in our gangs, only we kept very much to ourse
lves. And going home from school we went - we always went home for lunch, and - going home from school one gang would be pushed onto one side and the other gang on the other side, you wouldn't walk on the same side of the road as somebody who wasn't in yo
ur gang. No, no, you were very much a gang.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You went on to the grammar school from there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about your experiences there - was that a mixed or single sex school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Single sex, yes. I've never been with mixed school at all. 
Not as a - no, I have taught them you know but never - never been in a from with them. I was very happy indeed at my grammar school and - fortunately - for some reason that I - I - I can't explain, I was good at my work and - it was recognized by the teac
hers so I'd no difficulties you see, I just - just went through.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was that fairly near to where you lived?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 It was the next township, Batley. The Batley girls grammar school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 This involved going by some sort of transport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 We could walk i
f we - if we felt like it but it - we more often went by train. It was - what - it would be a four mile walk and I - I - quite for miles to the school and that really was rather much. Sometimes on very nice days one or two of us would decide we'd like to 
walk and we did walk. But - we had a contract and went by train.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would you be able to get home for lunch then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. Oh no. No. No, but there were - I don't know how many days a week, usually we took sandwiches but certain days in the week there wa
s a - a put - a cookery class and they cooked dinner for all who wanted. And so we had a cooked dinner, I think it was twice a week there was a cookery class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were there any facilities for getting a drink with your sandwiches?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. Only water
. No, only - no. But - we were allowed to go down into town it wasn't very far away and - we weren't compelled to bring sandwiches, we could go down to a caf\'e9
 and we used to get a very light meal there but then we could have a lemonade with that you see, get a lemonade. And I don't know how often, so many times a week one or two of us went down to the caf\'e9
 instead of sandwiches. I remember - my mother would have been horrified if she'd known - we were given so much you see, to get it, and - our favourite meal was a meat pie and you - it wasn't a caf\'e9
 where you were given a knife and a fork and a plate. You just too, it in your hands }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 andante}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 it and - really how - how we survived as we have done. A meat pie and a - vanilla slice afterwards and the friend with 
whom I went didn't like the ice part of the vanilla slice and I didn't like the lower part so I'd have the two top parts of the icing on and she had the two - fortunately mother never asked us what we got. No. Well, she'd say, when we - we'd been you know
, I'd say, well I had a pie. A tuppenny pork pie as they were in those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did you feel about your teachers there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I don't remember any that I disliked in the slightest degree. They were - a very kindly, very efficient, we had to work but 
I didn't mind that. They were kindly efficient people and - took a great interest in us and demanded the highest of us. I - I don't remember any occasion on which I was in disgrace at all at the - at the grammar school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did they attempt to push you on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 If you were promising for university entrance and this sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well, no, not university in those days but - it was - we - we knew pretty well what we were going to do you see and I was going in to - teaching, I knew t
hat, which meant - you had to go at fifteen to - to go as a pupil teacher. And - we taught all day and went to night school for our education. And then before I had finished - they - had - thought that we were being over worked, because I had to be at sch
ool at eight in the morning to have lessons with the headmistress, from eight to quarter to nine. I was always there on eight myself but she quite often wasn't but I had to get on with some work on my own then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was this infants or primary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Primary, yes. Yes, yes, the middle school. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 
And then in the evening you see we went to night school for classes, teachers - especially teachers' classes.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 About how many evenings a week would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Every evening - at first. Then they altered it and w
e had so many - mornings one week, I think it was three and three afternoons the next week so that we didn't have so many evenings and we made up the - the time you see with the evening work but we didn't have to go every evening. 'Cos we were coming home
, I think the classes started at seven, and we were coming home at ten night after night and then have to be at school for work the next day you know. It was - pretty stiff going. I had an excellent headmistress to train me but by }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 Jove}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  she wasn't half a - a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 termagant}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. I - I shall always remember one thing that happened. I was taking - I - I was only a girl of fifteen or sixteen - and I was taking a class and I just don't know - I think it was a mental arithmetic lesson, but I know I said to some of the - the
 children, come along, smarten up. And - it was the days when there'd be a class at that end of a big room and a class at that end and sometimes a class in the middle. But anyway, the headmistress's desk was in the middle of the room, and she was sitting 
t
here and she heard me say this, something - I - I'm not going to pretend I know the exact words but it was something of that nature, come on, liven up. In stentorian tones said - if the teacher would stand properly there might be a class - a chance of the
 
- of the class livening up. And I - you know - I put me studying cap on, I didn't know what I was doing, 'cos I'd always been very erect and I just didn't know what I was doing. Then it - I realized I had a big blackboard by me and I'd put my hand on that
 
and was leaning a little bit on the blackboard. And every week we had to give what we called crit lessons. And - the headmistress came in and the class teacher sat at the side and you gave this crit lesson. And again I remember so well, I was - nervous an
d
 I asked two questions, one following the other, without taking an answer and the headmistress was behind me, she said, if you tell them which one you want them to answer perhaps you'll get an answer. This was all said quite loud you know, the children he
a
rd it as well. They were stiff days. And when it got to the end of the time of your apprenticeship, of course throughout the time of your apprenticeship the inspectors came to watch you teach but when it got to the final you had two inspectors and your he
admistress and the class teacher and you'd to teach for a day with these folk sitting by taking notes. That was an ordeal. It was a real ordeal. But we got through and it made teachers. And we - before }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 we}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  went to college we knew how to handle a class. 'Cos we'd had to.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So then you went to college at London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, I went to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 Stockwell}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  College, yes. Oh well, of course you know, things in those days were very strict. We were in dormitories - a tiny little box of a room with a partition going hall way 
up we could climb over into the next room if - if we wanted. And we often did. And - the - bell went at - seven for wakening. Half past seven you were supposed to be dressed. Quarter to eight you'd }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 boo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  be down in the - in the room for morning prayers. At e
ight o'clock breakfast. And - then you'd go back and make your room - maker your bed, tidy your room and dust it. And then the bell went for lessons. And you had lessons from quarter to nine to I think it was half past twelve, with a break in which you co
u
ld have a cup of milk if you liked. And then afternoons were free, but you must not on any account go our alone. And you must go out at the front door where the matron sat in a little room with a window that she could see that nobody went out alone. And y
o
u'd to go out in - in pairs or more and you'd to come back in pairs. And - what - I think we'd be out by about two and back again for four. And sometimes we had to be back for half past - for three, because we had afternoon lectures. But other days we had
 
to four o'clock. Then we had tea. And then went in for evening lectures. And - you had a common room in which we could all assemble for chatting and so forth, huge room. That was our recreation. And at the weekend - on Saturdays, lessons stopped at half p
a
st twelve I think and those who lived in London, every fortnight could go home and back on Sunday afternoon but those of us who came from a distance couldn't - and still the rule was you couldn't go out alone. And - those of us left in had to sign the boo
k as we went out and sign when we came back.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about your time of coming back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well we - eight o'clock I think was the latest we were - in and if you were - didn't get in until eight you had to sign where you were going to have tea. And when 
you went up to college your parents had to send a list of the people whose homes you might visit, if there were any, go and stay for the fortnightly weekend you see. And the visitors that you might have come to see you in college. And - no man was ever al
l
owed through. Excepting a clergyman and - one girl had a clergyman friend - and she was engaged to him but she didn't let on about that you see and this clergyman could come and see her. It was a - it was a very strict life, very strict. Sundays - we had 
t
o go to service morning and evening unless you got excused, if there was any reason for not going you'd to go to the matron and be excused. And - on Monday morning slips of paper were handed round to everybody and you'd to say which - which church you had
 
been to and - what text the sermon was preached from. Both morning and evening. And however, if you anted to go up into the - into the city - some of us from the North did to hear the big preachers - you'd to walk. You were not allowed to use a bus on Sun
day. And quite early in my time there another girl from the North and myself wanted to go up and hear - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 Sylvester}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 Horn I think it was we went to hear, it doesn't matter, it was one of the big - and I had no sense of direction and this girl had little - litt
le more than I had and - we knew where - how to get to the church and we knew how to get back onto the main road and when we got back Maud said, which way do we go? I said, oh this way. And we went along and - we knew if we were late in there'd be no end 
o
f a row and - we seemed to be going on and going on, we didn't get anywhere we knew so at last I said, I'm going to ask this policeman. So I stopped a policeman and I said, how to get to Stockwell College, can you direct me? He said, right about face, Mis
s
, go back the way you've come. And we got in to time, we had to run and it meant four or five miles. Oh yes, the times were - they were very strict. I was - I've always been fond of needlework and I was doing some embroidery and I was expecting a visitor 
a
rriving and I was going out to tea, it was one of my approved visitors you see, I was going out to tea, it was a cousin as a matter of fact but a cousin much older than myself. And - we used to put a - up a notice on the notice board that - you'd be found
 
in such and such a place you see. So that when they came the matron could come and tell you. Well I got tired of waiting, so with my needlework in my hand I walked along to the entrance to see whether anything had happened that they hadn't - I hadn't been
 
fetched and I ran into one of the - mistresses, one of the lecturers and she stopped, Miss White, she said, there is a proper place for a needle work and it is not the corridors of the college. If you want to do needlework go back into the proper room for
 
it. Oh yes. Were great times. One evening it was all Souls night and a - a number of us agreed that we would go down and meet under the clock, you meet under the clock and if you stand perfectly quiet you see the face of the man that you are going to marr
y
 and of course it - at nineteen and twenty that was quite an exciting thing you see. But we'd be there - to be there at midnight which of course was quite forbidden. Nobody could be out of their room after half past nine, but four of us went down, we risk
e
d it. And - imagine our horror when we heard a door open, we knew who's it was, it was Principal's, we heard the door open, we were standing on a sort of alcove here with the clock straight over us and her room was just there. Well we didn't know what to 
d
o but we'd all put on dark dressing gowns and we flattened ourselves, she had to pass us, we flattened ourselves against the wall and she passed and went along. But you're never going to make me believe she didn't see four figures standing there. But she 
w
as a wise old lady - dame, she was a wonderful woman, a really wonderful woman. And we heard nothing about it. But - we none of us believed that we hadn't been seen. Of course it was dark, there were no lights you see. But - who - who could pass by and no
t
 see four - we - we turned our faces to the wall, but then there was eye - eye down, oh no, she acted wisely that night I think and let us - go. She went along with a - a guest that she'd had. No, she was a - she was a wise old bird. I had to go to her on
 
one occasion. I got a - a letter from home that was very distressing. My mother and father were both in bed ill and my sister, the one who lived older than myself was very inadequate and she had written to say that she didn't know how in the world to carr
y
 on. So - I went to Miss Mander, the Principal, and I told my tale and said, would she give me leave to go home? And see if I could make some arrangements about - getting help in to look after mother and father whilst they were ill. And I just said, I sai
d
, my sister is there but, I said, she can't cope. So she looked at her diary and I could have so many days, she told me. And I ought to have Miss Manley better, I said, well I'll do my best Miss Manley, to be back on that date. She said, Miss White, you w
ill be back on that date. And I was. Oh yes, she was a - she was a lovely old dear. And a very gifted woman. We owe a lot to her. She was a wonderful woman. Anybody who had been under miss Manley had reason to thank their lucky stars. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 She was one of - biggest influence in my - in my - scholastic days, of all the people I knew and it wasn't that she really seemed to very much but, everything she did was to the point. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, she was a wonderful woman. I've nothing but the highest regard for her. And been dead ye
ars. And - she - college - the head of a college, she - wore the little lace caps that old ladies wore in those days. Always a beautiful white cap on and a black bow either just in front there or just at the side there and - she was very stout but very st
ately. She was a lovely woman. Very lovely.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What did you feel about the lecturers in general?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Some of them lovely, some of them very futile. The - the speech training mistress - she - she took poetry and - and speech training and - oh she was wishy-washy. Very wishy-washy. She was taking a test one time and we strongly }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 objected}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 to - some of her - comments and markings and there was one person whom we knew was a real favourite with her, what was the - she was gone on her, the - the girl was gone o
n the mistress, I think that was what they - we used to say, I don't know, but anyway - the girl would have - she really and truly would have done anything, she was stupid. And - this girl got such a high mark and such high comment and - we showed our dis
a
pproval so she said, you don't think I'm fair? We said, no, we don't. So she said, well - what's your objection? So we made our objection. But, she said, I forget the girl's name - she - she has a naturally good trained voice, of course she will do things
 
like that. So I said, you're - I don't as I said it, but amongst us we said - you're not supposed to be judging her as a good trained voice - she was a singer so she had a well trained voice - you're supposed to be judging her on what she has done as a st
u
dent here. So you want me to penalise her then because she has a good voice? We said, we want you to judge her on what you're supposed to be judging. And - you know, she - she hadn't the guts to tick us off. It was after all a piece of impudence on our pa
r
t. But she - she just hadn't the guts. We loved to go with her swimming, she went - she professed to be very fond of swimming and - we always chose her as the drowning person to be rescued and did we love it, because you know with a drowning person that y
o
u're going to rescue you've go to shove them down and then get them onto the - she did get some shoving down. I think we all - we all felt that was the one way we could get our own back on her. But we - and we certainly didn't - we'd no respect for her. I
t wasn't a case of - disliking - I suppose we did dislike her but we certainly had no respect for her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 In general did you have respect for the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. And they deserved it. There was one - she was a funny old thing but she was grand. She
 knew her subject, she was the English lecturer, she knew her subject and she knew how to get it across to you. But she had rather a funny, her teeth were a little bit prominent and - she used to tick them together as she spoke and we always }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 christened}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  her bunny. She was never known as anything but Bunny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was there any social or recreational life in the college?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 In the college - amongst ourselves, but - once - twice a year, once at Christmas and once at the Easter, the end of Easter term I think 
it was, the seniors got up a play with the juniors as their - and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 vice}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 versa and we did some very good play too. Very good ones - we were very fond of the Gilbert and Sullivan and we used to produce those and we had some very good voices. Some really well 
trained voices. I remember the seniors did - what's the one about the sailors in the Gilbert and Sullivan - Pinafore. And - they did that one time, it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3028758\charrsid15878306 beautifully}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  done and do you know we - we weren't allowed to spend money, we had to make do with thing
s that we could collect amongst ourselves, excepting for paper, we could buy paper to make dressed and things. Yes, that was very good and - when I was a junior our year gave the Pirates of Penzance. And - the - the girl who was the producer was an excell
e
nt singer, she was a concert singer and she took the main part you know and she - just beautiful. And we were all well trained too, my goodness, we did have to put time in. One of the funny things, this is - passing from that - you - meals in college are 
r
ather - not - carbohydrates and you put on weight terribly and - we - we found that we were really - we were really getting fat and so we organized skipping and went out into the - it was a yard, we - it wasn't - we hadn't any garden and - skipped. And so
mebody counted so - to make sure you did the full lot and you'd to skip for so many minutes. By }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 Jove}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 it works. We soon got our weight down very nicely. But it was funny. I always think it's very very funny that at that age we liked midnight feasts. Really a
t nineteen, you can - you can expect twelve and thirteen year olds, but at nineteen I think were - we were a bit daft but parcels used to come from home you know and you got your own little group together and - we daren't make tea - or coffee. We - 'cos w
e
'd nowhere - except in the kitchens which were down four storeys. By the time we got them up, it would - if we'd dared to - to go. We might have got one of the maids to help us but it would have been cold before we'd got up. But - four or five in a - in t
h
ese little boxes of rooms you know, sitting on the - on the bed and terrified of making a sound. I remember once, I think it was my birthday, we were having one and my mother had sent me a very nice parcel, there were five of us there and - I don't know w
hat happened but one of them bumped and down came a picture. Oh such a clatter. And - every - every corridor had the mistress - mistress's room on and I heard our mistress - I think that's Miss Whit's room, will you report to me tomorrow morning. But -

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What was your report?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well I went in and apologised you see. They - they were very sensible about it, very sensible. We were always told, well see it doesn't happen again. Well it didn't happen for a little while.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You had a final exam after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes. Yes. Yes. I got a very nice certificate with - with - distinction in all three of the English language, literature and composition. Was very pleased with that because - I didn't care about anything else so long as I did - but what amazed me 
was we - we had to give practice lessons you know and again there you'd have a whole form of - of pupils who sat behind - the class was there and these pupils were behind with their notebooks, on one side was the method mistress from the college and the o
t
her side was the Principal and the class teacher and the headmistress, all scribbling down notes about you. Coo. I - I always said anybody who had been through - a period as a pupil teacher and then at college you oughtn't to be afraid of anything in scho
ol.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have a teacher practice period at college?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes. Yes. We had - I - I don't know if it was a week or a fortnight every term, that we had to go in and then we had our own practice in school and if anybody was ill in the school, any memb
er of the staff then some of the - one of the pupils, one of the students would be sent in to take their place, so we got a lot of practice. And it was the headmistress of the practicing school that - pushed me into teaching arithmetic. I don't like it, I
 
don't like teaching it but - in her report she said I was - gifted as an arithmetic teacher. Well that meant wherever I went I had to teach arithmetic. And it isn't really very interesting to teach. It's easy to teach because a thing's either right or it'
s
 wrong but it's not an interesting subject. English is much more interesting but much more difficult to teach. We had a poetry exam every year and - one of the H.M.I's came to - to hear we all had to go and - we'd our own choice, and then it - we gave him
 
a list the poems we were supposed to know and he would choose what he wanted out of them. And - I shall always remember one that I - one of those that I said was Duty. By Wordsworth. Ooh, I must have been draft, 'cos it's a difficult poem. However, I said
 
it. He gave a big sigh, he said, what a serious lot of people you are here in the - Stockwell College. He said, I've heard more serious poems in this exam than I'd hear in a half a dozen colleges. So I - I said well the next one who's coming after me, I k
n
ew who it was, I said, you won't get anything serious there. And - she was a - a real - mischievous person and - she - she started with Up the airy mountain, down the rushy glen, we daren't go a - hunting for fear of little men. And I was just going out a
s
 I heard Alice beginning it and I looked back and - there was such a relief on his face. Poor man, he'd listened - listened to such a lot of it. Yes, it was very - it was an interesting time, a very interesting time. Of course we - we were always very obe
dient you know and went out in two twos and came back in twos and we didn't expect any body to ask us what we'd done in between whiles. I had a friend at St John's college, the - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 men
\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  college, we'd both of us come from Dewsbury and - we used to corresp
ond. There was never any - anything more than - normal friendship you know, but we both came from Dewsbury and we used to meet occasionally and - he - wrote and asked me if I would go so - I wrote back, I said, yes, I'll - I'll come, but I said, don't you
 dare let anybody know you've got a Stockwell girl there because, I said, if it got back to our - to our Principal I should be expelled. Going to a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 men\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  college, coo. 
\par At twenty-one. However, I went and saw round his college and he said, can't I come back?
 I said, you wouldn't be allowed in. I said, no - nobody in trousers is allowed inside our place. They don't - don't deal in things like that. One girl was found with her fianc\'e9
, it was a silly thing to do because she knew that they were very strict but she went out onto the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 fire}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 escape you know, the - the - outside the rooms there was this - and - she went out and met him at the foot of the steps, but she might have known she'd be caught, but she was expelled straight away. Yes. Yes, she was. And there was
 nothing wrong in it. Excepting that she was disobeying rules. Fire practice was fun. We had the fire escapes outside and we had chutes. We had to come down head first. Oh it was a - it was an awful ordeal. If I was right in the top and this chute, you kn
o
w, you - you know, a big sack sort of thing - strong, that was fastened at the top and - two members of staff or two of the senior girls held it at the bottom and you got in and you shot down and - ooh it was an awful experience. It really was. But it was
 
all part of the fun. We were allowed to go out - in parties to lectures. But - it was only when the principal knew who was giving the lecture and knew where the lecture was. Always a member would be in with - didn't go with us but was in the lecture hall 
s
o - she knew what time the lecture was over, therefore she knew what time we ought to be in. None of us, well I don't know, I was going to say none of us ever ought to have gone wrong, you hadn't the change to go wrong there but I should think a lot of us
 
have had the desire to since leaving, they were so strict. Though you accepted it you know. It was - it was part of the routine. There had been a time when the boys college - and ours, had had a - a dance. One year at our - one term at our college, one te
r
m at theirs and something of this sort had happened that a girl and boy had been found on their own together you see out in the grounds and it was stopped then and there, never allowed again. Oh yes, we were brought up on very strict - this one I've been 
-
 this girl I've been telling you of who - who said the poem, up the airy mountain, down the rushy glen, she came down - down to breakfast one morning with her hair all in Victorian little curls, it must have taken her a generation to do it, and - she was 
a
t our table and - we daren't laugh you know because - everything was very decorous you see. And she came and she - she sat next to me and I was spluttering, absolutely holding - holding it in and I suddenly caught sight of her and said, ooh, look at Alice
.
 And you see the staff had their table on a raised platform. There was dead silence in the room. Absolutely dead silence. And - Miss Manley stood up, the Principal, and she said, will the person who was so forgotten herself as to call out like that in the
 
dining room see me after breakfast? So of course the poor girl who had called out had to go, but Alice went with her, with these curls. It was very brave of her but she went, she naturally would, went and said, I was responsible for it Miss Manley. But - 
Miss Manley said, she ought to have more control over herself and you ought not to be so silly. Go and get your hair done properly. That was all. There was nothing further you see. You shouldn't set me talking of these old days.
