 I tell you that, after I was appointed the Chairman said, I forget the name of the head now, Miss so and so will take you and show you the school and show you the room that you'll work in and as we walked up the path she stopped and she said, now Miss Wh
i
te, over this archway in - in letters of gold I want you to see as written, abandon hope all ye who enter here. And that was my introduction. She was a terror. The real - old style teacher. She worked like a galley slave and we had to do the same. When an
 inspector came round she'd poke her head inside the door and say, mind your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 demeanor}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 , mind your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6966429\charrsid15878306 demeanor}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
, I can hear her voice now saying that. I looked round and wondered what in the world she was talking about you know. At the end of a lesson she was a v
ery forceful teacher, very active and her hair was done in a bob at the back you know and as she talked she was - moved actively and her hair pins flew this way, that say, the other way and at the end of every lesson she stopped and said, now, pick up all
 
those hairpins, and the youngsters would go down on their hands and knees and pick up the hairpins and give them to her and - she screwed her hair round and jabbed the - no, she didn't spare herself at all. She was downright foolish, wrong. She'd keep the
 
children in in the dinner hour. We had from twelve to half past one and I've seen, it was a - mining and - you know, a - a real - Yorkshire town, industrial town, and I've seen parents come in furious at half past twelve, she still would have a group of p
eople in who hadn't pleased her and she was - she was working. It wasn't that she sat and looked at them, they'd got to work with her but I've seen the fathers - the mothers }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 daren't}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  come - the fathers would come in and - come on Tommy, come on. Your dinner'
s spoiling. And she would say, these children go when I tell them. He said, oh no they don't, they come when I tell them. Poor children.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did they suffer often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No, she hadn't that about her at all. But - she tried to - brow beat the fathers
 you know and of course she was - she was dealing with the wrong set of people. Go from Dewsbury to Elland and I left home at seven o'clock in the morning to get to school for nine. Really - what I ought to have done was to have taken rooms there but I kn
ew quite well I shouldn't stay. I was there just three months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You knew you wouldn't stay right from the start?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Right from the very first week I knew that wasn't my atmosphere. And - oh - she was a devil. She'd come in in the dinner hour, we had 
to stay, most of us came from a distance, and she'd say, an hour and a half I know, quarter an hour's enough for you to get your lunch and then find some school work to do. My - she did the same herself. She - she - really hadn't any indulgence I should t
hink except in driving folk to work. I don't think she'd me mother's bit of self indulgence. She was a terrific worker.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How many other teachers were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Four. Five with me and the headmistress. It was a - a junior school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What were the other teachers like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Terrified to death of her. They had been there for a long time and - they wanted to be near home, they could go home easily you see and - so they - they just stuck it. And I'm afraid I wasn't made of that caliber.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did you find them to get on with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Very, very nice. I think really rather glad to have somebody who would defy her. I hope always in a respectful way, but I just wasn't going to be browbeaten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Apart from not being happy with her, how did you feel about the teaching itself in that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well - to anyone's who's just come back from college with all their high ideals you had it was absolutely opposed to everything that I'd ever been taught as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 worthwhile}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  and it was opposed to anything that I had seen
 in my apprenticeship. It - it lacked everything that I considered education. It was drive, drive, drive and no attempt whatsoever to get the children to work with you. You drove them. And if the children got things wrong and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 ninety-nine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  cases out of a hun
dred, not because they hadn't tried but because they couldn't do it, they got a thrashing. The cane was always - she taught with a cane in her hand. To me, looking back, she was the last person in the world who ever ought to have been in a school. But she
 
got results. In that she got - scholarships, you know, for the grammar school but it was not from educational methods, it was by driving things in. And any thought of the children working with you - and being spoken to as human beings didn't exist with he
r.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would these children have known any other school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So it would be impossible to tell -?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Whether they resented it? No, you couldn't tell. But of course I - well I'd been a pupil teacher for four years and after that those four
 years the last two years I'd had my own class and been responsible for it. I'd been, as I'm sure I mentioned when I was talking of the college, the college that one just goes down on your knees and gratitude for such a wonderful place and our handling of
 children just wasn't that and what was more I found the children responded to me beautifully. And they - they didn't get any bawling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You then got another job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. My old headmistress, under whom I had been as a - as a child, had a vacancy. And
 - I knew the vacancy was coming and I went up - and saw her and - said I was going to put in an application and so she said, if you're - if you're applying Mary, you'll get it. So I said, well I can't stay where I am. And - I started at the school straig
h
t away. I didn't even work out a months notice. No. No, I wrote to the West Riding and asked - I said, there would have to be a supply teacher in one of the schools and they hadn't advertised the post, would they release me and put a supply teacher in thi
s school and let me go and take on the new job I'd got. They were very good, they let me go.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was it the same authority?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No, it was a Dewsbury authority. But, you see, I had been in known in Dewsbury because I had worked there for the four ye
ars and had got - good results all the way through and excellent - reports from the inspector so I wasn't even interviewed for this - this post, I was just - just given it, whether anybody - I don't think it was ever advertised. I was just appointed. But 
as the - the clerk said, I was known and my qualifications were known, there was no need to interview me you see. And I stayed there for the next seven - six and a half years and then I got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was the job all that you expected it to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh 
yes, I knew it would be, I knew where I was going. And - my head fortunately, and I were on very good terms and - she knew I would do the job and she left me - let me do it. But when I tell you that - it was just the end of the school year before people w
e
re leaving and my first class in this school was the older children, I had the - the top class, it was a through school and I had a hundred and ten children in the class. That lasted until March, which was the end of the school year in those days and then
 those who were - eligible to leave you see, but - I never had less than seventy in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did you manage with a hundred and ten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well you divided them up into groups. And worked the group system. And - it was only in a few lessons that there was 
any - giving a lesson to the class. You would set the - set work for the groups and then you went round amongst the groups and saw what they were doing. And inspectors came in one time. And I had, it was a needlework lesson she came in to watch and in tho
s
e days, you won't know anything about this, in those days we drafted patterns from measurements that we took, our own measurements you see and cut out a paper pattern in striped paper and you can imagine how it - rattled you know and - and one - one secti
o
n were doing the patterns, another section were cutting out garments from the patterns that they had cut out. Another section had got them going and were tacking and another section were making the garments, they - we had to do it you see in - in his like
 
that. And then the rest of them were doing mending. And I - I had the top class and - I expected them to bring mending from home so that they really and truly were doing the job, not pretending to do it. And they - they had socks and underclothing and so 
o
n. And - she stood and looked at them and then she turned to me, you don't know how you stand this Miss - Miss White, all this noise. Rattling of paper. The scissors going and so on and so on and so on. I said, nobody asks me how I do it but it's there to
 do and I've got to do it and, I said, you are the people who are responsible for these conditions. So she went to my headmistress and said that she thought I had got a very - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 independent}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 , I don't know what else she said about me, person in that top room. So Miss Gazey, said, yes, she is. But, she said, she works and she gets the results. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 So she told her what I had said, that it was the - the board that was responsible for us having to work under conditions like this and my - my head was a - she was a very l
oyal to her staff, she'd - she'd have protected us if we'd needed it, you know, through thick and thin. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
She said, well, do you disagree with that? The - the inspectors they had in those days were not people, this was Sir Goff's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 niece}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  and Sir John Goff was 
a big man at the board of education you see a do it was the board of education in those days, not the ministry, and - she - she'd never been into a - a school, she didn't no any - anything at all about what conditions were like the working in there you kn
o
w. Very high and mighty. We all roared when - well no we didn't roar laughing, that's not true - but we were all very thrilled and very pleased. She came to the school one morning and - it was assembly, she came right away at the beginning, they didn't us
u
ally because the first half hour we were not to be supervised or inspected, it was the - prayers and scripture period and the - the board of education's nothing to do with that. That was our own. But her, she arrived and Miss Gazey was taking prayers and 
we had a very mixed set of children there, mostly from quite }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 reasonably}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 classed homes but some from very poor homes and there was one little mite who had some buttons off her dress and in front of the whole school this inspectress called her out and pointed
 out to her that she was old enough to stitch buttons on and she should have more self respect than to come like that. That was in front of the full school, we were blazing. Because we didn't believe our children should be show up like that. But - she cam
e
 a day or two later - and this same child who was a very quiet retiring child had got guts enough about her to put up her hand and - again it was - it was assembly and Miss Gazey said, what's the matter? She said, the inspectress had got a button off her 
coat. We loved it - absolutely loved it. I thought that - that was really grand.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you tend to have the same inspector coming all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well, not all the time but for - they were - they were appointed to a district for quite a - a while. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 O
ne thing happened, Mr Ridge and Mr Thorpe came together to in - two H.M.I.'s and we had the boys department, the infants department and the girls department an they - if an inspector arrived the head of that department sent somebody round to the other sch
ool to say Mr Ridge is here, or Mr Thorpe is here. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
One particular morning, Mr Ridge arrived at the boys school. And Mr Shaw, the headmaster just sent a - a child round - boy round and he said, please Miss Gazey, I've come to tell you that Mr Ridge is arrive
d at our school, Mr Thorpe was in our school. So he said, that's very nice, now will you tell Mr Shaw when you go back that Mr Thorpe is busy with Miss Gazey. We thought that was lovely you know. Because of course you weren't supposed to give - make any p
r
eparation for them coming at all but naturally we'd send word. Oh it was funny. But they were very understanding on the whole. They - they knew - this woman didn't. She never ought to have been on the inspectorate, she never ought to have had anything at 
a
ll to do with council schools. She'd been educated privately all the way through and that was all she knew about education. She never would have been in the post if she hadn't had - influence behind her you see. But the - on the whole the men who came rou
n
d, they were very - very understanding. I remember one man coming and I was taking needlework, I said, it's a needlework class, I don't suppose you want to see anything they're doing, you won't know anything about it. So - oh he'd such a nice way - he sai
d
, well I'd like to see Miss White. So he went round to look and I listened very amusedly, he knew all about it. He knew what the different stitches were and he talked to the children intelligently about it. He'd a real twinkle in his eye when he came back
.
 So I said, well you certainly know more than I thought you would. No, they - inspectors - no, when you're trying to teach them. I remember one man coming in and - he wanted to see the arithmetic books including the practical arithmetic books which were d
r
awing as you know and so I just turned to the girl who was monitor of the - for that week and I said, just bring all, I told her, the arithmetic books and the practical arithmetic books. So I put them down in front of him, the whole pile as they were and 
I
 said - now I don't know what his name was - there are good, bad and indifferent there. That's the whole - the lot for the whole class. So he looked up and he said, well that's what most classes are isn't it, good, bad and indifferent, but, he said, it's 
surprising how I find the indifferent and the bad are very - usually sorted out and put away, I don't see those. Oh well, I said, you've got the lot there, they'll keep you busy for a while. No, it was lovely work though. Really lovely work.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you leave when you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Oh }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 women weren't acceptable. It was only in - very few cases that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 women were acceptable. They were glad to have us back again when war broke out you know, the 1914/18 war. So - I went back, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 To the same school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, no, we'd - when I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  I went to Leeds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So you taught in Leeds then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes, just - just for five months. And then we moved on to Manchester. My husband was moved, he was a lecturer and he was - moved. A lecturer in the temperance work and he was moved to Manchester so of course we'd to move you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you then teach in Manchester?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No. My babies were tiny then you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Have you done any jobs since the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh I - my husband became a
n invalid and I - I brought the family up, I had to provide for the family. And - and always to - enabled me to get a job but you're getting past 1918 now you know. You don't mind. Well I had to fill up a from and have it signed by a doctor that my husban
d was unable to work and that I had to work to provide for the family. And - back came the reply to this that I was a - appointed for another year and I was on a yearly basis until is death.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was this in Manchester?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. We went from Manchester to London. And then London back to Manchester he came and I went into Atherton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So you taught for about five months in Leeds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And then you taught next in London?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 In London next, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 For about how long?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Two years. Two to 
three years. But it was supply work. I went on - I was kept going you know because that - that was during the war years. And - they needed us and - it didn't matter whether you were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  or not if you were a - a teacher you could get a job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Which war are we talking about now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 1914/18.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 We moved back to Atherton. That was in 1922. Yes, I got a - I got a -a permanent post then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 In 1922.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. And I taught from 1922 until 1946 when I retired.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 In Atherton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. Five years in Atherton - five and a half years in Atherton. Five and a half years too long.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Then I went to Oldfield, which is on the other side of the valley from Howarth. And then - I was there for ten years - and then - I was a 
head then, I got a head of a little school and - then I - moved to between Halifax and Queensbury, Katherine Slack. And - a head teacher there and I was there until I retired.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 The supply teaching, was that in primary schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And your teaching after that continued in primary schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Are there any particular points about the supply teaching during the war that you feel are interesting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well I think it was all interesting and it was all good practice for me bec
ause you had to be prepared to go wherever you were sent. So that I got into all kinds of schools and one school in particular I remember was - near the Elephant and Castle in London which was a very down at heel district you know. And - the school was a 
t
hree storey building. The infants were on the first floor, the girls on the second floor and the boys on the top floor and I was sent to the boys school. And - the men there were - they were awfully nice to me, and one man took me on one side, we - the wh
i
stle went and the - the children assembled in lines in the playground with the teacher in charge of her own class and then you in turn took your classes up - up all these stairs you see and you can imagine you - you had to keep your eyes glued on a lot of
 
rough boys from a district like the Elephant and Castle, and I started lead - waiting and having the boys in front of me and going up behind them, this man, absolute gentleman he was, drew me on one side, he said, Mrs - I was Mrs Hatch by then you see, I 
w
ould like to suggest to you that you lead the boys up. So I said, I shan't know what they're doing behind me. So he said, no, but they'll be another class following up. But, he said - I said, well now tell me why, I know there's some reason for it. He sai
d
, well you know - many of these boys have got no seats in their trousers. They don't mind us men seeing it but they'll be very uncomfortable if a woman does. They were so poor. And - it was a really old fashioned building, a huge, huge fireplace and a bal
c
ony - arrangement of sets in front and - I - you have to feel your way with each school you go to and if there was a tiresome by I thought well if I have him near me I can - deal with him, but if he's right away at the back there, because again these were
 
fifty and sixty classes you see, if he's right away at the back there I can't deal with him. So I got into the way of saying, all right young man, come down and stand here by me. But to my amazement they continued being tiresome and being brought down. Of
 course I - I saw what it was then. The little souls were cold and it was lovely come and stand by the teacher by the fire. You - you -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did you counteract that one then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well I - I sent them back again. I told them, I said, it's much too comfortable for you - for you here. I sent them back again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What did you feel about these poor children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh it was shocking. It was shocking. You just ached, instead of teaching them, to have a pack of clothes and a nice big hot bathroom that you c
ould go and give them a good tubbing and clothe them in decent clothes. But they were good tempered little chaps. I said to this man who'd been so kind to me from the beginning, I said, tell me, what's the matter in my room, I said, there are - there are 
l
ittle bits hanging down from the ceiling, does it want - redecorating, because during the war things didn't get done. So he put back, his head and laughed, he said, haven't you twigged yet what that is? I said, no, I've been looking at it for a fortnight 
a
nd I', still in the dark, So he said, wee - do you ever have plasticine lessons. I said, I haven't had yet, I'm not very keen on it. So he said, well when they have a plasticine lesson they get a ruler and they put a piece of plasticine on the end and sna
p the ruler and - see who can get the plasticine onto the ceiling and they manage fairly well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of reaction was expected from you on those sort of occasions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well - I was a long time before I took a plasticine lesson. They had other thin
gs that weren't quite so easy and - you - they quickly you're your attitude to them. I don't say this }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 boastingly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 because I'm thankful - very thankful - I do think that I was cut out for a teacher and I always could get on good terms with my class and then 
they work with you. I - that was my objection you see to my first school, it was all drive, drive, drive. You weren't expected to get on decent terms with -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 With these poor children in the Elephant and Castle area, did you come across the parents at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of people were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 They were shocking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 In what sort of ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well they were - they were down at heel, I don't think they could help it you know, I don't think they got money and I wasn't - I think I was a
bout five months in that school and - that isn't long enough to get to know a big area like that you know, I was busy getting to know my children in school. But I was going out of the playground one day and to this day I don't know what I'd done, but a mo
t
her with rat tail hair hanging down and dirty face and dirty hands and torn clothes met me at the door and shouted obscene language at me. Fortunately again my guardian angel, this man, was coming out just behind me and he came up and joined me and he sai
d
, what's the trouble? Well we neither of us found out what I'd done wrong. But I had this woman's child in my class and something had upset her and - I always remember her expression, I'll rive every hair off your head. And ; this man just said, he said -
 
I don't think Mrs Hatch that you've ever realized the sort of district you're in. So I said, well really, one can't be in the school without knowing that and, I said, I do come from Waterloo Station her every day you know. So he said, yes, I know you do, 
b
ut he said, you know we've got some terrible characters here. And - he fortunately went to Waterloo station as well so from that time onwards we both sort of caught the same train. He really was - I - I wasn't frightened but that was my ignorance. It wasn
't bravery on my part. But he really was frightened that this woman would get a gang of women and attack me. They never did. I had no - no trouble in that way. That was the only incident that I remember.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you see anything of the fathers of any of the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. You see, they would be - at work. Or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would they be labouring types of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. I should think at the docks or road men. I'm only guessing - but that's what I should imagine that they would be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Then you went to the school at Everton in 1922, you had a little gap after this London school did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
No. I came - no, I came straight away. Yes I - well I realized you see, my husband's health - had gone, the doctor told me that he wouldn't be able to work and - he 
- he never settled in London, he didn't like it. Of course I loved it. But - it was - what was going to keep him happy that mattered most and we came - I - I got - vacancies - a vacancies schedule and applied for any school that I - that was within reason
able reach of Manchester.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was that his home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
He - no, no. Halifax was his home but - the people were keeping him on still to do - light - he didn't go out to do any speaking but he - he - worked a little bit in the office. Just for - well he - we
 left London in February and he stayed on at the office until June and then he had to give up altogether. And by that time I was settled in - Everton.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were you at the same school in Everton all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 All the time, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would you have preferred any other type of occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Than teaching? If I had my time to come over again I would go into teaching. I retired in 1946, I was back in teaching, I couldn't get into a - not in the area I was in - I couldn't get into a - a state school, 
but I went into private school teaching and - I taught from them until I came here when I was eighty. The year I was eighty I moved here because the family thought it was time I was nearer to them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was this private school up at Robin Hood's Bay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You told me to remind you about your night school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh that was back at Dewsbury before I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . They - night schools were - you know, they were the thing in those days because children left school they could leave school when they we
re twelve and they were encouraged to go to night school and - the Principal of the - of the Technical College that we attended as pupil teachers asked me if I would start one at the school and we started with, I think it was eight, I think you couldn't h
a
ve less than eight, and - well, we - we just managed to keep it going through the - the winter session. We started in September and went on until the Easter following. And - I was depressed about it, it - we didn't seem to be getting anywhere but - I want
e
d to make a go of it. Oh we introduced all sorts of things, I had gone throughout the winter to Wakefield to classes for night school teachers and I'd done domestic science there so I started a domestic science and - from the first year, and I can't be su
r
e what that year was, I think it was the first year I was out of college, 1907, I think but I'm not - I don't think it - 1908 would be more likely - and - we built that school up from those very small beginnings until we had well over a hundred girls comi
n
g. And I had four assistants in the school and it was such a happy experience and - the West Riding I've always found a very good - if they find that you're interested and will work you're left to work on your own lines. I had a man on the staff and he ar
r
anged - we had - we - it was only girls, he arranged for the girls to go down a coal mine and - for the domestic science I couldn't see the girls doing any good in the - wretched school desks because they were the long desks you know, six could sit on a d
e
sk, no comfort there wasn't and there couldn't be any interest for those girls to set a table when that was all we had to set a table. So I took them, my own home was only about ten minutes walk away and we had lessons in my mother's home you know. We - w
e
 set tables and we made out menus and we polished furniture. And - all - all that sort of thing and the - the school did build up. Then we started a - typing and shorthand class. Of course I - had to get a teacher for that but - we had - the inspectors br
o
ught people - from all over the county to see our school. It was - it was a wonderful - experience. And the girls were older you see, they were - well, most of them had left school at twelve so they'd be thirteen, fourteen, we kept them up 'til they were 
sixteen and - it was interesting work. Very interesting.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What was the whole range of the subjects that you covered then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well we -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you cover sort of continuation classes in English and arithmetic?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes, we'd English and arithmetic. Those had to be the basic subjects, we had to take }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 those}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. Anything else that we took was in addition so we - we started with our English and arithmetic which I took my self and - we had P.T. and as I told you we had the - the shorthand and typing and -
 we had dressmaking, I got a dressmaking teacher to come and - the girls made some beautiful things for themselves under her tuition you see. I forget what this man was who was so - what did he take? Do you know I don't know. But he was - he was so keen t
hat - he arranged all kinds of outside - activities for them. And I do remember that he - he took them down a coal mine. He }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 wanted}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  me to go as well and I'd }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 have}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 loved to go but for some reason I just couldn't - couldn't make it but - it really was a live hive and - nobody had to be made to work, we all worked together and - I think everybody loved it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of basis did the girls come on, did they have to come so many evenings a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes, and it was all evening work you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would the English and arithmetic be compulsory subjects?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Compulsory for all of them. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And then did they have an option amongst the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 The option of the others, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were they preparing for an exam like the City and Guilds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes.
 The - well the - it wasn't - it wasn't the City and Guilds but - there was a - a county council exam at the end of the time. And inspectors of course visited as they always do. Yes, I loved my evening school work.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would you find a very different atmosphere in the classes from the day school teaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well, yes, because the girls were older you see, they'd been at work all day. They were - they were adults. And we formed a library. I was fortunate in having lots of friends who were also interest
ed and gave me books and then the West Riding are very generous in that sort of thing. We had books from their library. So that we encouraged the girls to read. There was a boys department but that was - that was in the boys section you see, they didn't m
ix. I mean we didn't have boys and girls together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 This was in the school that you taught in during the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No. No, it was in a separate premises altogether. It was another school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 A school that was a day school by day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, quite
 and a night school in the evening, yes. I had one of the most frightening experiences of my life there. I - after the - the children worked until nine and - seven to nine were our hours and afterwards instead of carrying a whole lot of books home I quite
 
often stayed and did marking for another hour after they had gone to save me carrying so much you see. And the caretaker, who was very interested and very good with us, came up one night, he said, Miss White I do not like you staying here by yourself, he 
s
aid, you know you're up - it was a three storey again and I was on the top floor, he said, anybody could come in and murder you. So, I said, well - they'd get something before they get up to that stage. He said, well, I've brought a bell. If ever you're i
n
 any difficulty ring this bell, and he lived on the - in a cottage you see in the - playground, and, he said, I'll be up straight away. So I just laughed, I said, oh all right, if that'll soothe you, if that'll comfort you. And one night, naturally I didn
't keep the whole school lighted you see, just the room in which I was working and it was a classroom, had the one light on and - I think you get sort of feelings }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 sometimes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  that there's something not just as it ought to be. I was sitting in the desk with the books all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 strewn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 round me and I turned round and there was a glass door there and there was a man peering in. So I went to the door, what is it you want? You know, just dealt with him. Oh he was - he was wanting money. So I said, well, you've come }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  the
 wrong place but, I said, if you go downstairs the headmaster may be there - I knew perfectly well there wasn't another soul on the place but me - and he may be able to help you but, I said, I never carry money, I don't live far away and I don't need any 
m
oney. Oh well, I'd like to come in. I said, well I'm sorry you can't. It's a school, private property. And then he started forcing his way in so of course I picked up my bell and rang the bell for dear life, I heard the - the caretaker racing up the steps
 and he passed this man and didn't - didn't stop, he wanted to see whether I was all right. So we lost our - our - but I never had any other experience but - I can see that man now, peering through the - the glass door you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of pay did you get for your evening school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well it was better than the day school. Yes. It was so much an hour. And I think - but please I only think, it's a long way back to remember - I think it was five shillings an hour. But I can be hopelessly out. Which m
eant ten shillings for the evening you see. I think that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So that it would be quite a nice little supplement to your wages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, it was and - we were paid at the end of the first half and then again at the end of the second and that - the
 first half came at Christmas you see. So that it was really rather nice to have this because the - the day school money was nothing. And in those days my dear, we had to walk down to the Town hall to collect our money. And you can imagine what it looked 
like. All the teachers from all the different schools trooping down to the town hall to collect their five pounds for a months pay. But they were five golden }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 sovereigns}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 , they were - they were very lovely. But we were given little packets. You went into the 
room, you were given your packet and then you passed on and you - you signed for it. You know, it was a disgusting way to teach teachers - to treat teachers. But that was - it was - we were bank clerks as well as teachers because they - there was the scho
ol bank. The children had their books and - they - every Monday they could bring so much - bring what they liked and you had to enter it. I always resented that. Didn't - didn't see why we should - the school - why we should be bank clerks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Do you remember being involved in any war effort with the children at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes, we'd a tremendous one at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 Katherine\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  like that was in this last war you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I meant in the first war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 In the first - the first world war, no. No, I don't remember any there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you belong to the union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 The N.U.T.? Oh yes, all my life - all my teaching days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Any professional organisations as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Than the N.U.T. I can't remember what we called it, it was the - it was the West Riding Teachers 
- Association and we had a special name for it and I - I belonged to that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you take any active part in the union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. Yes, I was a very big worker. Yes. And - a big -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 In the early days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Particularly for the - charitable 
organisations, the - B and O. I worked hard for that. Yes. Every year I had a - either a - a garden party or a - a sale we made things, you know, amongst us but we raised a lot of money for B and O. Benevolent and Orphan Fund.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 This was when you were in Dewsbury was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes. And - well right a way through 'til the end o my time. I always was a - always. I contributed it to the B and O. As well as paying my subscription for the - the - for the N.U.T. Yes, I was secret - I was president of the N.U.T
. - local association, quite a few times. Used to go up to the annual conferences, I loved those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What was the relationship between the Dewsbury Authority and the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Very kindly, very interesting and very appreciative. We had our - when I
 was talking about my father I told you this, each member of the - of the board - the school board it was called - was allotted to a school and we loved to come, we - you know - we felt they really were interested and - we always knew that we should get a
 sympathetic hearing if there was anything special that we wanted, they would }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 Endeavour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 to get it for us, to get them - to see that we had the money allotted to us for it. They were never a bit interested in our salaries though. No. They thought we were well paid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would you say that starting full time work changed your attitude to life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I don't think so because you see I really started full time at fifteen when I went in as a pupil teacher. We worked full time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You continued to live at home when you first started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did starting work change your relationships there, either with your parents or with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, I don't think so excepting that I was at one of the older and you see of the family and 
although - looking back I wonder how in the world I ever had any pennies to spare - my younger brothers and sisters always knew that - there would be a few coppers for them. And of course that - that was especially so when; I had my night school because t
hen I had money that - I felt I could do as I liked with.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you continue to spend your Sundays the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Just the same. Yes. I was a Sunday school teacher. Had charge of the - the babies department and we had a cradle roll and the - the tiny t
ots, they were very lovely, would come along and say, we've got a new baby and his name is so and so and will you put - will you put her on the cradle roll? And I used to go round and see the parents of my - my kiddies you see and the - in the - Sunday sc
h
ool class and I remember going to one mother and she said, I've been in trouble. So I said, oh, what's the matter? Well, she said, so and so, mentioning my name said, somebody says we're going to have a new baby in this house, if we are Miss White ought t
o know and then it can go on the cradle roll and the baby wasn't do - for another month. It - it was to be on the cradle roll. They were very interested in the cradle roll. Yes, it was very happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And you still did the same sort of things in the evenings and so on and your spare time as you had done before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well there wasn't much spare time dear when I was teaching at night school, I was at night school four nights a week and I went to Wakefield another night for - classes. No, I think I was immer
sed in - in school - school life after I once came back from college.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about during the school holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well - I always went away for holidays and - being a big family, as we grew older we couldn't all have holidays together so - three or f
our of us went together and then stayed at home and took hold and looked after things generally while the next one went, usually there were three contingents for holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you make any new friends when you started to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well, yes, in the 
school there were teachers you see, well, some of them were new, some of them were old friends but some of them were new and we were always on very friendly terms in the - the teachers in the school. And - oh I had quite a lot of friends. I don't must kno
w now how I got - when they - going to concerts and things we used - used to meet with people. And I had some very lovely friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have some special friends about this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. Yes. Really special friends.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And your parents knew your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh yes, we were always - we were always really expected not just allowed, to take our friends home. My mother always kept open house for any of our friends. Both boys and girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did she expect to know where you were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. If
 we were going out we told where we were going. And if we deviated at all it was up to us as to whether we told her. I think one thing that they did that was really unfair. My eldest sister was - if she wasn't engaged she was - she knew to whom she was to
 
be engaged you see and - when they were going out one of us younger ones had to go with them. Well I think that's most unfair. And I thought so then. And I used to say, well, I'll meet you such and such a time, such and such time. We went out together and
 we came back together but we weren't together in between. But I think that was asking for deceit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were you ever subjected to any chaperoning of that kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. But I jolly well took good care that I got rid of them quickly. Oh yes, we were al
ways chaperoned. And - but I say we were expected to tell - well we really and truly think parents were seeking lies. They didn't think so themselves. They certainly put a great deal more faith in our probity than we ever deserved.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  in 1913?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How long had you known your husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well - he was a - he was a friend of my father's. A widower with two boys. And I myself had been through a - a very - dreadful time, I had been engaged an my fianc\'e9 was taken ill and - died just 
like that. And - this man was - he was twenty-one years older than me and at the time of my great trouble his wife was dying and that was really what - you know, both through sorrow at the time and three years later we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . With great opposition from the family. Understandably so. I would have - I would have opposed it for - for one of my girls. But - there it was. The day before we were 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  - I had gone to Leeds with him, that was where his home was and - he'd had a housekeeper who when he knew that he was going to be }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  - that he was going to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  again had walked out on him. So - the day before we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 I went to Leeds to the house to put in things in order as much as I can and I worked like a galley slave all day and the time we
nt and I got in home, I told my mother where I was going, but I confess I didn't there was so much to do, I didn't know it was going to take all that time. I got in home ten o'clock at night. I was twenty-nine - twenty-eight and my mother and my father me
t
 me as I walked into the house. And where have they been to this - to this time of the night? Any girl with any pride wouldn't be out with a man until that time of night. And that was at twenty-eight. Well - I wouldn't tell them what I'd been doing. I was
 too furious. That I just said to my mother, well - I've been out with him today, I shall sleep with him tomorrow night, so what about it? And I went off to bed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So you went into an existing home as it were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 The question of saving up to get }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, well you see, I'd been saving up before and I'd - in those days we all had bottom }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 drawers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  you now after we got interested in a man. So I had all my things that I had prepared for.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Your parents were opposed to the marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did they help you at all towards setting up home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did they come to the wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. But I didn't go home to the reception. No. I went straight away from the church, my husband and I went straight a
way by car to Leeds and then on to London, we were - we were going to London. No, I didn't go home. Never saw my wedding cake. Didn't even know there was one made, I mean the whole thing had been so unhappy that - no mention had been made of - of - of the
i
r being a wedding cake and I never did see it. I got a piece of it sent to me later. No, that's a - a part of my life that I don't recall, I let it go. It was a frightfully unhappy time. Because from being - very happy at home and - very close to my mothe
r
 and father I was a - an outcast. My father never sat down to a meal in the house with me from the day my husband I were engaged until we - until we left home. No. No. If I walked in and he were having a meal and he thought I was going to sit down he'd le
a
ving it and go out. I left home for a period but it seemed to me fantastic, I - I wasn't happy and I was causing a lot of unhappiness at home so I came back again. I wasn't away very long. No, it was a - it was an unhappy time. And I - I don't hold any - 
a
ny meal - I don't feel any malice about it or - I'm unhappy - I'm a - unhappy when I recall it but - I can understand parents not - not wanting their daughter to marry - but you see I'd lost the one love of my life and - I felt I was helping somebody who 
was - in need and there's no doubt about it, I did. 'Cos the - both the boys and their - and their father needed a woman in the house.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You say he was working for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 his}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  temperance as a lecturer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. The U.K.A. - United Kingdom Alliance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Had he always done that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
No. No. He was one of these who - this - this was a very big point that my father pointed out. He was not very interested in education. And - his father was a schoolmaster, headmaster in Halifax and - my husband just refused to st
ay on at school, he left - the others went through the grammar school you know, though it wasn't a grammar school in those days, but it doesn't matter it - it - it took the place of a grammar school. He left when he was fifteen and went into business. But
 - he hadn't a lot of interest in education but - he hadn't atom of a business man about him. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You mean he went into -?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Into a shop, to work in a shop - an ironmongers shop. And - I don't know how long he was there because that was a long ti
me before you see, that was - that was before I was born. And - then as - as time went on he wanted to start a business of his own and his father was all out for it, his father was - was very good in that he always wanted to do the best he could, all the 
others had a full training you see, so he - he funded him for a business. And - I always say, well I - I know my husband better than his father ever knew him. I wouldn't have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 funded}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  him for a - for anything, he was a - the world's worst where handling money was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 concerned}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  and he bank - and lost everything his father put in. and thin it was lecturing was his forte. He was absolutely splendid at it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 
And he of course was in the days of the open air meetings - I've seen him hold - hold a huge, huge audience in Dewsbury and Leeds, in London, in Manchester and he just had them there - the palm of his hand. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And - one thing we were always very proud of, at no time throughout the whole of his long career did he ever had to withdraw any statement he made. He was accurat
e - accurate to a degree. I did a bit of public speaking - well I've done a good deal in my day, but - not on his subject. But I was asked to - to speak at a British }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 Women\rquote s}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  meeting - a temperance association meeting and - I was - making my notes and so on
 and naturally I handed them on to him. Now I can't tell you the figures but I do know that in some thousands - some hundreds of thousands I was some shillings out and he pointed this out to me. That is not correct, I gave you the correct figures. He was 
accurate absolutely to the - to a degree. A man to be depended upon in things of that sort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And then when his health failed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well he just gave - gave up then. Packed up altogether. That was - it was a very sad thing because he'd seventeen years o
f it you see. He could still go to - to meetings but he couldn't speak. They still kept him on committees because he was a good committee man but - I had to warn them that he wasn't take any part in debates because he'd have a heart attack. No, it was sev
enteen very hard years for me but I think that it was harder for him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did he feel about your working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
I don't think he minded because he knew I was much happier at school than doing housework, I don't like housework. So - and - everybody kne
w I was happy. When we were going - my father gave me away and when we were going into the church, we just got up - there were three steps up and then there was the entry you know - and he stopped and looked at me, he said, now Mary, make up your mind not
 
to go through with this. He said, and I'll take you back home and I'll face the music. He said, you'll never be happy unless your teaching. And when my husband asked that we might be engaged then there was great opposition naturally - naturally - it was p
erfectly natural, I didn't - I didn't accept it so at the time but I do know it was - and my father just said, he said, she'll never be happy outside a school. Well I was back in a school within three years. And intermittently I kept in from then onwards.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Then your children started arriving didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And there were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Three.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When were they born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Dorothy in 1915. And Joan in 1917 and Mary in 1919.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were they born at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. All of them, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you know what to expect in childbirth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What did I expect?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you know what to expect?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I only knew it was a - it was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 damned}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  difficult time, I knew that but I didn't know anything else. No. People weren't taught about those things you know in our days at all. And - one - new in a very very vague indefinite way what marriage meant - what the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  life meant but a very vague way. You went - you went into marriage - they said - innocent, I say ignorant.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did you get on at the confinements?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
At the confinements? The first two were downright damnable. The next one was easier - the third one was easy. But the first one - neither the nurse nor the doctor thought that I should live through it. I had in the end - I'd - I'd - near
ly two days of - of labour and then in then end they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 chloroformed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 me and used the forceps and brought the baby. There were two doctors on the job and they held me - I - I didn't know of course, I was under chloroform, but I was so badly bruised they must h
ave held me terribly tightly by the shoulders and I just said to the nurse - the - the first two days I was - I wasn't here really and then I said, oh my back is painful, whatever is the reason? She was rather a blunt sort of person, well - she said, if y
o
u'd seen the way they had to hold you, one hold and the other drag to get the baby out, you wouldn't be surprised. But I was bruised right away down my back with the pressure. So the marvel is that I ever suffered another one isn't it? If I'd been sensibl
e
 I shouldn't have done. And with the second one, a fortnight before Jack was born the doctor - you know, they do think women are daft, they really do. And - I could tell from the look on my husband's face and from the very gentle way the doctor handled me
 
that he thought the baby was dead. I didn't feel the child for some time. And - I knew what they were thinking and - the night Jack was born he was a real howling - he was howling the - the roof off and the doctor - he was born, the doctor had been and th
en he said, oh he won't - the child won't be here for so many hours, and he went home to have his supper and had to be fetched back very quickly because the end of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 labor}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  came very quickly and the - the brain was yelling blue murder and as the doctor came in
to the room I said, he's rather noisy isn't he for a dead baby? And the doctor turned to the nurse, he said, what have you been telling her? I said, now nobody's told me anything, you told me it all. I said, I never knew a man so gentle as you were when y
o
u examined and, I said, your face told it you know. He said, nonsense. An experienced man like you, I said, well I know you think that we women are - are daft but, I said, we're not just as daft as you think. That was what they had thought you see. Howeve
r, he wasn't. A big strapping }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 bairn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. But born with a fear of the dark. From babyhood, right away from birth, as soon as you put the light out he started screaming. And we tried to check it but - I was - I was too ill to be - to have a screaming baby like th
at all the time and I said to nurse, put the light on. When I get stronger I'll deal with it, but I said, now all I want is a bit of peace. And as soon as you put the light on he stopped crying and he dropped off to sleep. But put it off, thinking that he
'd gone to sleep, and ooh - he was up screaming again. That lasted with for - quite two years. And I - I've no idea why. I don't know anything at all about it. It was a very strange thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How long were you in bed?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well - with Dorothy three week
s. And then I wasn't really fit to get up but - the nurse had to go to another case and I had to get up and - get going. And - with Jack, three weeks with him. But with Muriel, I think about a fortnight. Of course now they get them up and about within the
 week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was your husband involved at all at the time of the birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no. It wasn't done, no. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have any domestic help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes, I - I had - I had domestic help although I couldn't afford it. I couldn't afford to knock mys
elf up either. And although I - I'm very fit I don't seem to have a lot of - physical strength. I - I soon get tired.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did you feed your first baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Feed? Oh I - I fed them all by breast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you enjoy this or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were there any difficulties?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Only that - not being very fit - I - in those days it was all gruel you know to make the milk, we were fed on gruel. I didn't have a cup of tea until a week - until baby was a week old. I had gruel three times a day. I only did
 that with the first one. But I - I drunk oatmeal gruel galore. I should think gallons of it. Whether it did the trick or not I don't know but I fed - I fed Dorothy right through until she was ten months old. But - I couldn't satisfy Jack, he was a very b
i
g lusty boy and - although - there seemed to plenty of milk he cried night and day and the doctor at last, my own doctor, had - had to go to the war and you know we were handed on to another doctor in the area - this doctor came and he said, well you'd cr
y
 if you were hungry. So I said, but why is he hungry, I said, I have him weighed every week and he's putting on weight? Regularly, and I've plenty of milk. He said, he's putting on weight but he isn't - he isn't gaining strength and he's not being satisfi
ed, he said, wean him straight away. And that was at five months. And I weaned him and he went straight on to sterilized milk and I'd no more bother. He wasn't being satisfied.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 If the baby was asleep at feeding time would you waken it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 With - wit
h the first child, yes, not with the other two. The first child was brought up by the book, the other two were brought up on common sense.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 If the baby cried before the normal feeding time would you feed it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. Not with the first one, not the first one, no. Even - even up to minutes. I did what the book said.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What did you do if the baby didn't seem hungry at feeding time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well I never had that experience. They were - they were three hungry bairns.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How long did they go on feeding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well Dorothy until ten months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I mean at a time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh - now I've forgotten. I think it was half an hour but I real - I really forget.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When did you first give the baby solid food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I think Dorothy started at eight months. There was
 some - some special food that was - I think it was an Allenbury's that was recommended, it was semi-solid you know, it wasn't real solid. But Dorothy was on normal diet by twelve months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So her weaning was gradual?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 But John's was sudden was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Absolutely sudden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did the babies seem to mind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Didn't seem to mind at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 In neither instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No. Excepting that Jack and - I think boys are lazy you know - and - he - where as the girls had a cu
p of milk for their - when - this was when they were toddlers you know - they had a cup of milk for their supper and a biscuit and - Jack wouldn't have a cup of milk, he'd have a bottle. Want me bobble - bobble, mummy - bobble. And he went to bed until he
 
was two years old with a bottle. And he had a habit, when his bottle was empty, he was in the cot you see, when his bottle was empty he'd put his hand over and drop the bottle. And of course, bottles got broken that way. So I told him one time, I said, no
w
 the next bottle you break, Jack, is the last you'll have. I shan't buy another bottle for you. And - that was how he was broken off a bottle because he broke it and I - I wouldn't - wouldn't buy another one. I was thankful you know to be rid of bottles r
eally. And then he - he accepted it, he'd been told that - see - if he broke another bottle well that was the last.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 In those days did you think that it did any harm to a baby to let it cry or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well - I did, but the doctor told me that it was
 exercise for the lungs and I must let them cry. Well I let them cry if I felt there was anything to cry for. But I wouldn't let them cry just for the sake of crying. If there was something I could do to stop the crying - give them a sweet or distract the
re attention, I did. I can't see any joy in listening to a baby yelling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about punishing it when it was naughty, when it was still quite tiny?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How much did your husband have to do with them when they were babies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Very little. But - he was an excellent nurse, there was something comforting about his arms. I remember him coming in from a - he'd been out lecturing and it was late at night and I don't know why because Dorothy was a very good baby but she'd been re
stless the whole evening and nothing I did - it was in early days - nothing at all I did would soothe her or comfort her. And when - when her father came in he found her - a worn a woman, her mother, I - I was absolutely at the end of my teacher, I didn't
 
know which way to turn, and he just took the child from my arms and cuddled her in his and she dropped off to sleep. There was something - something about him that calmed the babies. But - that was all he would do, he'd take the child to relieve me, you k
now, now and again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would he ever bath them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh no. Oh no. No. No. Wouldn't even change a nappy my dear. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about attending to them in the night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh I always did that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would he take them out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When they got to the stage that they were able to walk. But not with a pram. He was too old you know. But when they got -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about coming out with you with the pram?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. He didn't like doing that either. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Of course he would be getting in pretty poor shape physically by then would he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes. Yes, he was, yes. Yes, I was back at - at work and Dorothy - Muriel was born in April 1919. Well I - I was then - as soon as I was able to get out I was doing supply work and I was back in full time teaching in February 
1922. That was when I came to Atherton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Now, the managing of the budget.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Enough said. When Dorothy was - she wasn't two - my - my husband couldn't manage money at all and wouldn't make me an allowance, you know, he'd give me - he'd give me a lit
tle bit and it - I'd to manage with it as long as I could and then ask for more and - that didn't go down with somebody' who'd been earning their own living. So I told - I told him - and it - in telling these things I'm always afraid that it looks as if -
 
life wasn't - it wasn't easy but it wasn't unhappy. I think I'm a pretty decided person and - I told him, I said, either I have an allowance or I'm going out to earn me. And he said well he would make one. He'd make me a regular allowance but it didn't la
s
t a fortnight, I got it one week and I didn't get it again, so I - without saying anything to him I applied for a post in - we were living in Leeds you see, I applied for a post and got one and advertised for a housekeeper and got one. And that was when I
 taught for five months in - in Leeds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you know how much your husband did earn?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. I do - I'd more than a vague idea. But - he was the world's worst at handling money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you discuss at all how the money should be spent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I tried.
 You couldn't get him to discuss money. Oh - he didn't discuss money. The housekeeper I got was a scream. She really was efficient. And she was a Mrs somebody and again I don't remember, you see I'm going back now to the 1915's - '15 - '16. I - I just - c
a
n't - can't remember any names. But I had to go to Hull to interview her and she - very nice she seemed and she hadn't - she came, settled in and she did very well indeed. The - looked after the baby well and everything but letters came and - I usually to
o
k the post in, the postman would ring and - I took them in and he was giving me some letters one morning and I said, well - those - that's not for me, we've nobody of that name in here. It was a Miss so and so, care of Mrs Hatch. And I - a voice from the 
r
oom said - may I know what name that is? So I told her. Oh yes, she said, I'm known by that name. So - I took it in and gave it to her and I said, and why? She said, well - I don't know what excuse she gave but it - it was a lame excuse she gave but her l
etters came on in that name, not in her - the name she'd given me as a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 name. Then one time she said her husband was - was on leave, could he come. Well of course he could come. So he came and stayed for the weekend and - somehow one had a feeling th
at things weren't straight. And - one night a policeman came to the door, asked if he could see my husband privately. So I brought him in and then John called me into the room and a light was seen from the window at the front of the house which was her be
d
room window and he said, we've seen it regularly, well my husband and I were very well known and - we were treated - very gently, there was no question of a case being made but the policeman had come to tell us about it. But I said, there - there can't be
 
a light anywhere. I said, that window at the front's completely blacked out. So he just said to my husband he said, well you come with me across the park, there was a park in front of our house, and there was a light - a beam of light shining straight fro
m
 the window. So they came back and I said, well I'll go upstairs. I said, she's gone to bed but that's her room. And I knocked and I could get no answer. Then I tried the door. And I couldn't open it and it wasn't locked because there wasn't a lock on. Bu
t
 she'd moved furniture against it and we couldn't open it. So I - I called to her, I said, will you open this door Mrs so and so, I still called her Mrs you see, and I said, it's very important. We've got the police here and they demand to see you. So she
 
put on her dressing gown and she had to move quite a big piece of furniture to get away and she came down and - oh yes, she swore black and blue there hadn't been a light but of course that was no good at all you see. So - after the policeman had gone he 
s
aid, well you - you will see to it Mrs Hatch? Well I said, so far as I knew I had seen to it, I said, the house - the - all the windows are thoroughly blacked but I talked it over with John, I said, I'm not running any risks like this. There's something w
r
ong. And I said, it's up to the police and the police said if ever she left us we were to let her - so I gave her a week's notice and - she moved to the other side of Leeds altogether and I lost touch with her, I had nothing more to do with her. But I alw
ays thought she was a German spy and that her husband was a German. But I hadn't suspected it before. It was a-
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 But as far as her housework and so on went she was quite satisfactory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh she was - yes - very satisfactory. She was a good cook and 
she looked well after the baby. I had help in the house to do the rough housework you see. No, it was a very worrying time. Because the blackout, in both world wars, was very strict.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have somebody else living in after her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. Yes. I got someone - almost straight away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have help continuously then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Both the living in and for the rough as well?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, for the rough and for the washing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of relationship were you on with your helps?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well they were friends. They - they didn't have meals with us but - we were on very friendly terms and I always found them very good workers but - one that I had had a strange - failing. She stole things. And she was such a nice girl, I would have trusted
 her with anything. But I kept missing things, packets of tea and - oh various things and - I asked her about them. No, she didn't know at all. And then I - again, I don't know, I think }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 
somethings}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  - it's instinctive - I went and looked under the mattress in
 her bed and there all the things she'd stolen were stowed under the mattress of her bed. I didn't say anything to her, I took them and put them back and she never said anything to me but when anything was missing in future I just went up to her bedroom -
 
and she was a grand girl. Kindness itself. Save me - Jack was a - a very difficult baby. We had a double fronted house and - so there was a bedroom on each side you see and I slept in one bedroom, this bedroom this side one week and the next bedroom the o
t
her so that the people on - on each side of us should have a - a week's rest from his yelling at night. And - she - she would be - she'd come into the bedroom five o'clock in the morning and say, I know you've had no rest, m'm - I'll take him downstairs a
n
d you got to sleep now. And - about half past seven to eight she'd bring me a cup of tea and bring back you see because then she was going to get breakfast ready. There was nothing too much trouble for that girl. But the crisis came when on one occasion I
 
had been to the bank with the pram to draw out a fair amount of money, I'd about thirty pounds in the - I was going to pay some bills. And - I knew it was a - I don't know whether you know much about prams but there's a well in the middle of some prams fo
r
 - I put the money in that well and the lid you see over the top and there were two children in, one was a baby - quite little and - the other one sitting at the other end and I lifted them out and I called - to - the girl to come and give me a hand, I'd 
g
ot the pram in the hall and I don't know, she took one of them and I took the other and - while she settled them and them when - when I got them - the children all right I went to get the money out and there was no money there. So - I said, now Gladys, th
e
re was money in this well when we came in. You and the two children and myself are the only people in the house. So - it's between us, we know the children couldn't have touched it. I know I haven't. Well, she said, I haven't m'm. So I said, well - I'll j
ust have to ring the police, that's all. I said, they'll have to find out and - she said, just wait a minute. I'll go and see, perhaps I lifted it out with baby. And she brought it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 back}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 , to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And did she have to go then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No. I talked to Joh
n, my husband, when he came home and he said, well mother you know it's been going on now for a couple of years and he said, you won't have money like that, it was just some special bills I was paying so he said, He said, you please yourself. So I said, w
e
ll I don't want to lose her. 'Cos she was splendid in the house - an excellent worker, an excellent cook and such a good friend. It was very strange. I don't remember - oh yes I do - I lost some silk stocking and in those days silk stockings were silk sto
ckings and they were a present that I'd had, I couldn't afford silk stockings but I - I'd had some sent. But they were under her bed. I got them back. It just seemed to be a kink with her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 This was in Leeds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, that was in London. It was in Lon
don. We'd had her when we were living at Heaton Moor. We went from Leeds to Manchester you see and we lived at Heaton Moor and I got her there. She came from - from the potteries. She was a - her family were miners, she'd a big number of brothers and they
 were all miners and her father was a miner. And she went with me to London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Which place did you live at longest up to 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well Leeds and London were pretty much the same. And - you see it was 1922 we went to Atherton. And Leeds we - we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  in 1913 and left it in 19 - we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  in the August of 1913 and we left it - early - in 1917. And we went to Leeds - to London from there in 1918. We weren't very long in Heaton Moor. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 
1918 and we were there 'til 1922. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So Leeds and London were pretty much the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Then I'll asking the questions about the community relating to Leeds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 To Leeds? Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When you were first }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 and living at Leeds you moved into this house that your husband already had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Presumably you stayed in that one house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of a house was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Three bedrooms. Sitting room and a dining kitchen and a big cellar kitchen. And lovely garden, nice garden at the back and just a small garden at the front. 
And it was in - Crossrites Avenue which was an avenue with nice - middle class people in it. And the park was straight opposite our house so that I simply could go across and into this park with the - well, Dorothy was the only one I had there you see. Th
e boys went to school in the morning, they were still at - they were still schoolboys you see when we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of terms were you on with the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Splendid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 They accepted your quite naturally did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. I was -
 their father asked them what they would like to call me, you see, I told them I said, it's what the boys want that matters. And I was mother from the beginning. They'd really never known their own mother. She had been dead three years when we were }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. And she'd been an invalid in bed - with the T.B. for two years - three years before that. So they - they'd never known what it was to have a mother really. So - yes, they accepted me. I - I had the younger of the boys and his wife - where are they now, 
Friday, Wednesday they were here for the day. They live - they live in Cheshire. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 Bramhall}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. And they come over quite often to see me. The other one lives in - in Essex and when I go to London we always meet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was there anybody else living in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have any living in help then or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. Not until after }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 Dorothy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  was born. Not at first. I used to have a woman in for washing and for cleaning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you do any making and mending of clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. I made - made - shirts, sleeping suits, pyjama sets you know and - I made all Dorothy's things, everything including her bonnets.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You'd buy some clothes wouldn't you, you'd buy clothes for yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, well I was very well stocked with clothes when I went and I
 - we didn't have to buy any for a long time. My husband, of course, had to buy his suits and the boys suits we bought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have a special place to go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 There was one place in - in Leeds that I went to but I can't tell you the name, I coul
d take you to it but I can't tell you the name. I - my brother lived in Leeds and - I knew Lees shops, from Dewsbury we used to come to Lees to shop, it was the - the nearest big town you know for shops that I knew the Leeds shops and - I go to in touch w
ith this shop that I liked the look of and bought the boys suits there. But I made their shirts.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about shoes, would they be bought in Leeds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Your husband didn't do anything with the children, did he do anything in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh no. My dear, your back in the early 1900's and men didn't in those days. Mind, when his health failed and he had to be at home and I was out all day he would help me with the washing up then. Yes. But that was - lot later you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were the boys old enough to do anything in the house to help you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
They'd help with the washing up. And they cleaned their own shoes. I'd done my whack of shoe cleaning having five brothers - six brothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about Dorothy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well whilst we were at Le
eds you know, we left Leeds - she was born in '15 and we left in '17 so she wasn't old enough to do anything. And she was a very forward child and she was passionately, passionately fond of her older brother, the eldest - the older of the two step-sons. A
n
d he started work before we left Lees and - he - she always watched for him coming home. And she called him, she couldn't say Percy, she called him Perc-perc. He was Perc-perce for a long time and when he came home on Saturday she always ran down the path
,
 you see, when he came home during the week it was too late, she was getting ready for bed when he got it but on Saturday he came home at dinner time and she always ran down the path to see him and - I can hear her excited little voice now, mummy, mummy, 
P
erc-perc coming, and off she went down the path and then he took her by the hand and took her to the sweet shop and bought chocolate for her. That was a - every Saturday. And he had to join up. In 1915 she was born - 1916 - I think it was 1916 he joined u
p. I don't know it was late 1916 or early 1917 but it was while we were still at Leeds. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 
And the boys had always lived a very sheltered life and when he was going into the forces I said to his father, you must have a good talk with that boy, he doesn't know 
life, he doesn't know what - what's before him when he goes into the forces and it's our duty to see that he's prepared, we don't want him to go and get - into bad company and - do something that he'd regret. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So, I said, you must have a good talk with him.
 And the time went on and - I said, you know, there's only another day John. That boy goes tomorrow. So I said, I'll go off to bed early and take Dorothy off I can read in bed. So after tea, he said, I'm going to bed early mother and I'm going to take - I
'
m going to read in bed. So I said, well of course I know what that means. And I said, you know that's most unfair. It ought to be his father. Not his mother. And particular not his step-mother. Oh well, he says, I can't do it, you do it. So - they're all 
g
one off to bed and Percy and I were sitting talking and - we had a real heart to heart talk and I pointed out to him the dangers of being amongst men with very different ideas from what he had ever known and - told him - I'd already told the boys - the fa
c
ts of life as we say. Anyway I'd had a talk to them on sex when they were younger. And - he said, you know mother, the men at work talk about these things. And he said that they say that sexual intercourse is necessary, that a man needs it. So I said, wel
l Percy, if a man needs it he's got to find a girl for it. Now I said, supposing when Dorothy gets }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 up to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 the age where she could be attractive to a man and the man spoiled her, what about it. He said, I'd kill him mother. So I said, yes Percy, and all these
 girls who are being ruined are somebody's sister, somebody's daughter. And he said, him, I never thought of that. I says, well think about it. But I'll always remember that. I'll kill him mother. And - oh we talked into the early hours of the morning. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 But my husband was a very, very ,very, very reserved man. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
I don't think he could have talked to anybody and certainly when he couldn't talk to his own son, he couldn't could he.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And yet he could do public speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes, that was a different m
atter you see. That wasn't intimate. But in lots of ways, my dear, you haven't had - with your father being - going out of your life early, you haven't had a man to handle but on the whole they're cowards. When it - when it comes to a real difficulty. Tha
t
's my experience and that's speaking with six brothers and three sons and a husband to say nothing of lost of other men folk who I know. I still feel if it comes to a real - stiff point - the majority of men are cowards. I have known men who were not at a
ll. But that is my feeling about the majority of men. If it's something really difficult they'll back out if they can find somebody to do it for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How old was the younger boy round about that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Wilf was twelve when we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 , that w
as 19 -s 13 and this we're speaking of four years later, he would be sixteen you see and Percy was eighteen. That was why for - you see - conscription came in they had to join up. We could have got exemption for him because he was in engineering works, bu
t he wouldn't have it. He said, no, it was the - he considered it the duty of men to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So they weren't really children then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
, no. No. No, they were twelve and fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When your own children were youngish, what was their bed time, did you stipulate a bed time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well - until they were five they went to bed at - at half past six. I used to take the - my husband, you see, that was during London days. My husband was in the city and - the children had their tea at half
 past four and then a game. Then I bathed them, they had their - they went into bed and I either told them a story or read a story to them and - then they had their supper which was glass of milk and a biscuit or bun, something of that sort you see. Then 
they all trotted off to the bathroom and did their teeth and then they were settled in bed by the time their daddy came home. And - and then he and I had tea together. When he came in.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Obviously bathing facilities were much better?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes, in - in my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 days than they had been in my un}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  - oh yes, yes. Yes, the children always had a bath every day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Although you had somebody to help with the children this person wasn't really responsible was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did you feel 
about the things that you ought to do you're your children in the way of showing affection or ensuring their safety or supervising, ensuring that their food was adequate and of the right kind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well I had to do - I had to do all tat all the way throug
h you see and - when we - when we were living in Atherton - the - although Muriel was only three, I took her to school with me, that was after I'd got a house, the first - the first time, of course we got to '22 now you know. Do want that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I think we'd better stick to Dorothy because otherwise we're going to get out of the period aren't we?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes. Yes, that's what I feel you see. And - Atherton is out of the period. Yes. Yes, well - 1918 Dorothy then would be five. No she wasn't. She was born 'til 1915.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Let's just deal with Dorothy then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes, all right. Well she didn't go to school 'til she was six but - she could read and she could write when she went and I don't know how she learnt to read. Excepting, that I always read a lot to them an
d - she would stand by my side and if I was reading and I'm sure she picked it up from - from watching. But - she's been a tremendous reader all her life and when she went to school, as I say, she could read. Writing it was because she said, mummy, how me
 how to write my name, show me how to write mummy and - I would write it down and then she would copy it and she was very quick, she took things in very quickly in deed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about discipline with your children, what was your line there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well I 
always found - that - I think I have a firm way with me and when I spoke they knew and they responded. Certainly it was so with Dorothy, certainly it was not so with Jack. Jack has taught me that from what - what he used to do as a baby and - just when he
 was toddling about - you know, rationing was on, he was awfully fond of sugar. I had a - a fitting like that, a bookcase at the top but it was covered with - there was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 escritoire}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  in the middle, there's cupboard below and in the cupboards I kept sugar a
nd he was - just - just a baby toddling about between two and three and - I always kept him in washing suits and I would put a - an overall on him to keep the suit clean for when we were going out you see. And I want into the dining room, I'd find him sea
t
ed, he manage - he learnt how to open the doors and I never knew how because they were locked but he'd open the door and he - he'd have the brown sugar on one side of him and the white sugar on the other and - and - I scolded him, told him he mustn't do i
t
 and he still went on doing it and then - I went in one time, he - he dug his hand into one and into the other - and ran out of the room and then when he'd finished it he came up to me and lifted up - he lifted up his little overall and he says, pank mumm
y
. I thought, well panming doesn't do you any good then. No, he says, pank mummy. Dorothy was a very reserved child. She didn't mix easily with other children. And she was terribly serious. Terribly so. And I took her to school and I knew quite well she wa
s
 quite up to the standard and I told the head when I - when I put her into school - I - I said, I want her just to go her own pace, I didn't want her pushing at all. And - and she'd come home in the evening. Mummy, I must do so and so and so and so. I sai
d
, and you mustn't. Oh but I must, teacher said we must. And it got so that she wasn't sleeping at night. And so I went to see the head, you see it was two teachers talking to one another, and I told her, oh dear, she said, you know Mrs Hatch, you just tel
l
 them the backward ones, you must do so and so and she said, it's always those who don't need to do it that worry. I said, well she's talking about the lessons in her - in the night. And so she said, all right, I'll put that right. So of course she told h
er that it wasn't meant for at all. But she was such a serious child. I never had that difficulty with Jack. But I did have one difficulty with him, I - we - it was in London. I had help in the house you see, Gladys had left to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  so it wasn't her, 
it would never have happened with her but I had a - an older woman in and she was one of the real old Victorians with a very strict sense of how much - how children should be brought up. She was a - an un}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 
Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  woman and I couldn't understand, Jack seemed
 - to be getting nervy. And he wouldn't let me out of his sight. When I went to school in the morning I had to slip out without him knowing and then sometimes I'd hear him crying after me and when I came in at night he'd come rushing up to me and throw hi
s arms round me and say, oh you're back safely mummy. I said, of course I'm back safely. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 
And then - we went away for a holiday and the girls were in - in one room, they had their own bed in the rooms I had taken but we had Jack in our bedroom in a single bed because he - he was restless at night and I had to get up a fair amount with him. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And this particular night, I'd been up and down and up and down and I said - I said to his dad, he's not awake you know, he's just talking in his sleep. And then, he gave a
 big cry and I jumped out of bed and ran to him, put my arms round him, I said, what's the matter. Oh mummy, he said, you are here? So I said, yes. Well, he said, I forget the woman's name, Miss so and so told me that one day they'd take you away from me 
a
nd put you in a box and bury you down in the ground. Of course that woman was out. And that was what had been worrying the child. He - he remembers it now. He said, I - I never - I never knew when you went out in the morning whether you'd come back alive.
 It was a - a wicked thing to do.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did your children tend to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 confide}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  their worries in you or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh yes, they always came and - they - he never told me you see, he never told me that. I think he was too terrified to speak of it really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you and your husband go out on your own when the children were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2562636\charrsid15878306 Yes, as long as we had somebody in the house the children were never, never left.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have your help to look after them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was there ever a time when you had to get somebody else in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. Always somebody that the children knew. And we always told them. That we were going out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you let your children join in a grown up conversation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 If they were all grown ups at the table they were allowed to - give their little bit. Oh yes, there was no restriction that way at all.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of things did you bring them up to consider important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did? Well - to be truthful. I always taught them the lessons from the Bible though we didn't alwa
ys take them to church I didn't take them to church until they were old enough to understand what they were doing. When they were playing games I expected them to play them fairly, no cheating.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did you expect them to behave towards you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Simply as mummy and dad - as mummy and child would. If you mean did I expect them to be very respectful, no. We were just pals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you tell the children that they should hit back if another child hurt them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I don't remember - I should have done if 
I'd ever thought it necessary. But I don't remember having that problem come - I just don't remember it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were there any children that you discouraged them from playing with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. When - when we were in Atherton specially so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 We're going a bit beyond there aren't we?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes, we are. But - you see - Dorothy - '22 - she was only seven when we left London and in London you don't let children go out and play on their own - we'd a big garden for them to play in. And - we did play with other
 children but it was when I took them out onto the common. The big }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 common}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
, and - I encouraged them then to play with the children who were playing about then because we always took balls and - so on you see. They'd throw them to other children and play with them but it was when I was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of punishments did you use?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well don't ask me what I did it for because - before I answered I was trying to think - I would - if they'd done anything that I thought called for punishment I would slap their arm but I don't remember to - ever there being much of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would you say that the children were influenced equally by you and their father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Not much by their father because he was a public man you see whist they were growing up and when
 - I tell you that Muriel was only three when his health failed and they - they now say we always had to be careful with daddy, we hadn't to upset him. 'Cos he was a heart case you see and - I kept him as quiet as possible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did you feel about leaving the children with somebody else while you went out to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I hated it. But it was necessary. So where was the good of making a - making a burden of it. It had got to be done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You know how some people think that children should be with the m
other all the time and others think that it's not necessary and it does them good to be with other people quite a lot as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What did you think at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well whilst they were tiny I thought they were definitely better with me a
nd - and their dad and of course there were the two older boys you see until Percy went - went away so that they'd quite their own circle. It was not until they got - considerably older that they went out and mixed with other children, as tiny children th
ey didn't. Fortunately always we had a garden for them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When they had a birthday how did you celebrate it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh we always made a - a real - day of the birthdays. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 
They - special tea and - candlelight, not electric light, we had candle light and of course a birthday cake that was decorated and was kept very, very strictly out of the way until it was brought on the table. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And - presents of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well that was a home day. And - the - the two boys never went to Lon
don with us, they were at work you see, but they always joined us for Christmas. They always came up for the holiday at Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have musical instruments in your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes, we - a piano. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were the children taught to play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes, they had lessons.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about singing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 They none of them are singers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did they used to have little sing-songs in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes, round the piano. Oh yes. They always had a - I used to have a - you see I had to put them
 to bed before their father came home and we'd have a hymn and a Bible reading or a Bible story or something of that sort before they went to bed at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you play games in the house with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. Hide the thimble was a - was the one
 that they were so very fond of. And of course we'd the snap and that sort of thing. Oh yes, there was always a period of the day when we had games and the children chose their own games.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You say you'd take the children out to play, were there any people that you'd take them to visit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Not in - in London definitely, yes, yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 
And - in - in Lees there - although Dorothy was a still a baby - they were - there were babies near you know, young mothers with their babies and we - we used to go with our 
prams into the park together and - as Dorothy got to be a toddler she would go - one person lived next door and had a little girl another one lived a few doors lower down the avenue and there was a little girl there and - we always took the children ourse
lves, and we'd play in their garden or we'd take them into the park together and play. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
And then in London there were two families there that had children and I used to take them to play there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you take them shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh I had to, they always went shopping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Nothing special - except stay at home, away from the crowds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did you spend Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well - the morning I always had a - a baking day for the weekend, baking morning. And then the afternoon - if the
ir dad was free and at home - we'd all of us go onto the common and he would play games - ball games with them. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 
He was very, very keen that Jack should be a good cricketer and footballer although he was just a - a little podge so - but his dad showed him how to hold a bat and how to kick a football how to bowl a ball, right away from babyhood he was taught that.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Sunday we went to service. I never took the children as tiny children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Special clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I don't think so. No. The children always had washing - washing dresses, washing suits you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you think it was wrong to work or enjoy yourself on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I did not. Before - before ever I was grown up I - I kicked against that at home. And - my father, who was 
very broadminded, said, for heavens sake, if she wants to knit or crochet let her, at least she's quiet then, but - I - on the whole the family didn't approve. My mother certainly didn't approve and my older sisters thought I was a wicked person but - you
 know, they came to it in time and did it themselves, it helped the day through.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you let your children play games on Sunday?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Definitely. Yes. Either inside or outside.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you continue in a Congregational church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Until after my husband's death. And then I went back to the church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did he come to church as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Sometimes, but usually he was taking meetings on Sunday. You see, the temperance people held their own Sunday meetings. They were religious meetings but the sermon was on temperance and it was - he was very seldom at home on Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were you involved in the temperance thing at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, I belonged to the White Ribboners and - I - was on the committee of the - what did they call them - I've forgotten it all now. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 Women\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  Temperance Association. We held meetings and raised money and sort forth and I helped with that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you belong to any clubs organized by the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. Not after I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. Before I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  I was in charge of the t
eachers training class, I used to take a teachers training class every week, a weeknight. We prepared the lesson for the coming Sunday you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How old would the children be before they started going to church or Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 They never went t
o Sunday school at all. No, no. No, my husband had a strong objection to Sunday school 'cos he said people were not trained and - he didn't think children - he thought the - the home was the place to train them in the Bible knowledge, but they went to - t
o church from being about five. And if I thought the service was too long I brought them out half way through. I don't think children ought to be bored by - church service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have grace at meals in your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Who was it who said it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 My husband. If he were either, if not I did it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 On Sunday morning. Other times we were all - you - this is my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  life? Yes. Other times - my husband would be out late at night and he didn't have his breakfast until the boys had gone to school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You were interested in politics always?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about your husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Not very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was he the same party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. Yes, we were both strong Liberals but - he registered his v
ote and - I liked going and helping at the - committee rooms and - belonging to the party.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And of course you would vote wouldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh rather. In the last two elections I was at - still at the Bay you see when those last two elections were fou
ght and - I worked all day long. Canvassing and so forth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did you and your husband spend your leisure time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 He is very musical and - we went to - being in Leeds of course it's a musical city you see and we went to musical concerts. And - in 
those days - the - Roundhay Park was noted for the bands that played there so many days a week and he liked to; go to that. He was not a walker I missed that very much. He always preferred to ride to walking. But - he would go in the evening, he knew I wa
s
 fond of walking, he knew I was missing it and in the evening he would go for, what he called a long walk, what I called a short one. He was a keen follower of Yorkshire and was a - Yorkshire cricket - and was a member and we used to go to the matches the
r
e. And of course we had to take it in turn - he always went and one of the boys with him, see you can take one person with you when you're a member, and if I could fit it in I would go sometimes and it was in the early days of flying and I saw my first ae
roplane in Ro}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
ndhay Park and - the man was doing acrobats and did a - turn over and I was so upset and so sick at seeing this - this plane turn over, I was sure the man was going to fall out you see, that I - just said, I said, well I can't see any more, I'
ll meet you so and so and I went. I went, I couldn't stand it at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did either of you take part in any sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 My husband did in early days but of course he was - his health wouldn't allow, and his age wouldn't allow. And the only sport I took 
part in was I played tennis. But not after I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . That was before I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was he out in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 A lot. Oh his work. Yes. You see, he had to collect subscriptions and so on and it was in the evenings that had to be done beca
use in the daytime folk were out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you belong to any savings schemes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 For sickness or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. Excepting I did with the B. and O., you see, the N.U.T. and I kept that on. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you go to theatres as well as to the concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh loved it if - if we could get a chance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What was your attitude towards the cinema?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I wasn't very keen. I don't think my husband was either. A con - a good concert or a good theatre and he loved the music hall. I hate
d it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you go with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh yes. Yes. Who was it we went to see? I called for a - a - a common - oh I can't remember her name, in - she's been on the - at least - records of her been on. The name will come but I can't remember it now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have any hobbies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
No, I'd - my hobby was making clothes. And mending. No time for any hobbies. Though we used to play cards if you call that a hobby. When we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  there wasn't a pack of cards in the house and of course I'd come from a ho
me where we'd always had a hand of whist or - bridge you see and - sometimes I'd - I'd feel a bit lost just what to do with these two older boys and quite early in our }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  life I said to the boys, well, where are the cards? They'd never seen a pack of 
cards. And my husband, to my amazement, thought cards were wrong. So I said, don't be so silly, I said, where's the harm in cards more than in your - we had a - a half size billiard table - more than - than billiards. I said, I don't see it. Well - he sai
d
, well billiards is a game of skill. I said, so are cards. And, you know, I - I wore the - opposition down and bought a pack of cards. But - I never - my husband loved to play a hand of whist but he never was much good. I always used to say, so long as da
d gets a - a couple of aces }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 hand}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  it doesn't matter if he's nothing, he's happy with a couple of aces.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about the garden, who saw to that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well I tried to but - you know, I had too much to do and I got a man in to come and every now an
d again to keep it tidy and Wilf, that's the younger of the two boys, was interested and - very spasmodically he'd have a turn in the garden. I cut the lawn. We had a lawnmower and quite a big lawn and I quite liked doing that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you ever have help from relatives, would you have any relatives in Leeds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Or friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 In looking after the house or family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. Excepting - once a fortnight, whilst Dorothy was still a baby - between feeds, if I'd anybody to 
look after her I could slip into town and have tea with my husband in town, his office was in Leeds you see and I had a very dear old friend, she was - oh, older than my mother but she was a good old soul and she used to say, now you bring her across as s
o
on as you've fed her, she lived quite opposite to me, and get the next bus down, trams they were, not buses and - you'll just have time to have a nice little jaunt round town, a cup of tea with your husband and then back again ready for her. And - once a 
fortnight I used to do that. It made a break for me you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were you ever ill yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh yes, I used - I used to have terribly bad throats and I'd very bad attacks of tonsillitis and they were bad, believe me, out completely. I had one in Leeds that was so bad the doctor - said it was not tonsillitis, it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 diphtheria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  and he was sending for the ambulance to send me away to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 diphtheria}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  hospital. I said, you're not you know. I said, you haven't taken a swab. You haven't had it tested. I'm not
 going. Oh but I must have you - you must - I said, I'm not going. And my husband - was very fond of this man, I loathed him, and my husband said, don't you think you'd better do as the doctor told you? I said, yes, I'll do as the doctor tells me when the
 
doctor's done his part. But I said, you take a swab. If it comes back positive I've no option. I knew it wouldn't come back positive, I'd had - I'd had tonsillitis too often. But it's a very nasty thing and it absolutely laid me low. This was quite early 
in time because it was before }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 Dorothy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 was born you see so the doctor fining that I was - I knew what I was talking about took the swab a-n it was negative, I knew it would be. And what was more I knew what to do for my - for myself. I was able to crawl out 
of bed, had I been at home you see my mother would have - well - got what I needed, but - there was nobody there to do it so I did it for myself. But I was a full week in bed and really very ill. I've never had anything much else. But always a week for it
.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have friends in Leeds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I made friends after I got there, I hadn't any when I went you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you share your husband's friends or did you make new ones of your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well he hadn't any friends in the immediate area when I went there so I - I made my own friends, by degrees you know. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 And they were all very - very helpful and forthcoming, we - it didn't take long though I don't believe in rushing those things but I had - oh in the avenue there were one, two, three, four famili
es with whom I was very, very friendly.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you visit each others homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 For a meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes. Yes, we'd go in, have tea you know. We didn't go in for - for lunches of course. But we'd have tea. And sometimes - in the evenin
g when Dorothy had got settled I'd just say, well I'm - I'll go down to Margaret or I'll go to Elizabeth for a - an hour or so and you know where I am if you - if I'm wanted. That was on an evening when my husband was in for the evening. But he didn't rea
l
ly like it only - I did feel that unless I was pretty firm I should have no life of my own. It would be merged in the family and I don't think that's good you know, I think you've got to - you've got to keep your own personality. So I would slip down or u
p, whichever it was I was going to, just for an hour. It made a break.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did your friends call in casually to see you in the same way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes, quite casually, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of things did you do with your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well they like me had a
 baby. And - we'd each of us be either knitting or - or - I'd take my knitting down with me you see and - what does a mother talk about? Her wonderful baby. And we compared notes. And of course our own baby was always the most wonderful. But seeing there 
were three of them we each of us thought our own was most wonderful and we didn't quarrel about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did the house belong to your husband?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, we rented it. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you see much of your landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, very little because the - the rent
 was sent by cheque. He would come, if there was anything that - wanted doing in the house or if he - I think he used to come once a year to see if there was anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 How did you feel about him as a landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh he was - he was a very good man,
 very good landlord. Never refused you anything reasonable. And we didn't need much, they were well built houses. The neighbourhood's gone down I - if I go to Leeds I slip up at have a look at the old house sometimes but the - the whole neighbourhood's go
ne downhill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of a community was it when you lived in it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 A very -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 As }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 compared}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  to what your Dewsbury community had been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well it was nicer - if you mean the people - well, they were pretty much same. But the actual district wa
s much nicer. You see, we were in the heart of the town in a business premises. These were all private houses and - I liked it very much. Big - big change from being I - a business house. We'd no garden at home you see, at my old home. But the - the peopl
e
 who lived in the avenue were all - very nice middle class people, very friendly. There was no snobbishness there. At least if there was I never met it. The - the man who lived two doors above us was a coal merchant and people don't believe me but unfortu
n
ately I can't prove it because I haven't got the bills now, they've been destroyed long ago - but for the very best coal I paid fifteen shillings a ton. Delivered. And - it was a coal cellar and they tipped it outside and - and put it down the - the grate
 and then swept up afterwards. Fifteen shillings a ton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were the social classes in that part of Leeds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Yes, the avenue in which we lived was the - the better class. Next to it was - their back and our back came - there was a road between - the Grove, that was not quite so - good class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of people lived there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well there were really living there people who worked in the mill. But you see, mill people were very thrifty folk. I quite expect they would be a good deal better off than us but they were not - not }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 especially}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  well educated. But I believe all of them, well no, I don't know, but quite a number of them would own their houses.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were the sort of relationships professional classes, mill owners, people of this kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 T
here weren't mill owners round us. They - they were - on the other side of the - park. On the other side of the park was really more - more working class than ours but there was a district on the far side of the park where mill owners did live, but the mi
ll owners you know of Leeds lived mostly in Headingly and - and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 Round hay}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. The other end - the other side of - of Leeds altogether. There weren't many wealthy folk round us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were the relationships between the different groups similar to the ones in Dewsbury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Quite the same. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about church going and so on, was that the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well it was - what shall I say - varied. There were some very very regular members of the church. Went - you know - like we had done in Dewsbury, every 
Sunday regardless. There were others who didn't go at all and then there were some who went now and again. Just like it was in most areas you know. The - the churches and chapels were certainly much better filled than they are now. There'd be good congreg
ations at any of the churches you went to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And would they be composed of the same sorts of people as had been in Dewsbury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 yes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . Yes. Pretty much the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were any of the mill families thought of as being rough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Some of them were very 
rough. But that was when you got - below the park, you're getting then towards the city and they were - rows of back to back cottage houses and they were spotlessly clean but they were rough cuts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Would some of the families be thought of as rough and some as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Being rough? Oh yes. Yes, yes, because some of them definitely were - they kept themselves in the - the old saying was, they kept themselves very much to themselves. And - they had - a refinement - that - wasn't an educated refin
ement bit it was, nevertheless, a refinement. They - they were very nice respectable people. But of course there were others who were - very course and rough. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 
Our doctor was - he was a - a very, very clever man. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I changed doctors by the by after this. I - 
I wouldn't have him near again. But - the doctor that we - that I went to was a - an exceptionally clever man. He passed all his exams as a doctor and - he was also a fully fledged - not lawyer, not solicitor - an - a barrister and a very interesting man 
a
nd - he - we - we became very good friends. He had three daughters and they were personal friends of mine and to - to get him talking about some of the cases were very funny. He - he said one man came one night, he'd been up at the house and it was some m
i
les out - up in the - up in the country and he'd been in his car to see a - a sick child and - it - about midnight and - the father came in about two o'clock in the morning, roused him up, could he - could he give him some - could he come. He said, there'
s
 nothing to come for, I was there a couple of hours ago and I know the child's all right. What - what's the - what's brought you here? Oh I don't think she is - I think - I think she wants you. Well he said, I'm not coming. So he said, well - if you won't
 
come will - will you give me some medicine. So he said, no. I never give medicine without knowing what I'm giving it for. But the man was so persistent that in the end he said, all right, I'll come. And - I'll come and see her. And - he took is car, took 
t
he man with him and he said, as he knew quite well, there was nothing that he said the man had got me up so, he said, I thought he should - he should be taught a lesson so he said, well you'll come back with me and get the medicine. He said, well won't th
e
 medicine do in the morning? So he said, no, you said, you - you said you must have it tonight so you come back. So he took him back, made the bottle of medicine and the man had this long walk back again. He said, you really do have to teach them a lesson
 
now and again. But to go down to the doctors on a Friday was an - it was a - a real education. His - I - I used to go down to see the girls and his wife would be carrying in little packets, there was a blue one and a white one. She said, I'm just packing 
t
he doctor up ready to go to - to his old folk. She said, Friday morning's the visiting morning and the delivery morning so I said, what are you talking about? She said, tea, sugar for each of his - old patients today and every Friday he went round to thes
e old folk and took them a little packet of tea and a little packet of sugar.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So he really was on close terms with his patients?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh - yes. Yes. They worshipped him you know. But he - he hadn't a - he was never soft with anybody at all. My husban
d came in one day when Dorothy was - she'd be about six or seven months old and - it took an awful lot out of me, I took a long time to get really well again and the doctor had been in, he was - he came in as a friend you see and he said, what in the worl
d
 are you doing with yourself? So I said, why, what's the matter? He says, you know what's the matter. He said, who's looking after you? So I said, don't be silly. And, you know, left it at that. Well he went out and a little while afterwards my husband ca
m
e in, oh in such a state. So I said, whatever's the matter. He said, I've come in to see what's the matter with you. So I said, well I didn't know what you're telling about. He said, just seen Doctor Hawkyard and he says, he stopped me and told me that I 
w
as going the way to be - to become a widower again. When was I going to learn sense. So - I said, well don't ask me what it's about. Well he said, he's been to see you. I said, he's just been in, paid one of his friendly calls, that's all. But he met my h
usband down - and he thought my husband wasn't looking after me as he ought to you see so - you're going to be a widower. Oh it was - it was very - but that was Doctor Hawkyard you see. He'd - he never minded his words.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When you were first }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 and living at Leeds did you have a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh very hard struggle. Yes, very hard struggle. Because money slipped through my - my husband's fingers. I went in - one time - and - I knew he was - he was going away. Going away for a - a 
week's mission or something, I don't know, and - the cab was waiting so he said - I haven't got any money. So I said, you look well won't you, going away for a week and no money to go with. Why haven't you been to the bank and got some. Well I don't know 
w
hat excuse he made about that. Well he said, I know you've got some in your desk. I says, how do you know I've got some in my desk? My desk was supposed to be private. No it isn't. But - he was without money. And he'd found twenty pound in my desk and so 
h
e'd taken it. And he just couldn't help himself, you know, he never - never could keep money. I was say - I would say to him, I say, well if you'd a shilling today you know John you'd spend two to - before the day was out. Oh yes, it was a very big strugg
le. That was in the first case what made me go back to school you see. I just couldn't - I wasn't used to that sort of - of way of living. He'd had a very stiff time though with his wife all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 that time}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . And his - his salary wasn't such a big one. And - he could always live like a lord.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So you really did have to manage the purse strings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh well once I got to school it - I had all the money. It never was - I never handed any of my money to him. Not to - I - I don't mean I wouldn't have - I wouldn't 
give him some. Because I had to do that in the latter years but to hand over my money and expect some to be paid back, not on your life. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3028758\charrsid15878306 After}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  all you do learn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3028758\charrsid15878306 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  don't you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 It's a different thing when you've earnt in your own right isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh y
es, it's your own money then. Yes, yes, it's your own money. No. No, money was - money was his weakness absolutely. He'd be away from home - I'd get a telegram, send ten pounds, I've spent all - and I used to say }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3028758\charrsid15878306 where}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  in the world do you think I'm going to get ten pounds from. No, money was always a - a difficulty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were you able to keep good humoured about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 I think so. Yes, I think so. I'm not going to say I didn't ever - tell him off you know. But I - I think the way of telling him off would
 be, to say, well you know how much money I earn John, and it's gone on the house. We never had any - any quarrels about it, if that's what you mean, at all. But of course, as I say, I - I learnt my lesson. And what money I had I kept. But - it was spent 
on the house. And I gave him as good }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 a time}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 as it was possible to - to give. We lived in a hilly district and he couldn't manage the hills and there was a farmer in the area who had a little car and he would run it for the cost of the petrol plus a little m
ore you see and my husband had that whenever he wanted it. To save him the - the strain of walking up hills you see. No, I - I think he would be the first one to say that - I played my side quite generously. I think I did, I hope I did anyway. Well I hope
 I did. It - it's so easy to think something you know and then find that you're hopelessly wrong.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Where were the meals eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 We had a kitchen dining room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Were there ever any }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3028758\charrsid15878306 occasions}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  when you might have eaten somewhere }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3028758\charrsid15878306 else}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Where did you cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
In the - partly in the kitchen dining room, it was one of those big old fashioned kitcheners you know. And then I had a gas oven in the scullery which was - off from there. That was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 
separate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 - part.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What time did you have breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
From half past seven 'til eight because the - whilst the boys - well, even when they went out to work because they had to get out you see, they - they'd quite a - a good long walk to school. They had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3028758\charrsid15878306 only}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  to go on the bus or the - the - i
t was a bus or tram, I think it - tram - but they quite often preferred to save the money and walk and - we'd no objection to that you know. If it were wet they were expected to go on the tram then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 You were all present for breakfast at that time then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. My husband didn't - he always said he preferred the streets to be - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 
warmed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 ; before he - and he'd no set hours you see. So either I gave him his breakfast in bed, really and truly to get it over with. 'Cos really if you was to set a second break
fast you know it's a nuisance. Or - if for some reason I didn't want to take it up then he would have his after nine o'clock, after the boys had got off. But that wasn't usual. I usually took it up and then he could get up when he liked and I was free to 
get on and get my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 chores}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of a meal was your breakfast?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Always porridge and then something cooked - boiled eggs or - or scrambled eggs or bacon and egg.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And to drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about the midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well the
 boys were at school. It was a school meal. It was too far to come home excepting on very rare occasions and then for some reason or another they would come back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you pack them a meal up to take?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, they had a meal at school. There was a - they - it was provided but it wasn't meals like they get nowadays you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was it customary in the schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 To those who had any distance to go and I'm saying that they - I think really - when it - it's just come back in looking aback - I think
 really they came home for dinner more often than they stayed because they were not very keen and they could get the - the tram from just by the school up to the bottom of the avenue and then I had - it was on the table ready for them when they came in yo
u see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What sort of a meal }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 you had}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh the usual Yorkshire meal you know. Two vegetables and a roast or - some other meat to take the place of the roast and always a pudding afterwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have a cooked meal in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. No
t if they'd had one. If they hadn't had one - if they hadn't come home and had a proper cooked meal then that I could cook in the evening for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about your husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well - quite often he would work, he had a study in the house and quite 
often he would work there for the morning and have a meal and then go out for the afternoon, and I didn't see him 'til bedtime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 So that your midday meal was really dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Yes, it was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And your evening meal was tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Was high tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have any supper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
If the boys wanted they - they could have a cup of cocoa, cocoa was a fovourite drink with them but there was no definite set supper. We - we had - cocoa, hot milk, few sandwiches if they wanted them, biscuits, cake, you kn
ow, just whatever they wanted, but there was no definite set meal at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have any special menu on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, only - again, be two vegetables and a roast and the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 Yorkshire}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  pudding and then a meal - a pudding of some kind to follow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have time to make bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Oh yes, I made - yes, I made bread and cakes and scones, in fact all the baking I did after I'd had the - the - the instruction. And I - I told you the first bread I made. I - I couldn't break it with a hammer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you do any jamming?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. Yes, I did a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you bottle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you do anything with medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No. My husband did. Yes. His father and mother had been - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 homeopathic}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  but I knew nothing about it and I just asked him
 well if you know what it - what to get and take do so, but I'm not going to bother learning it, I'm not - I'm not interested. But - his mother and father had been very keen and all their medicines were homeopathic medicines.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did he prepare things or get things for the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well not after I went there. The boys were neither of them very strong and - they had emulsions and cold liver oil and things and that sort to build them up you know, but I - I had to see to that naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Fruit and vegetables, would the be grown or bought?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Bought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And what about tinned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well tinned things you know, we used very little in those days. We bought fresh fruit and - the boys had lots of fresh fruit and - I cooked apples and, you know, the so
rt of general fruits that you so. No, tinned - tinned fruit was one of those things that you had on very rare occasions.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, I don't remember using it at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you ever have a smaller portion of a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 favorite}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  dish so that the others could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes. I - I found - we - I told you, we hadn't a great deal of money you know to work on and - I suddenly found after I was }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  that I had no liking for bacon. It was a very convenient find. As a matter of fact I did like it but I - it gave the three }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 men folk}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
 more bacon if mother didn't have it, so mother didn't have it. All - all mothers you know on - on limited incomes, did that sort of thing. It was a case of you held off when - when it was expensive food, bu
t of course food wasn't expensive in those days you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you ever actually go short?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well if I did I didn't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did your husband have bigger helpings or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 No, the three - you see the two boys were growing boys, they were twelve and fourteen when we were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid143632 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
. Well - they needed the best food and - and particularly so as they were not too strong. No, mother was the one who had the small helpings. It was just taken for granted. I mean, I never felt that I was a martyr at all. It was just taken for granted.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What about the atmosphere at the meal table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well just - just friendly happy chatty family - there was no - no feeling of restriction. I had come from a family of then you know and - you couldn't have kept ten children quiet if you'd wanted to unfortunately my mother and father didn't
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What was your attitude if the boys didn't care for some of the food that was prepared and left it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well - if they - if they knew what they - what they didn't like they si
mply said they didn't like it and that was all right, they didn't have it. There was no compulsion to have it. But I didn't go and get something else to make up for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 And if you had enough did they have second helpings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Oh yes, if they wanted it. There was always enough for them to have second helpings if they wanted them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you have any restrictions about when they could leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well we all sat chatting when the meal was over and then usually was a case of mother would sa
y, well come along, I want this table clearing. And then the boys would help me you see with the clearing and the washing up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you always have the same places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Do you know, I don't remember. But I'm perfectly certain that - that if they wante
d to change they wouldn't have been any objection to them changing. Life's too short to make regulations like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you serve the meal or did your husband carve the meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 He did the carving. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 What order were they served in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 Served in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
? Oh we always served the boys first. Then I was served, and then daddy last you see. As he was - as he was carving.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When you had your own children when they were too small to feed themselves what arrangements were there for them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Well - 
they - we had a high - when they got to the stage where they were fed we had a high chair and the high chair was always put by me and I supervised their - their feeding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 When your children were young did you feel strongly about the right or wrong way of bringing them up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well I was a teacher you know. And you've always got a right and wrong if you're a teacher. But if you mean was I severe with them, no, I was strict, I wasn't severe. I think they had a very happy childhood myself. Think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13047860 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 Did you and your husband have the same ideas about bringing up the children?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14232424 MH  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 
Well he had different ideas for his two boys than I would have had but then it wasn't my place to interfere with that you see. I fell in with that and - well if he'd diffe
rent ideas about how I brought our three up, well he didn't say anything. The only difference came when they got older and the boys just refused to stay on at school. They left when they were fifteen or sixteen. And - they'd no interest in anything beyond
, they wanted to get to work. With my own three children, well there was just no question of it at all, I wanted them to go to the university and they all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3028758\charrsid15878306 went}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306 . Their father was very proud, the - my eldest daughter went to Somerville college and Jack went t
o - to Cambridge and Muriel went to London and he'd very great pride in it but he never would have done it himself only he left me to make the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12475850\charrsid15878306 decisions}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1770950\charrsid15878306  in that you see.
